WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.820 --> 00:00:02.176
- [Narrator] A single empire in Europe

00:00:02.176 --> 00:00:03.477
would take over a quarter

00:00:03.477 --> 00:00:06.113
of the planet's land and population.

00:00:06.113 --> 00:00:08.849
(dramatic music)

00:00:08.849 --> 00:00:11.685
The foundations began on the lands of England

00:00:11.685 --> 00:00:14.054
with a powerful British monarchy igniting

00:00:14.054 --> 00:00:18.826
an extraordinary story of exploration and world domination.

00:00:18.826 --> 00:00:21.529
The British Empire saw the greatest stories

00:00:21.529 --> 00:00:23.831
of human achievement and triumph,

00:00:23.831 --> 00:00:25.433
(dramatic music)

00:00:25.433 --> 00:00:28.769
but also saw the worst sides of humanity.

00:00:28.769 --> 00:00:32.440
After the discovery of America around 500 years ago,

00:00:32.440 --> 00:00:34.675
they ventured out into the oceans.

00:00:34.675 --> 00:00:37.778
The British would encounter unknown civilizations,

00:00:37.778 --> 00:00:41.048
creating historic partnerships and rivalries.

00:00:41.048 --> 00:00:42.650
Within four centuries,

00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:45.953
the empire would be worth over $600 billion.

00:00:47.121 --> 00:00:50.558
But how did an empire that owned parts of the Americas,

00:00:50.558 --> 00:00:53.661
Asia, Africa, and even Australia

00:00:53.661 --> 00:00:56.063
eventually come to an end?

00:00:56.063 --> 00:00:58.399
We must start from the beginning.

00:00:58.399 --> 00:01:01.135
(dramatic music)

00:01:06.907 --> 00:01:09.643
(dramatic music)

00:01:11.612 --> 00:01:14.548
Long before the knowledge of far-flung places,

00:01:14.548 --> 00:01:16.917
a man by the name of King Alfred the Great

00:01:16.917 --> 00:01:19.854
had to defend his small Anglo-Saxon kingdom

00:01:19.854 --> 00:01:22.223
from the invading Danish Vikings.

00:01:22.223 --> 00:01:25.292
In 878 AD, the Vikings under Guthrum

00:01:25.292 --> 00:01:27.027
launched a massive invasion

00:01:27.027 --> 00:01:28.796
and Alfred was forced to retreat

00:01:28.796 --> 00:01:30.698
to the marshlands of Somerset

00:01:30.698 --> 00:01:33.234
where he sought refuge on the Isle of Athelney.

00:01:33.234 --> 00:01:36.971
Alfred used this time to regroup and gather loyal followers.

00:01:36.971 --> 00:01:38.739
He formed a strong army,

00:01:38.739 --> 00:01:41.408
and in a decisive battle at Edington,

00:01:41.408 --> 00:01:43.677
he defeated the Viking leader Guthrum.

00:01:43.677 --> 00:01:47.014
The victory forced Guthrum to sign the Treaty of Wedmore,

00:01:47.014 --> 00:01:48.849
which established the Danelaw.

00:01:48.849 --> 00:01:50.784
A region of England where Viking ruled

00:01:50.784 --> 00:01:52.419
was officially recognized,

00:01:52.419 --> 00:01:53.821
but also secured peace

00:01:53.821 --> 00:01:56.724
between the Vikings and the Anglo-Saxons.

00:01:56.724 --> 00:01:58.359
He then began the process

00:01:58.359 --> 00:02:01.328
of unifying all of the Anglo-Saxon kingdom,

00:02:01.328 --> 00:02:04.031
which his grandson Athelstan would finish.

00:02:04.031 --> 00:02:08.068
In 924, when Athelstan ascended to the throne of Wessex,

00:02:08.068 --> 00:02:10.037
his rule faced opposition

00:02:10.037 --> 00:02:12.573
and challenges from rival claimants,

00:02:12.573 --> 00:02:15.142
particularly from the Viking-controlled areas

00:02:15.142 --> 00:02:17.177
of Northumbria and Mercia.

00:02:17.177 --> 00:02:18.712
Despite these obstacles,

00:02:18.712 --> 00:02:22.082
Athelstan proved to be a capable and determined leader.

00:02:22.082 --> 00:02:26.353
In 927 AD, Athelstan managed to conquer Northumbria

00:02:26.353 --> 00:02:29.056
and effectively unite England under his rule,

00:02:29.056 --> 00:02:32.726
which led Athelstan to be the first king of England.

00:02:34.862 --> 00:02:37.765
200 years later, that battleground would be set

00:02:37.765 --> 00:02:39.867
when English King Henry II

00:02:39.867 --> 00:02:42.236
wanted to expand his kingdom to Ireland.

00:02:42.236 --> 00:02:45.706
In the spring of 1171, King Henry II,

00:02:45.706 --> 00:02:48.676
accompanied by a retinue of knights and soldiers,

00:02:48.676 --> 00:02:51.445
sailed from England to Waterford, Ireland.

00:02:51.445 --> 00:02:52.746
Upon his arrival,

00:02:52.746 --> 00:02:55.316
he quickly set about asserting his authority,

00:02:55.316 --> 00:02:56.850
demanding the submission

00:02:56.850 --> 00:03:00.154
of various Irish kings and chieftains to his rule.

00:03:00.154 --> 00:03:01.522
Henry was determined

00:03:01.522 --> 00:03:04.158
to establish English control over Ireland,

00:03:04.158 --> 00:03:06.594
and firmly believed that the Irish kings

00:03:06.594 --> 00:03:08.529
should acknowledge his sovereignty.

00:03:08.529 --> 00:03:11.899
As news of King Henry's arrival spread across the island,

00:03:11.899 --> 00:03:14.702
reactions among the Irish leaders were mixed.

00:03:14.702 --> 00:03:18.005
However, when various Irish bishops and clergymen met

00:03:18.005 --> 00:03:20.674
at the Senate of Cashel in 1171,

00:03:20.674 --> 00:03:23.611
these religious leaders recognized Henry II

00:03:23.611 --> 00:03:26.013
as the sovereign ruler of Ireland,

00:03:26.013 --> 00:03:28.882
acknowledging his authority to rule the island,

00:03:28.882 --> 00:03:31.885
making Ireland the first colony of England,

00:03:31.885 --> 00:03:35.456
long before anyone knew they would be a global empire.

00:03:38.092 --> 00:03:41.428
Another hundred years later, in 1277,

00:03:41.428 --> 00:03:43.464
King Edward I of England wanted

00:03:43.464 --> 00:03:45.733
to bring Wales under his control

00:03:45.733 --> 00:03:47.835
and incorporate it into his kingdom.

00:03:47.835 --> 00:03:50.137
His desire to conquer Wales was driven

00:03:50.137 --> 00:03:54.208
by strategic, political, and territorial motivations.

00:03:54.208 --> 00:03:56.910
The journey towards the conquest of Wales began

00:03:56.910 --> 00:03:59.980
with the First Welsh War in 1277.

00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:03.784
Edward I launched a determined invasion into Gwynedd,

00:04:03.784 --> 00:04:07.521
the heartland of Welsh resistance, in North Wales.

00:04:07.521 --> 00:04:10.557
His forces clashed with the Welsh defenders.

00:04:10.557 --> 00:04:12.326
Though fierce and relentless,

00:04:12.326 --> 00:04:14.461
the Welsh were eventually defeated,

00:04:14.461 --> 00:04:16.897
and their ruler, Prince Llywelyn, was compelled

00:04:16.897 --> 00:04:19.033
to submit to Edward's authority.

00:04:19.033 --> 00:04:21.402
Having established his dominance in Gwynedd,

00:04:21.402 --> 00:04:25.205
Edward I set out to solidify his control over Wales.

00:04:25.205 --> 00:04:28.208
He understood that military might alone not be enough

00:04:28.208 --> 00:04:30.844
to subdue the Welsh spirit of resistance,

00:04:30.844 --> 00:04:33.781
so he devised a multi-pronged strategy.

00:04:33.781 --> 00:04:36.050
One of the critical components of his plan

00:04:36.050 --> 00:04:37.484
was to construct a network

00:04:37.484 --> 00:04:39.920
of imposing fortresses across Wales

00:04:39.920 --> 00:04:43.424
to maintain English dominance and keep the Welsh in check.

00:04:43.424 --> 00:04:45.559
Despite the initial show of force,

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:47.428
Welsh resistance persisted,

00:04:47.428 --> 00:04:50.898
and in 1282, a second conflict erupted

00:04:50.898 --> 00:04:53.100
known as the Second Welsh War.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.536
The war was fierce and hard-fought,

00:04:55.536 --> 00:04:58.005
but fate was not on the side of the Welsh.

00:04:58.005 --> 00:05:00.774
With the Welsh resistance largely quelled,

00:05:00.774 --> 00:05:03.944
Edward I swiftly solidified his conquest,

00:05:03.944 --> 00:05:07.014
making Wales part of the English kingdom.

00:05:07.014 --> 00:05:08.515
(dramatic music)

00:05:08.515 --> 00:05:11.051
England's war struggles aren't done yet.

00:05:11.051 --> 00:05:14.021
From 1337 to 1453,

00:05:14.021 --> 00:05:17.891
the Hundred Year War began with England and France.

00:05:17.891 --> 00:05:21.261
The everlasting conflict weakened both empires

00:05:21.261 --> 00:05:24.231
and kept England tied to their tiny island.

00:05:24.231 --> 00:05:26.166
Right after the Hundred Years' War,

00:05:26.166 --> 00:05:28.202
England was amid another war.

00:05:28.202 --> 00:05:31.238
This time it was between the House of Lancaster

00:05:31.238 --> 00:05:32.539
and the House of York

00:05:32.539 --> 00:05:34.708
in the infamous War of the Roses

00:05:34.708 --> 00:05:37.945
from 1455 to 1487.

00:05:37.945 --> 00:05:39.613
The Lancastrians won

00:05:39.613 --> 00:05:42.382
and King Henry VI was declared king.

00:05:42.382 --> 00:05:45.052
The rest of the world was starting to open up.

00:05:45.052 --> 00:05:48.655
Christopher Columbus sailed the ocean blue in 1492

00:05:48.655 --> 00:05:50.424
and landed in The Bahamas.

00:05:50.424 --> 00:05:52.126
After his initial landing,

00:05:52.126 --> 00:05:55.329
Columbus explored several other islands in the Caribbean,

00:05:55.329 --> 00:05:57.531
including Cuba and Hispaniola,

00:05:57.531 --> 00:06:00.601
now shared between the Dominican Republic and Haiti.

00:06:00.601 --> 00:06:02.202
He also explored the coasts

00:06:02.202 --> 00:06:04.705
of present-day Central and South America,

00:06:04.705 --> 00:06:06.940
including Venezuela and Panama.

00:06:08.175 --> 00:06:10.611
This discovery of a massive landmass

00:06:10.611 --> 00:06:11.812
led the British government

00:06:11.812 --> 00:06:14.181
to desire land on this new continent.

00:06:14.181 --> 00:06:16.984
When Italian Giovanni Caboto sought support

00:06:16.984 --> 00:06:20.521
from King Henry VII to explore this new continent

00:06:20.521 --> 00:06:22.956
and find a direct route to Asia,

00:06:22.956 --> 00:06:26.193
King Henry was intrigued and granted Caboto a patent

00:06:26.193 --> 00:06:28.061
which authorized him to explore

00:06:28.061 --> 00:06:32.065
and claim any lands he might discover for the English Crown.

00:06:32.065 --> 00:06:34.668
Giovanni changed his name to John Cabot

00:06:34.668 --> 00:06:36.136
and he was ready to go.

00:06:36.136 --> 00:06:40.440
In May 1497, Cabot set sail from Bristol, England,

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:43.076
in hopes to find a passageway to Asia.

00:06:43.076 --> 00:06:45.245
He led a crew of about 18 men

00:06:45.245 --> 00:06:47.581
aboard a small ship called the Matthew.

00:06:47.581 --> 00:06:50.751
Their journey across the Atlantic was challenging

00:06:50.751 --> 00:06:53.220
as they faced treacherous weather conditions

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:54.955
and unknown dangers.

00:06:54.955 --> 00:06:56.757
After several weeks at sea,

00:06:56.757 --> 00:07:01.762
on June 24th, 1497, Cabot and his crew finally spotted land.

00:07:01.895 --> 00:07:03.163
They had arrived somewhere

00:07:03.163 --> 00:07:05.566
along the eastern coast of North America

00:07:05.566 --> 00:07:10.103
in an area later named Newfoundland as it was newfound land.

00:07:10.103 --> 00:07:13.740
Cabot and his crew were greeted by an unfamiliar landscape

00:07:13.740 --> 00:07:16.043
and encountered indigenous peoples,

00:07:16.043 --> 00:07:18.312
likely the Beothuk or Mi'kmaw,

00:07:18.312 --> 00:07:21.248
who had lived in the region for thousands of years.

00:07:21.248 --> 00:07:23.383
Cabot claimed the land for England,

00:07:23.383 --> 00:07:25.452
planting the English flag on the shore

00:07:25.452 --> 00:07:28.655
and taking possession of the newly discovered territory.

00:07:28.655 --> 00:07:30.490
The exact duration of Cabot's stay

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:32.459
in the New World is uncertain,

00:07:32.459 --> 00:07:35.362
but it is believed that he explored the coastline briefly

00:07:35.362 --> 00:07:37.030
before returning to England,

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:40.701
arriving back in Bristol in August 1497,

00:07:40.701 --> 00:07:44.238
where he was celebrated as a hero for his achievements.

00:07:44.238 --> 00:07:47.207
Cabot's discovery spread quickly throughout Europe,

00:07:47.207 --> 00:07:49.543
generating great excitement and interest.

00:07:49.543 --> 00:07:52.012
His successful voyage provided the English

00:07:52.012 --> 00:07:54.581
with hope of finding a western route to Asia

00:07:54.581 --> 00:07:57.117
and competing with other European powers

00:07:57.117 --> 00:07:59.786
in the lucrative trade markets of the East.

00:07:59.786 --> 00:08:01.722
Encouraged by his success,

00:08:01.722 --> 00:08:04.892
Cabot made a second voyage in 1498,

00:08:04.892 --> 00:08:07.160
possibly intending to explore further

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:10.731
and solidify England's claim to the newfound lands.

00:08:10.731 --> 00:08:14.902
However, the details of this expedition are lost to history.

00:08:14.902 --> 00:08:17.738
Some reports suggest that the voyage was successful

00:08:17.738 --> 00:08:20.574
while others claim it ended in disaster

00:08:20.574 --> 00:08:23.277
with Cabot and his crew lost at sea.

00:08:24.912 --> 00:08:27.948
(dramatic music)

00:08:27.948 --> 00:08:31.184
While back in England, King Henry VIII was married

00:08:31.184 --> 00:08:34.054
to his first wife, Catherine of Aragon.

00:08:34.054 --> 00:08:36.156
During their beginning years of marriage,

00:08:36.156 --> 00:08:37.791
everything was going fine.

00:08:37.791 --> 00:08:39.293
Like any king at the time,

00:08:39.293 --> 00:08:41.828
he was forced to be loyal to the Catholic church

00:08:41.828 --> 00:08:44.798
and yearned for a strong and legitimate heir

00:08:44.798 --> 00:08:46.533
to secure his dynasty.

00:08:46.533 --> 00:08:50.304
However, Henry's heart grew heavy with a troubling dilemma

00:08:50.304 --> 00:08:51.872
as the years passed.

00:08:51.872 --> 00:08:53.840
His marriage to Catherine of Aragon

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:58.445
had only yielded a single surviving child, Princess Mary.

00:08:58.445 --> 00:09:01.381
The king's desperate desire for a male heir

00:09:01.381 --> 00:09:02.983
began to consume him

00:09:02.983 --> 00:09:04.785
and he became increasingly convinced

00:09:04.785 --> 00:09:07.788
that his marriage was invalid in the eyes of God.

00:09:07.788 --> 00:09:09.623
Turning to the Pope for a solution,

00:09:09.623 --> 00:09:11.458
Henry beseeched the Holy See

00:09:11.458 --> 00:09:14.428
to grant him an annulment of his marriage to Catherine.

00:09:14.428 --> 00:09:16.730
He argued that the marriage was unlawful,

00:09:16.730 --> 00:09:18.565
for Karen had previously been married

00:09:18.565 --> 00:09:21.802
to his older brother, Arthur, who had passed away.

00:09:21.802 --> 00:09:23.303
According to the Old Testament,

00:09:23.303 --> 00:09:26.573
marrying one's brother's widow was strictly forbidden,

00:09:26.573 --> 00:09:29.843
and Henry believed this was why he lacked a male heir.

00:09:29.843 --> 00:09:32.713
However, fate had other plans.

00:09:32.713 --> 00:09:36.049
The Pope, influenced by Catherine's powerful nephew,

00:09:36.049 --> 00:09:38.285
Emperor Charles V of Spain,

00:09:38.285 --> 00:09:40.454
refused to grant the annulment.

00:09:40.454 --> 00:09:44.291
Frustration and desperation gripped the king's heart,

00:09:44.291 --> 00:09:46.760
and he made a momentous decision.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:49.663
In a bold and unprecedented move,

00:09:49.663 --> 00:09:51.732
Henry VIII decided to break away

00:09:51.732 --> 00:09:53.767
from the Roman Catholic Church

00:09:53.767 --> 00:09:56.636
and establish his own church within England.

00:09:56.636 --> 00:10:00.240
So in 1534, the English parliament passed

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:01.942
the Act of Supremacy,

00:10:01.942 --> 00:10:05.012
formally severing England's ties to the papacy

00:10:05.012 --> 00:10:07.814
and officially creating the Church of England

00:10:07.814 --> 00:10:11.218
with King Henry VIII to be its spiritual leader,

00:10:11.218 --> 00:10:13.453
and Anglicism was born.

00:10:14.421 --> 00:10:17.157
(dramatic music)

00:10:18.558 --> 00:10:21.862
After King Henry divorced and beheaded his other wives,

00:10:21.862 --> 00:10:25.432
his daughter from Catherine, Mary 1, became queen

00:10:25.432 --> 00:10:28.668
and was nicknamed Bloody Mary through her killing spree

00:10:28.668 --> 00:10:30.771
to reestablish Catholicism.

00:10:30.771 --> 00:10:32.739
But her reign was short-lived

00:10:32.739 --> 00:10:36.076
as her half-sister Elizabeth I would soon take over

00:10:36.076 --> 00:10:39.579
and re-declare England to be a Protestant state.

00:10:39.579 --> 00:10:43.183
Elizabeth passed the Act of Supremacy in 1559,

00:10:43.183 --> 00:10:44.084
which made Elizabeth

00:10:44.084 --> 00:10:46.720
supreme governor of the Church of England.

00:10:46.720 --> 00:10:49.156
She also passed the Act of Uniformity,

00:10:49.156 --> 00:10:51.425
establishing the Book of Common Prayer

00:10:51.425 --> 00:10:53.093
as the official liturgy.

00:10:53.093 --> 00:10:55.062
However, outside of England,

00:10:55.062 --> 00:10:58.065
the race for colonization has already begun.

00:10:58.065 --> 00:11:01.001
Under King Philip, the Spanish established colonies

00:11:01.001 --> 00:11:03.236
across the South American continent.

00:11:03.236 --> 00:11:05.272
The Spanish were expanding their wealth,

00:11:05.272 --> 00:11:08.408
from the former capital of the Aztec, Tenochtitlan,

00:11:08.408 --> 00:11:10.143
to Machu Picchu in Peru

00:11:10.143 --> 00:11:12.412
and the Andes Mountains in Chile.

00:11:12.412 --> 00:11:13.947
Along the Brazilian coast,

00:11:13.947 --> 00:11:16.383
the Portuguese at several settlements,

00:11:16.383 --> 00:11:20.120
like Sao Vicente, Pernambuco, and Rio de Janeiro.

00:11:20.120 --> 00:11:22.989
The French established northern colonies in Quebec

00:11:22.989 --> 00:11:26.693
and some small territories in Florida called Fort Caroline.

00:11:26.693 --> 00:11:29.663
The race for overseas land was on.

00:11:29.663 --> 00:11:32.766
So Queen Elizabeth commissioned an army of seafarers

00:11:32.766 --> 00:11:34.167
to discover this planet.

00:11:34.167 --> 00:11:37.170
The group, colloquially known as the Sea Dogs,

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:38.638
was given legal access

00:11:38.638 --> 00:11:41.675
to pillage and loot all Spanish ships they saw

00:11:41.675 --> 00:11:44.344
with the hopes of creating British dominance

00:11:44.344 --> 00:11:46.046
on the global stage.

00:11:47.481 --> 00:11:50.784
One of her first appointees was John Hawkins,

00:11:50.784 --> 00:11:52.886
a pardoned killer who saved his life

00:11:52.886 --> 00:11:54.588
by joining the Royal Navy.

00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:59.259
In 1561, Hawkins made a voyage down to the Canary Islands,

00:11:59.259 --> 00:12:02.295
a Spanish island colony off the coast of Africa.

00:12:02.295 --> 00:12:05.198
Hawkins saw a process that would make him wealthy

00:12:05.198 --> 00:12:07.234
and hurt human beings.

00:12:07.234 --> 00:12:08.869
He learned about how to capture

00:12:08.869 --> 00:12:10.937
and sell people into slavery.

00:12:10.937 --> 00:12:12.339
With his new knowledge,

00:12:12.339 --> 00:12:15.509
in 1562, Hawkins set sail,

00:12:15.509 --> 00:12:18.712
traveling along the African coast to Sierra Leone,

00:12:18.712 --> 00:12:21.314
where he captured 300 Africans

00:12:21.314 --> 00:12:22.949
and trapped them in their ship.

00:12:22.949 --> 00:12:25.118
From there, he sailed to the Caribbean.

00:12:25.118 --> 00:12:28.855
He did not have permission from either Spain or Portugal

00:12:28.855 --> 00:12:30.590
to trade with their colonies,

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:32.259
so he sold his enslaved people

00:12:32.259 --> 00:12:35.562
in Isabella, Puerto de Plata, and Monte Christi,

00:12:35.562 --> 00:12:38.365
places where the local authorities did not enforce

00:12:38.365 --> 00:12:40.367
government trade embargoes.

00:12:40.367 --> 00:12:41.968
The enslaved people were traded

00:12:41.968 --> 00:12:44.538
for pearls, hides, and sugar.

00:12:44.538 --> 00:12:46.773
The trade was so prosperous

00:12:46.773 --> 00:12:48.742
that when he returned to England,

00:12:48.742 --> 00:12:51.545
he was knighted and to be called sir.

00:12:51.545 --> 00:12:53.847
In October 1564,

00:12:53.847 --> 00:12:57.250
Hawkins went on another voyage back to Sierra Leone.

00:12:57.250 --> 00:13:01.121
He took over 400 enslaved people from Africa.

00:13:01.121 --> 00:13:03.123
Some he bought from the Portuguese,

00:13:03.123 --> 00:13:06.560
others he kidnapped directly by raiding the coast.

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:10.730
He left Africa on January 29th, 1565.

00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:13.400
On April 3rd, 1565,

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:16.102
Hawkins arrived at Borburata in Venezuela.

00:13:16.102 --> 00:13:18.038
As trade was prohibited,

00:13:18.038 --> 00:13:20.040
he carried out a fake threat of force

00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:22.242
with the local governor's collusion.

00:13:22.242 --> 00:13:24.678
He then traveled to Rio de la Hacha

00:13:24.678 --> 00:13:25.912
where he used power

00:13:25.912 --> 00:13:28.582
to ensure the deals he thought were fair.

00:13:28.582 --> 00:13:31.117
He sold 300 enslaved people.

00:13:31.117 --> 00:13:34.554
He was paid in gold, silver, and other precious items,

00:13:34.554 --> 00:13:37.224
and took further orders to trade enslaved people

00:13:37.224 --> 00:13:38.692
on a future voyage.

00:13:38.692 --> 00:13:42.529
His third slave voyage wasn't as easy as the first two.

00:13:42.529 --> 00:13:44.598
When he arrived on the African coast,

00:13:44.598 --> 00:13:46.967
he could not gather any enslaved people

00:13:46.967 --> 00:13:49.269
because of a Portuguese embargo.

00:13:49.269 --> 00:13:51.304
He attempted to capture and kidnap

00:13:51.304 --> 00:13:54.040
the inhabitants of a village near Cape Verde,

00:13:54.040 --> 00:13:56.209
but he was wounded and had to retreat.

00:13:56.209 --> 00:13:59.279
Hawkins recruited a local king in Sierra Leone

00:13:59.279 --> 00:14:01.948
to help him forcibly kidnap people,

00:14:01.948 --> 00:14:04.751
capturing over 500 people.

00:14:04.751 --> 00:14:07.454
On February 7th, 1568,

00:14:07.454 --> 00:14:11.024
he set sale across the Atlantic Ocean to sell these people.

00:14:11.024 --> 00:14:13.927
He sold some of his captives in Margarita Province

00:14:13.927 --> 00:14:15.528
and others in Borburata.

00:14:15.528 --> 00:14:17.063
At Rio de la Hacha,

00:14:17.063 --> 00:14:19.733
the governor refused him permission to trade.

00:14:19.733 --> 00:14:22.402
So Hawkins and his assistant, Francis Drake,

00:14:22.402 --> 00:14:23.837
shot at his house,

00:14:23.837 --> 00:14:25.438
and they took over the town

00:14:25.438 --> 00:14:27.607
before selling the enslaved people.

00:14:27.607 --> 00:14:28.942
On his retreat, though,

00:14:28.942 --> 00:14:32.212
the voyage ran into the Spanish port of San Juan de Ulua

00:14:32.212 --> 00:14:33.580
because of a storm.

00:14:33.580 --> 00:14:35.749
The Spanish cannons roared to life

00:14:35.749 --> 00:14:37.617
in the middle of peace talks,

00:14:37.617 --> 00:14:40.153
sending cannonballs hurdling through the air

00:14:40.153 --> 00:14:41.921
towards the English ships.

00:14:41.921 --> 00:14:45.258
Though outnumbered, Hawkins' fleet maneuvered skillfully,

00:14:45.258 --> 00:14:47.294
evading the deadly projectiles

00:14:47.294 --> 00:14:49.462
and returning fire with cannons.

00:14:49.462 --> 00:14:50.997
The battle raged on

00:14:50.997 --> 00:14:54.301
and the English sailors fought with fierce determination.

00:14:54.301 --> 00:14:56.269
However, amid the chaos,

00:14:56.269 --> 00:14:58.371
Hawkins and his men had a choice:

00:14:58.371 --> 00:15:00.607
retreat or spend the rest of their lives

00:15:00.607 --> 00:15:02.108
in a Spanish galley.

00:15:02.108 --> 00:15:05.478
114 men became prisoners,

00:15:05.478 --> 00:15:08.581
while Hawkins and 15 others returned to England

00:15:08.581 --> 00:15:10.583
and made a handsome profit.

00:15:10.583 --> 00:15:15.055
Regardless of the morals, slavery was a lucrative business

00:15:15.055 --> 00:15:18.558
and the English would do anything to protect it.

00:15:20.727 --> 00:15:24.364
That's when, in 1577, she sent Francis Drake

00:15:24.364 --> 00:15:26.800
to find a new trade passage to Asia.

00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:28.601
Unlike previous explorers,

00:15:28.601 --> 00:15:30.837
Drake knew of the existence of America

00:15:30.837 --> 00:15:33.840
and wanted to find a way around the massive landmass

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:36.076
so they could reach the lands of Asia.

00:15:36.076 --> 00:15:38.945
Drake's first destination was around Cape Horn,

00:15:38.945 --> 00:15:41.114
the southern tip of South America.

00:15:41.114 --> 00:15:42.982
The fierce winds roared

00:15:42.982 --> 00:15:45.452
and the waves towered like mountains,

00:15:45.452 --> 00:15:48.121
testing the crew's resolve and comradery.

00:15:48.121 --> 00:15:49.956
But Drake's steady leadership

00:15:49.956 --> 00:15:53.126
and unwavering determination carried them through,

00:15:53.126 --> 00:15:55.462
and they emerged from the Strait of Magellan

00:15:55.462 --> 00:15:57.764
into the boundless Pacific Ocean.

00:15:57.764 --> 00:15:59.432
The world was their oyster

00:15:59.432 --> 00:16:00.734
as they sailed northward

00:16:00.734 --> 00:16:03.336
along the western coast of South America.

00:16:03.336 --> 00:16:07.240
The landscapes were a tapestry of untamed beauty

00:16:07.240 --> 00:16:10.110
and the wildlife fascinated and intrigued them.

00:16:10.110 --> 00:16:13.613
As they journeyed onward, they reached a land of wonder,

00:16:13.613 --> 00:16:16.182
the present-day coast of California.

00:16:16.182 --> 00:16:19.486
Here, they made a landfall in a place of beauty and bounty,

00:16:19.486 --> 00:16:22.989
naming it Nova Albion in honor of England,

00:16:22.989 --> 00:16:24.591
their beloved homeland.

00:16:24.591 --> 00:16:27.260
Their voyage then stretched through the Pacific

00:16:27.260 --> 00:16:28.928
and took them to Indonesia,

00:16:28.928 --> 00:16:32.332
which was aptly called the Spice Islands at the time,

00:16:32.332 --> 00:16:35.168
a treasure trove of fragrant delights.

00:16:35.168 --> 00:16:37.604
Here, they traded with the welcoming locals,

00:16:37.604 --> 00:16:41.040
exchanging goods and stories from distant lands.

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:43.410
The journey homeward was challenging.

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:45.345
The vastness of the Indian Ocean

00:16:45.345 --> 00:16:47.680
and the unpredictable seas tested them,

00:16:47.680 --> 00:16:50.016
but Drake's ingenuity and determination

00:16:50.016 --> 00:16:52.786
guided them safely around the Cape of Good Hope,

00:16:52.786 --> 00:16:54.587
the southern tip of Africa.

00:16:54.587 --> 00:16:57.023
Finally, after nearly three years

00:16:57.023 --> 00:16:58.625
of adventure and discovery,

00:16:58.625 --> 00:17:03.530
the Golden Hind returned to England in September 1580

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:06.566
and was knighted as Sir Francis Drake.

00:17:06.566 --> 00:17:08.401
(dramatic music)

00:17:08.401 --> 00:17:10.103
Looking upon this New World,

00:17:10.103 --> 00:17:11.237
the English realized

00:17:11.237 --> 00:17:13.339
that if they wanted to grow as an empire,

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:16.676
they would need to establish a colony in the New World.

00:17:16.676 --> 00:17:21.080
In 1584, Queen Elizabeth I granted Sir Walter Raleigh

00:17:21.080 --> 00:17:22.515
a charter to explore

00:17:22.515 --> 00:17:25.185
and colonize the lands of the New World.

00:17:25.185 --> 00:17:27.053
Raleigh dispatched an expedition

00:17:27.053 --> 00:17:30.256
led by Sir Richard Grenville to Roanoke Island

00:17:30.256 --> 00:17:32.959
off the coast of present-day North Carolina.

00:17:32.959 --> 00:17:35.195
The group consisted of about a hundred men,

00:17:35.195 --> 00:17:38.565
including soldiers, scientists, and artisans.

00:17:38.565 --> 00:17:42.202
They arrived in 1585 and began building a fort

00:17:42.202 --> 00:17:45.538
and interacting with the local Native American tribes.

00:17:45.538 --> 00:17:48.274
The relationship between the English colonists

00:17:48.274 --> 00:17:51.411
and the Native Americans was initially positive

00:17:51.411 --> 00:17:54.047
as they traded goods and exchanged knowledge.

00:17:54.047 --> 00:17:56.850
However, tensions rose over time

00:17:56.850 --> 00:17:59.085
and the region's harsh conditions,

00:17:59.085 --> 00:18:01.588
including disease and food shortages,

00:18:01.588 --> 00:18:03.623
strained the colonists' morale.

00:18:03.623 --> 00:18:05.024
Amid the challenges,

00:18:05.024 --> 00:18:07.760
Sir Francis Drake, on his way back to England

00:18:07.760 --> 00:18:10.830
after another successful privateering expedition,

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:13.299
offered to take the colonists back with him.

00:18:13.299 --> 00:18:15.001
Disheartened by the hardships,

00:18:15.001 --> 00:18:17.403
many of the settlers accepted the offer

00:18:17.403 --> 00:18:20.340
and returned to England in 1586,

00:18:20.340 --> 00:18:22.942
leaving the Roanoke colony to fail.

00:18:22.942 --> 00:18:27.914
Raleigh tried again a year later in 1587 with 118 settlers,

00:18:27.981 --> 00:18:31.684
but yet it was found abandoned just three years later.

00:18:31.684 --> 00:18:34.220
(dramatic music)

00:18:34.220 --> 00:18:38.858
In 1588, Spanish King Philip II felt he had a moral duty

00:18:38.858 --> 00:18:41.661
to take over England in the name of Catholicism,

00:18:41.661 --> 00:18:43.496
so he sent the Spanish Armada,

00:18:43.496 --> 00:18:46.266
which wasn't just an ordinary naval force.

00:18:46.266 --> 00:18:50.270
It was arguably one of these scariest ones in history.

00:18:50.270 --> 00:18:53.840
The armada consisted of around 130 ships.

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:55.942
Among these ships were galleons,

00:18:55.942 --> 00:18:58.978
which were the principle warships of the armada.

00:18:58.978 --> 00:19:01.781
Galleons were large, heavily armed vessels

00:19:01.781 --> 00:19:03.983
that were the backbone of the Spanish fleet

00:19:03.983 --> 00:19:05.118
during that period.

00:19:05.118 --> 00:19:06.219
Accompanying the fleet

00:19:06.219 --> 00:19:10.523
were more than 30,000 soldiers, sailors, and marines

00:19:10.523 --> 00:19:12.458
who were part of the expedition.

00:19:12.458 --> 00:19:14.694
The soldiers were seasoned veterans,

00:19:14.694 --> 00:19:17.030
while the sailors were experienced navigators

00:19:17.030 --> 00:19:18.097
and crew members,

00:19:18.097 --> 00:19:22.068
many of whom had participated in previous naval campaigns.

00:19:22.068 --> 00:19:23.836
The Spanish Armada was intended

00:19:23.836 --> 00:19:25.738
to be a formidable force

00:19:25.738 --> 00:19:28.675
capable of overpowering any opposition

00:19:28.675 --> 00:19:32.178
and making England a colony of the Spanish empire.

00:19:32.178 --> 00:19:34.414
On the other side of the English Channel,

00:19:34.414 --> 00:19:37.050
Queen Elizabeth and her advisors were well aware

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:38.518
of the impending threat.

00:19:38.518 --> 00:19:41.821
She called upon her naval commander, Sir Francis Drake,

00:19:41.821 --> 00:19:44.223
and her vice admiral, Charles Howard,

00:19:44.223 --> 00:19:47.193
to prepare the English fleet for the upcoming battle.

00:19:47.193 --> 00:19:48.661
Despite being outnumbered

00:19:48.661 --> 00:19:50.730
and having fewer and smaller ships,

00:19:50.730 --> 00:19:53.366
the English Navy had a significant advantage

00:19:53.366 --> 00:19:55.969
in maneuverability and firepower.

00:19:55.969 --> 00:19:58.104
In the late spring of 1588,

00:19:58.104 --> 00:20:00.873
the Spanish Armada sailed towards England,

00:20:00.873 --> 00:20:02.976
confident of its superiority.

00:20:02.976 --> 00:20:05.845
However, the English had a cunning plan.

00:20:05.845 --> 00:20:08.448
Using smaller, more agile ships,

00:20:08.448 --> 00:20:09.816
they sacked the armada

00:20:09.816 --> 00:20:12.185
as it made its way along the coast of England.

00:20:12.185 --> 00:20:14.487
The English ships would attack from the rear,

00:20:14.487 --> 00:20:18.191
firing salvos at the larger, slower Spanish vessels,

00:20:18.191 --> 00:20:19.726
and then quickly retreat,

00:20:19.726 --> 00:20:23.363
making it difficult for the armada to respond effectively.

00:20:23.363 --> 00:20:26.065
As the Spanish fleet approached the English Channel,

00:20:26.065 --> 00:20:28.334
the English sent eight fire ships,

00:20:28.334 --> 00:20:31.838
vessels loaded with flammable materials and set ablaze,

00:20:31.838 --> 00:20:33.373
towards the armada.

00:20:33.373 --> 00:20:36.142
The sight of the fiery infernos heading their way

00:20:36.142 --> 00:20:37.944
unnerved the Spanish sailors,

00:20:37.944 --> 00:20:39.912
who broke formation to avoid the risk

00:20:39.912 --> 00:20:42.215
of being consumed by the flames.

00:20:42.215 --> 00:20:45.251
This disruption further weakened the Spanish fleet

00:20:45.251 --> 00:20:48.755
and allowed the English to gain a tactical advantage.

00:20:48.755 --> 00:20:53.526
The decisive Battle of Gravelines came on July 29th, 1588

00:20:53.526 --> 00:20:55.862
off the coast of Gravelines, France.

00:20:55.862 --> 00:20:58.498
The English fleet engaged the Spanish Armada

00:20:58.498 --> 00:21:00.867
in a fierce and prolonged battle.

00:21:00.867 --> 00:21:03.636
The English employed innovative naval tactics,

00:21:03.636 --> 00:21:05.738
including ship boarding techniques

00:21:05.738 --> 00:21:08.341
involving grappling hooks and small arms fire,

00:21:08.341 --> 00:21:10.743
to engage the enemy at close quarters.

00:21:10.743 --> 00:21:13.179
After a full day of intense fighting,

00:21:13.179 --> 00:21:15.982
the Spanish Armada, battered and disoriented,

00:21:15.982 --> 00:21:17.417
attempted to regroup.

00:21:17.417 --> 00:21:20.586
However, the English were relentless in their pursuit.

00:21:20.586 --> 00:21:22.789
With dwindling supplies and morale,

00:21:22.789 --> 00:21:24.424
the armada began to retreat,

00:21:24.424 --> 00:21:26.492
trying to navigate back to Spain.

00:21:26.492 --> 00:21:27.760
The journey back to Spain

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:30.530
was a harrowing one for the Spanish Armada.

00:21:30.530 --> 00:21:33.266
Harsh storms and strong currents took their toll

00:21:33.266 --> 00:21:35.234
on the already weakened fleet.

00:21:35.234 --> 00:21:38.137
By the time the remnants of the armada reached Spain,

00:21:38.137 --> 00:21:40.873
it was but a shadow of its former self.

00:21:41.841 --> 00:21:42.775
(dramatic music)

00:21:42.775 --> 00:21:44.577
While closer to home,

00:21:44.577 --> 00:21:47.714
England wanted to expand their power over Ireland.

00:21:47.714 --> 00:21:51.484
At the time, Ireland was divided into two main regions,

00:21:51.484 --> 00:21:54.287
the Pale and the Gaelic Irish regions.

00:21:54.287 --> 00:21:57.724
The Pale, which is located under the greater Dublin region,

00:21:57.724 --> 00:22:00.159
was under English control and authority,

00:22:00.159 --> 00:22:03.629
while the Gaelic Irish regions were largely autonomous

00:22:03.629 --> 00:22:06.099
and operated under traditional Brehon law.

00:22:06.099 --> 00:22:08.000
In the Gaelic Irish regions,

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:11.170
the English sought to assert more control over the island

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:14.540
and imposed policies that threatened the Irish way of life,

00:22:14.540 --> 00:22:16.275
leading to rising tensions

00:22:16.275 --> 00:22:18.778
and discontent among the Gaelic lords.

00:22:18.778 --> 00:22:20.947
Hugh O'Neill, the Earl of Tyrone,

00:22:20.947 --> 00:22:23.182
was in the middle of this brewing storm.

00:22:23.182 --> 00:22:26.352
He was a man of noble birth and strong convictions,

00:22:26.352 --> 00:22:29.155
torn between his loyalty to the English Crown

00:22:29.155 --> 00:22:31.691
and his love for the land and its people.

00:22:31.691 --> 00:22:33.292
As the Earl of Tyrone,

00:22:33.292 --> 00:22:36.863
he held significant sway over the province of Ulster

00:22:36.863 --> 00:22:38.865
located in the north of the country.

00:22:38.865 --> 00:22:42.268
He, though, was tired of all the power hungry demands

00:22:42.268 --> 00:22:43.736
of the English empire

00:22:43.736 --> 00:22:46.973
and could not bear to see his beloved Ireland suffer

00:22:46.973 --> 00:22:48.908
under the yoke of foreign rule.

00:22:48.908 --> 00:22:51.310
It was time for a rebellion.

00:22:51.310 --> 00:22:53.112
Hugh O'Neill raised his banner,

00:22:53.112 --> 00:22:56.883
calling upon other Gaelic lords to join him in a resistance.

00:22:56.883 --> 00:23:00.219
Among those who rallied to his cause was Hugh O'Donnell,

00:23:00.219 --> 00:23:01.788
the Earl of Tyreconnell,

00:23:01.788 --> 00:23:04.657
a fierce and noble warrior in his own right.

00:23:04.657 --> 00:23:05.958
United in purpose,

00:23:05.958 --> 00:23:08.661
the two lords formed a formidable alliance,

00:23:08.661 --> 00:23:11.063
determined to face the storm that awaited them.

00:23:11.063 --> 00:23:13.366
The English Crown responded swiftly,

00:23:13.366 --> 00:23:16.068
sending forth armies led by seasoned commanders

00:23:16.068 --> 00:23:17.637
like Sir Henry Bagenal.

00:23:17.637 --> 00:23:19.572
Battle after battle ensued,

00:23:19.572 --> 00:23:21.841
each skirmish leaving the countryside scarred

00:23:21.841 --> 00:23:23.743
with the remnants of the struggle.

00:23:23.743 --> 00:23:26.712
As the days turned into months and then into years,

00:23:26.712 --> 00:23:30.016
the rebellion earned the name of the Nine Years' War.

00:23:30.016 --> 00:23:32.318
The Irish people and the English suffered,

00:23:32.318 --> 00:23:36.222
for the conflict brought untold hardships to both sides.

00:23:36.222 --> 00:23:38.124
As the Irish were near defeat,

00:23:38.124 --> 00:23:42.261
in 1601, a glimmer of hope appeared on the horizon

00:23:42.261 --> 00:23:45.631
when a small Spanish expeditionary force arrived

00:23:45.631 --> 00:23:47.900
to aid the Irish rebels.

00:23:47.900 --> 00:23:49.769
It was a welcome respite,

00:23:49.769 --> 00:23:52.638
and the tide seemed to turn in their favor for a moment,

00:23:52.638 --> 00:23:54.907
but fate had other plans.

00:23:54.907 --> 00:23:57.610
The turning point came at the Battle of Kinsale,

00:23:57.610 --> 00:23:59.679
where the Irish and Spanish forces suffered

00:23:59.679 --> 00:24:01.380
a crushing defeat.

00:24:01.380 --> 00:24:03.883
The dream of independence disappeared

00:24:03.883 --> 00:24:06.652
and the rebellion's fate hung in the balance.

00:24:06.652 --> 00:24:09.856
In 1603, the rebellion came to an end.

00:24:09.856 --> 00:24:12.325
The Irish forces, tired and depleted,

00:24:12.325 --> 00:24:14.660
surrendered to the English Crown.

00:24:14.660 --> 00:24:16.562
The terms of the Treaty of Mellifont

00:24:16.562 --> 00:24:18.531
granted pardons to the rebels,

00:24:18.531 --> 00:24:20.766
allowing them to retain some of their lands

00:24:20.766 --> 00:24:22.468
and religious freedoms.

00:24:22.468 --> 00:24:26.005
However, the treaty also led for the language of Gaelic

00:24:26.005 --> 00:24:28.507
to be systematically destroyed.

00:24:28.507 --> 00:24:31.344
Catholicism was to be strongly discouraged,

00:24:31.344 --> 00:24:33.312
only Anglicanism.

00:24:33.312 --> 00:24:36.015
Ireland was to be transformed into England,

00:24:36.015 --> 00:24:38.451
to no longer be a Gaelic country,

00:24:38.451 --> 00:24:41.787
but one of the Anglo-Saxons.

00:24:41.787 --> 00:24:44.523
(dramatic music)

00:24:45.591 --> 00:24:48.261
However, England didn't just want to be the master

00:24:48.261 --> 00:24:49.462
of its neighbors.

00:24:49.462 --> 00:24:51.998
It wanted control over the New World.

00:24:51.998 --> 00:24:56.135
So in 1606, the Virginia Company of London was founded

00:24:56.135 --> 00:24:59.105
to find wealth and a passage to the Pacific.

00:24:59.105 --> 00:25:00.740
With the blessing of King James,

00:25:00.740 --> 00:25:03.309
on December 20th, 1606,

00:25:03.309 --> 00:25:06.312
104 settlers left the River Thames in London,

00:25:06.312 --> 00:25:09.248
and, throughout the cold, blistery winter,

00:25:09.248 --> 00:25:11.484
went off to the New World.

00:25:11.484 --> 00:25:13.886
After a grueling winter on sea,

00:25:13.886 --> 00:25:17.590
on the fateful day of May 13th, 1607,

00:25:17.590 --> 00:25:20.426
the settlers arrived on a marshy peninsula

00:25:20.426 --> 00:25:23.896
in a town they've named Jamestown, after their king.

00:25:23.896 --> 00:25:26.265
Upon reaching the shores of the New World,

00:25:26.265 --> 00:25:28.935
the colonists marveled at the breathtaking beauty

00:25:28.935 --> 00:25:30.703
of the untamed land.

00:25:30.703 --> 00:25:34.974
The lush green forests, crystal clear waters,

00:25:34.974 --> 00:25:38.444
and abundant wildlife promised a paradise,

00:25:38.444 --> 00:25:42.081
but paradise quickly turned into a harsh reality.

00:25:42.081 --> 00:25:45.785
The unfamiliar environment presented numerous challenges.

00:25:45.785 --> 00:25:48.354
With its relentless heat and humidity,

00:25:48.354 --> 00:25:51.757
the Virginia climate proved unbearable for many.

00:25:51.757 --> 00:25:53.993
Disease spread among the settlers,

00:25:53.993 --> 00:25:56.395
taking its toll on their health and strength.

00:25:56.395 --> 00:25:59.498
Malaria and dysentery ran rampant,

00:25:59.498 --> 00:26:00.700
claiming many lives

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:03.803
and making each day a struggle for survival.

00:26:03.803 --> 00:26:07.873
The colonists faced another formidable adversary, hunger.

00:26:07.873 --> 00:26:11.310
They had arrived when crops were not yet ready for harvest.

00:26:11.310 --> 00:26:14.680
With dwindling supplies and no fertile soil to plant,

00:26:14.680 --> 00:26:18.117
the settlers found themselves on the brink of starvation.

00:26:18.117 --> 00:26:19.852
Their situation was dire,

00:26:19.852 --> 00:26:22.722
but the settlers' spirits were not quickly broken.

00:26:22.722 --> 00:26:24.623
They toiled day and night,

00:26:24.623 --> 00:26:26.559
determined to find a way to survive

00:26:26.559 --> 00:26:28.494
and thrive in this new land.

00:26:28.494 --> 00:26:31.931
They explored the surroundings hoping to find sustenance

00:26:31.931 --> 00:26:34.867
and establish relations with the native inhabitants,

00:26:34.867 --> 00:26:36.702
the Powhatan confederacy.

00:26:36.702 --> 00:26:39.739
However, the initial interactions with the Powhatans

00:26:39.739 --> 00:26:43.109
were fraught with misunderstandings and mistrust.

00:26:43.109 --> 00:26:46.379
The settlers struggled to communicate and negotiate,

00:26:46.379 --> 00:26:49.015
leading to clashes and heightened tensions.

00:26:49.015 --> 00:26:52.818
The Powhatans, understandably cautious of these strangers,

00:26:52.818 --> 00:26:55.588
did not readily embrace the newcomers.

00:26:55.588 --> 00:26:58.791
Leadership within the colony also faced challenges.

00:26:58.791 --> 00:27:02.395
With shifting power dynamics and a lack of solid direction,

00:27:02.395 --> 00:27:05.698
the settlers grappled with maintaining unity and order.

00:27:05.698 --> 00:27:08.601
The departure of their bold leader, John Smith,

00:27:08.601 --> 00:27:12.371
further exacerbated the situation, leaving them adrift.

00:27:12.371 --> 00:27:14.874
In the harsh winter of 1609,

00:27:14.874 --> 00:27:16.842
known as the Starving Time,

00:27:16.842 --> 00:27:19.612
the colonists faced their darkest hour.

00:27:19.612 --> 00:27:22.815
Food supplies ran out and desperation set in.

00:27:22.815 --> 00:27:25.184
They ate whatever they could find,

00:27:25.184 --> 00:27:27.653
even horses, pets, and leather.

00:27:27.653 --> 00:27:29.455
But it was never enough.

00:27:29.455 --> 00:27:32.925
The colonies population dwindled as hunger, disease,

00:27:32.925 --> 00:27:35.928
and conflicts with the Powhatans took their toll.

00:27:35.928 --> 00:27:39.532
Despite all odds, a glimmer of hope emerged.

00:27:39.532 --> 00:27:42.435
A young and innovative settler, John Rolfe,

00:27:42.435 --> 00:27:45.438
introduced tobacco cultivation to Jamestown.

00:27:45.438 --> 00:27:48.707
The crop thrived in the Virginia soil and climate,

00:27:48.707 --> 00:27:51.877
bringing financial prosperity to the struggling colony.

00:27:51.877 --> 00:27:55.114
Tobacco quickly became a valuable commodity,

00:27:55.114 --> 00:27:56.615
attracting more settlers

00:27:56.615 --> 00:27:59.151
and rejuvenating Jamestown's fortunes.

00:27:59.151 --> 00:28:01.153
With their determination renewed,

00:28:01.153 --> 00:28:04.623
the settlers worked tirelessly to build a better future.

00:28:04.623 --> 00:28:06.358
They established better relations

00:28:06.358 --> 00:28:08.027
with some of the Powhatans,

00:28:08.027 --> 00:28:09.462
learning from each other's ways

00:28:09.462 --> 00:28:11.464
and building bridges of understanding.

00:28:11.464 --> 00:28:13.999
An English colony was finally able

00:28:13.999 --> 00:28:16.902
to be established on American soil.

00:28:16.902 --> 00:28:18.871
(bright music)

00:28:18.871 --> 00:28:21.440
While Jamestown was burgeoning as a colony,

00:28:21.440 --> 00:28:23.375
merchant William Hawkins was sent

00:28:23.375 --> 00:28:25.344
to establish trade in India.

00:28:25.344 --> 00:28:28.881
In 1607, he sailed from the port of Plymouth, England,

00:28:28.881 --> 00:28:30.082
aboard the Hector,

00:28:30.082 --> 00:28:32.518
accompanied by a fleet of three ships.

00:28:32.518 --> 00:28:33.486
The crew was a mix

00:28:33.486 --> 00:28:36.922
of experienced sailors, traders, and diplomats

00:28:36.922 --> 00:28:40.025
carrying various goods to trade with distant lands.

00:28:40.025 --> 00:28:44.029
After a perilous voyage fraught with storms and rough seas,

00:28:44.029 --> 00:28:47.299
the fleet arrived at the Cape of Good Hope in South Africa,

00:28:47.299 --> 00:28:50.469
marking a significant milestone in their journey.

00:28:50.469 --> 00:28:52.805
They entered the vast Indian Ocean

00:28:52.805 --> 00:28:55.741
and made their way towards the western coast of India.

00:28:55.741 --> 00:28:59.211
Hawkins arrived in the Port of Surat in 1608,

00:28:59.211 --> 00:29:01.547
one of the most important trading centers

00:29:01.547 --> 00:29:03.415
on the Indian west coast.

00:29:03.415 --> 00:29:07.653
The Mughal Emperor Jahangir, who ruled over a vast empire,

00:29:07.653 --> 00:29:09.922
showed a keen interest in foreign trade

00:29:09.922 --> 00:29:12.358
and welcomed the English visitors.

00:29:12.358 --> 00:29:14.927
Hawkins' first meeting with Emperor Jahangir

00:29:14.927 --> 00:29:18.264
occurred in Agra, near the famous Taj Mahal.

00:29:18.264 --> 00:29:19.899
Through skilled interpreters,

00:29:19.899 --> 00:29:21.300
they engaged in discussions

00:29:21.300 --> 00:29:23.936
about trade, politics, and culture.

00:29:23.936 --> 00:29:27.072
The emperor was intrigued by the English goods

00:29:27.072 --> 00:29:30.075
and desired further interaction and trade with England.

00:29:30.075 --> 00:29:33.479
The negotiations between Hawkins and the Mughal emperor

00:29:33.479 --> 00:29:35.714
resulted in a favorable agreement,

00:29:35.714 --> 00:29:38.884
granting the English East India Company the privilege

00:29:38.884 --> 00:29:41.587
to establish a trading post in Surat.

00:29:41.587 --> 00:29:43.522
This marked the official beginning

00:29:43.522 --> 00:29:46.358
of England's trade relations with India.

00:29:46.358 --> 00:29:50.863
By 1612, the Surat trading post was an entire operation

00:29:50.863 --> 00:29:52.531
where the English would begin trading

00:29:52.531 --> 00:29:54.233
for various Indian goods,

00:29:54.233 --> 00:29:57.336
such as textiles, spices, and indigo

00:29:57.336 --> 00:30:00.406
in exchange for English weapons and metalware.

00:30:01.440 --> 00:30:02.575
(dramatic music)

00:30:02.575 --> 00:30:07.346
In 1615, an English diplomat of the name Sir Thomas Roe

00:30:07.346 --> 00:30:10.115
arrived at the Grand Court of Emperor Jahangir

00:30:10.115 --> 00:30:11.584
of the Mughal Emperor.

00:30:11.584 --> 00:30:14.453
As Sir Thomas Roe stepped into the opulent halls

00:30:14.453 --> 00:30:15.621
of the Mughal court,

00:30:15.621 --> 00:30:18.624
he was greeted with a display of cultural grandeur

00:30:18.624 --> 00:30:20.226
unmatched in the West.

00:30:20.226 --> 00:30:23.329
The colorful fabrics, the exquisite jewelry,

00:30:23.329 --> 00:30:26.232
and the sweet aroma of incense filled the air.

00:30:26.232 --> 00:30:28.367
The English envoy was mesmerized

00:30:28.367 --> 00:30:30.569
by the splendor of the Mughal empire.

00:30:30.569 --> 00:30:32.705
Amidst the regal surroundings,

00:30:32.705 --> 00:30:35.874
Sir Thomas Roe presented King James I's letter

00:30:35.874 --> 00:30:39.912
to Emperor Jahangir, a token of goodwill and friendship.

00:30:39.912 --> 00:30:43.582
In return, he gave a collection of rare English goods,

00:30:43.582 --> 00:30:45.651
marveling at the Mughal appreciation

00:30:45.651 --> 00:30:47.653
for luxurious commodities.

00:30:47.653 --> 00:30:50.723
Over the three years Roe spent in Jahangir's court,

00:30:50.723 --> 00:30:54.526
England increased trade and influence in the lands of India.

00:30:55.394 --> 00:30:56.929
While back in England,

00:30:56.929 --> 00:31:00.833
King James made his religious expectations very clear.

00:31:00.833 --> 00:31:03.202
Everyone must be Anglican.

00:31:03.202 --> 00:31:05.571
If you do not comply, leave.

00:31:05.571 --> 00:31:07.406
That's when the idea of America

00:31:07.406 --> 00:31:09.241
came to spark in their minds,

00:31:09.241 --> 00:31:12.444
a place where they can openly practice whatever they choose

00:31:12.444 --> 00:31:14.546
without any say by the government.

00:31:14.546 --> 00:31:17.750
If one wanted to practice a religion, they could.

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:20.152
Of course, most people wouldn't leave their homes

00:31:20.152 --> 00:31:21.420
for an unknown place

00:31:21.420 --> 00:31:24.590
if they weren't genuinely convicted of their beliefs.

00:31:24.590 --> 00:31:26.358
Only the most faithful

00:31:26.358 --> 00:31:29.595
and those who genuinely desire religious freedom

00:31:29.595 --> 00:31:31.830
would dare go on this voyage.

00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:34.700
The people who did were called pilgrims.

00:31:34.700 --> 00:31:39.171
So in mid-July 1620, the English Mayflower ship

00:31:39.171 --> 00:31:40.839
and the Dutch Speedwell ship

00:31:40.839 --> 00:31:43.042
were set to depart from Southampton.

00:31:43.042 --> 00:31:46.378
But yet, shortly after the crews were about to depart,

00:31:46.378 --> 00:31:48.447
the Speedwell sprung up a leak,

00:31:48.447 --> 00:31:51.283
forcing it to return to Dartmouth for repairs.

00:31:51.283 --> 00:31:53.786
They made a new start after the repairs,

00:31:53.786 --> 00:31:56.855
but more than 200 miles beyond land's end

00:31:56.855 --> 00:31:58.824
at the southwestern tip of England,

00:31:58.824 --> 00:32:00.893
Speedwell sprang another leak.

00:32:00.893 --> 00:32:02.828
It was now early September

00:32:02.828 --> 00:32:05.597
and they had no choice but to abandon Speedwell

00:32:05.597 --> 00:32:07.766
and decide on which passengers.

00:32:07.766 --> 00:32:10.269
However, this decision was not easy

00:32:10.269 --> 00:32:13.072
because while the Speedwell was making repairs,

00:32:13.072 --> 00:32:14.973
the other pilgrims on the Mayflower

00:32:14.973 --> 00:32:18.110
were eating all of the rations that were supposed to last

00:32:18.110 --> 00:32:20.045
until they made it to the New World.

00:32:20.045 --> 00:32:21.413
During the time of repair,

00:32:21.413 --> 00:32:23.549
the passengers never left the ship.

00:32:23.549 --> 00:32:25.584
After three months of delay,

00:32:25.584 --> 00:32:28.320
the Mayflower sailed from Plymouth, England, alone

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:31.123
on September 16th, 1620.

00:32:31.123 --> 00:32:32.691
The chances of the Mayflower

00:32:32.691 --> 00:32:34.693
making it to the New World was low

00:32:34.693 --> 00:32:36.562
because it was built to transport wine

00:32:36.562 --> 00:32:38.397
between England and Bordeaux,

00:32:38.397 --> 00:32:40.666
not across the Atlantic Ocean.

00:32:40.666 --> 00:32:42.668
Yet, they were driven by a purpose,

00:32:42.668 --> 00:32:46.405
the purpose of creating a new civilization for God.

00:32:46.405 --> 00:32:48.707
Their beliefs gave the passengers strength

00:32:48.707 --> 00:32:51.410
to crouch in semi-darkness below deck.

00:32:51.410 --> 00:32:54.513
With waves tossing the boat in different directions,

00:32:54.513 --> 00:32:56.215
men held onto their wives,

00:32:56.215 --> 00:32:58.450
who themselves had onto their children.

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:02.054
Water was soaking everyone and everything

00:33:02.054 --> 00:33:04.089
above and below the deck.

00:33:04.089 --> 00:33:07.659
In mid-ocean, the ship came close to being totally disabled

00:33:07.659 --> 00:33:11.163
and may have had to return to England or risk sinking.

00:33:11.163 --> 00:33:13.766
A storm badly damaged its main beam

00:33:13.766 --> 00:33:16.001
that even the sailors despaired.

00:33:16.001 --> 00:33:17.803
By a stroke of luck,

00:33:17.803 --> 00:33:20.239
one of the colonists had a metal jack screw

00:33:20.239 --> 00:33:21.640
he had purchased in Holland

00:33:21.640 --> 00:33:24.343
to help construct the new settler homes.

00:33:24.343 --> 00:33:26.211
They used it to secure the beam,

00:33:26.211 --> 00:33:28.147
which kept it from cracking further,

00:33:28.147 --> 00:33:31.016
thus maintaining the vessel's seaworthiness.

00:33:31.016 --> 00:33:32.418
Despite the crowding,

00:33:32.418 --> 00:33:35.721
unsanitary conditions, and seasickness,

00:33:35.721 --> 00:33:39.358
they somehow made it to Cape Cod on November 21st

00:33:39.358 --> 00:33:41.560
with only one fatality,

00:33:41.560 --> 00:33:44.329
establishing the colony of Plymouth.

00:33:44.329 --> 00:33:47.266
However, their luck will soon fade

00:33:47.266 --> 00:33:51.203
because by December, most of the passengers had become ill,

00:33:51.203 --> 00:33:54.807
coughing violently and suffering from the effects of scurvy.

00:33:54.807 --> 00:33:58.510
By March, only 47 colonists had survived,

00:33:58.510 --> 00:34:01.480
but yet the pilgrims were resilient people

00:34:01.480 --> 00:34:04.383
who could build houses and didn't die off completely.

00:34:05.684 --> 00:34:07.920
Shortly after the establishment of Plymouth,

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:10.889
explorer Thomas Warner wanted to grow the empire

00:34:10.889 --> 00:34:13.525
down to the tropical Caribbean islands.

00:34:13.525 --> 00:34:17.830
On January 28th, 1624, they landed on the island

00:34:17.830 --> 00:34:20.499
and established the colony of St. Christopher,

00:34:20.499 --> 00:34:23.068
which is now called St. Kitts today.

00:34:23.068 --> 00:34:26.939
In 1625, French Captain Pierre Belain d'Esnambuc

00:34:26.939 --> 00:34:27.873
joined the English

00:34:27.873 --> 00:34:31.276
and established a joint colony between the two countries.

00:34:31.276 --> 00:34:33.445
The reason Warner accepted the newcomers

00:34:33.445 --> 00:34:35.247
was nothing but benevolent.

00:34:35.247 --> 00:34:38.083
He was beginning to fear the native Kalinago tribe

00:34:38.083 --> 00:34:39.418
of the Carib people.

00:34:39.418 --> 00:34:42.020
Kalinago leader Ouboutou Tegremante

00:34:42.020 --> 00:34:45.824
held a secret meeting in 1626 with the other heads

00:34:45.824 --> 00:34:47.860
and decided to attack the Europeans

00:34:47.860 --> 00:34:49.995
on the night of the next full moon.

00:34:49.995 --> 00:34:52.130
The plan was revealed to the Europeans

00:34:52.130 --> 00:34:54.366
by an Igneri woman named Barbe.

00:34:54.366 --> 00:34:57.469
She was recently brought to St. Kitts as a slave wife

00:34:57.469 --> 00:35:00.372
after the Kalinago raided an Arawak island.

00:35:00.372 --> 00:35:02.241
The English and French joined forces

00:35:02.241 --> 00:35:04.209
and attacked the Kalinago at night.

00:35:04.209 --> 00:35:08.146
The colonists killed between 100 and 120 Caribs

00:35:08.146 --> 00:35:09.982
in their beds that night

00:35:09.982 --> 00:35:13.051
with only the most beautiful Kalinago women spared

00:35:13.051 --> 00:35:14.653
to serve as slaves.

00:35:14.653 --> 00:35:17.122
The following day, the French and British settlers

00:35:17.122 --> 00:35:20.659
rounded up the roughly 4,000 Kalinago natives

00:35:20.659 --> 00:35:23.662
and killed them while attempting to surrender.

00:35:23.662 --> 00:35:27.933
After the massacre, piles and piles of dead rotting bodies

00:35:27.933 --> 00:35:31.003
lingered throughout the point, the Bloody Point.

00:35:31.003 --> 00:35:34.373
The river was red with blood, the Bloody River.

00:35:34.373 --> 00:35:38.043
The remaining Kalinago people fled to neighboring islands.

00:35:38.043 --> 00:35:40.312
With all of the Kalinago people dead,

00:35:40.312 --> 00:35:42.381
a nasty problem has arrived.

00:35:42.381 --> 00:35:46.251
Who was supposed to do the labor-intensive tobacco farming?

00:35:46.251 --> 00:35:48.453
It wasn't going to be the Europeans.

00:35:48.453 --> 00:35:51.189
Instead, they looked to Africa,

00:35:51.189 --> 00:35:54.693
and thus the slave trade was in high demand.

00:35:54.693 --> 00:35:57.863
While the English weren't done colonizing in the Caribbean,

00:35:57.863 --> 00:36:01.199
in 1625, they settled in Barbados.

00:36:01.199 --> 00:36:04.336
In 1627, they had Nevis.

00:36:04.336 --> 00:36:08.240
In 1632, they settled in Montserrat and Antigua.

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:10.409
The British were not going anyway,

00:36:10.409 --> 00:36:13.712
and they were determined to make a profit in the Caribbean.

00:36:14.813 --> 00:36:15.714
(dramatic music)

00:36:15.714 --> 00:36:17.249
While back in England,

00:36:17.249 --> 00:36:20.319
the religious atmosphere for extreme religious groups

00:36:20.319 --> 00:36:22.588
looked bleak for the Puritans.

00:36:22.588 --> 00:36:26.758
When King Charles the first had ascended the throne in 1625,

00:36:26.758 --> 00:36:30.162
he doubled down on his hatred for non-Anglicans.

00:36:30.162 --> 00:36:32.030
His atmosphere of intolerance

00:36:32.030 --> 00:36:34.766
led Puritan religious and business leaders

00:36:34.766 --> 00:36:37.202
to consider immigration to the New World

00:36:37.202 --> 00:36:40.372
as a viable means to escape persecution.

00:36:40.372 --> 00:36:42.507
In March 1629,

00:36:42.507 --> 00:36:44.610
King Charles dissolved parliament,

00:36:44.610 --> 00:36:47.312
beginning 11 years of rule without it.

00:36:47.312 --> 00:36:49.348
The Puritans were livid.

00:36:49.348 --> 00:36:50.682
They wanted freedom.

00:36:50.682 --> 00:36:52.651
Yet Charles was a dictator.

00:36:52.651 --> 00:36:55.887
That's why under the leadership of Minister John Winthrop,

00:36:55.887 --> 00:36:57.589
they've decided to leave.

00:36:57.589 --> 00:37:01.760
On April 8th, 1630, 11 ships left the Isle of Wight

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:05.163
carrying Winthrop and 700 other settlers.

00:37:05.163 --> 00:37:08.000
When the settlers landed in Salem, Massachusetts,

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:09.034
later that year,

00:37:09.034 --> 00:37:10.969
John Winthrop gave a sermon,

00:37:10.969 --> 00:37:12.971
a model of Christian charity

00:37:12.971 --> 00:37:15.407
that would change American history.

00:37:15.407 --> 00:37:17.409
The Massachusetts Bay Colony

00:37:17.409 --> 00:37:20.112
wasn't just another moneymaking expedition

00:37:20.112 --> 00:37:22.447
like Jamestown or St. Kitts.

00:37:22.447 --> 00:37:23.715
They viewed themselves

00:37:23.715 --> 00:37:26.251
as the people who would change the world.

00:37:26.251 --> 00:37:29.521
Their strict moral code would impress upon God

00:37:29.521 --> 00:37:32.290
and shine them to the center of history.

00:37:32.290 --> 00:37:33.825
Throughout the next 10 years,

00:37:33.825 --> 00:37:36.561
about 20,000 Puritans immigrated

00:37:36.561 --> 00:37:38.764
from England to Massachusetts

00:37:38.764 --> 00:37:41.900
and the neighboring colonies during the Great Migration.

00:37:41.900 --> 00:37:45.303
However, due to the sudden influx of Puritan settlers

00:37:45.303 --> 00:37:47.372
and slight religious differences,

00:37:47.372 --> 00:37:50.108
they migrated all across New England.

00:37:50.108 --> 00:37:52.811
Thomas Hooker established the Connecticut colony

00:37:52.811 --> 00:37:54.613
while Thomas Williams established

00:37:54.613 --> 00:37:56.415
the colony of Rhode Island,

00:37:56.415 --> 00:37:59.117
allowing for the growth of the Puritan religion

00:37:59.117 --> 00:38:01.553
and creating more cities on a hill.

00:38:02.587 --> 00:38:04.089
The Puritans weren't the only ones

00:38:04.089 --> 00:38:05.824
struggling with Anglicanism.

00:38:05.824 --> 00:38:08.627
Cecil Calvert, the Second Lord Baltimore,

00:38:08.627 --> 00:38:10.595
pursued an audacious plan.

00:38:10.595 --> 00:38:12.030
As the holder of the title,

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:16.101
he was granted a charter by King Charles I in 1632

00:38:16.101 --> 00:38:17.836
for lands in the New World.

00:38:17.836 --> 00:38:19.671
This charter recognized his right

00:38:19.671 --> 00:38:22.207
to establish a colony north of Virginia,

00:38:22.207 --> 00:38:23.909
which he named Maryland

00:38:23.909 --> 00:38:26.878
in honor of the Catholic Queen, Henrietta Maria.

00:38:26.878 --> 00:38:29.414
Cecil Calvert never set foot in Maryland,

00:38:29.414 --> 00:38:31.850
but his influence was deeply felt.

00:38:31.850 --> 00:38:32.884
Under his guidance,

00:38:32.884 --> 00:38:36.655
in 1634, two ships, the Ark and the Dove,

00:38:36.655 --> 00:38:39.691
carried the first settlers across the Atlantic.

00:38:39.691 --> 00:38:43.028
These pioneers, a mix of Catholics seeking religious freedom

00:38:43.028 --> 00:38:45.964
and Protestants hoping for economic opportunities,

00:38:45.964 --> 00:38:49.835
established the colony's first settlement, St. Mary's City.

00:38:51.336 --> 00:38:52.938
While the Americans weren't the ones

00:38:52.938 --> 00:38:54.773
struggling with Anglicanism,

00:38:54.773 --> 00:38:57.476
even though Scotland was neighbors with the English,

00:38:57.476 --> 00:38:59.811
they had their own religious traditions

00:38:59.811 --> 00:39:02.414
called the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.

00:39:02.414 --> 00:39:04.549
While King Charles I was focused

00:39:04.549 --> 00:39:07.052
on converting Scotland to Anglicanism,

00:39:07.052 --> 00:39:10.322
the Scottish Covenanter army was ready to defend.

00:39:10.322 --> 00:39:13.425
As Charles sent 20,000 soldiers to Edinburgh,

00:39:13.425 --> 00:39:17.996
he could not penetrate the Scottish army of 16,500 men

00:39:17.996 --> 00:39:19.731
in the border town of Berwick.

00:39:19.731 --> 00:39:23.902
Charles joined his troops at Berwick on May 30th, 1639,

00:39:23.902 --> 00:39:26.104
announcing he would not invade Scotland

00:39:26.104 --> 00:39:28.173
as long as the Scottish Covenanter army

00:39:28.173 --> 00:39:30.408
remained 10 miles north of the border.

00:39:30.408 --> 00:39:33.345
For now, there will be peace in Scotland.

00:39:34.813 --> 00:39:36.615
While across the world in India,

00:39:36.615 --> 00:39:40.051
the British East India Company was growing in influence.

00:39:40.051 --> 00:39:42.220
Trade between the sects of the world

00:39:42.220 --> 00:39:44.956
was eclipsing what the rest of Europe intended.

00:39:44.956 --> 00:39:47.993
This created the desire for a tiny parcel of land

00:39:47.993 --> 00:39:50.095
within the Indian subcontinent.

00:39:50.095 --> 00:39:54.466
So in 1639, the British East India Company dispatched

00:39:54.466 --> 00:39:57.969
two of its agents, Francis Day and Andrew Cogan,

00:39:57.969 --> 00:40:00.338
to the shores of the Coromandel Coast.

00:40:00.338 --> 00:40:03.942
Day and Cogan arrived in the bustling port of Masulipatnam,

00:40:03.942 --> 00:40:07.445
a central trading hub of the Vijayanagara Empire.

00:40:07.445 --> 00:40:08.680
They came with ambitions

00:40:08.680 --> 00:40:10.782
to establish a foothold in the region

00:40:10.782 --> 00:40:12.384
to secure their trade interests

00:40:12.384 --> 00:40:14.586
and compete with other European powers

00:40:14.586 --> 00:40:17.923
vying for control over these lucrative waters.

00:40:17.923 --> 00:40:21.560
Negotiations with the local Nayak rulers were complex.

00:40:21.560 --> 00:40:24.596
After months of discussions and an exchange of gifts,

00:40:24.596 --> 00:40:25.964
a deal was struck.

00:40:25.964 --> 00:40:29.301
The British East India Company secured attractive land,

00:40:29.301 --> 00:40:32.671
a mere stretch of coastal dunes and palm trees

00:40:32.671 --> 00:40:35.841
which they intended to develop into a trading post.

00:40:35.841 --> 00:40:37.475
The company could have spent more time

00:40:37.475 --> 00:40:40.345
with a modest parcel of land under their control.

00:40:40.345 --> 00:40:42.948
They began constructing a humble trading post

00:40:42.948 --> 00:40:46.484
consisting of a few warehouses and shelters for traders.

00:40:46.484 --> 00:40:49.888
The initial goal was to facilitate the exchange of goods,

00:40:49.888 --> 00:40:53.258
primarily textiles, spices, and precious metals,

00:40:53.258 --> 00:40:56.127
between the Indian subcontinent and England.

00:40:56.127 --> 00:40:58.697
The site was named Fort St. George

00:40:58.697 --> 00:41:02.033
as a nod to England's patron saint, Saint George.

00:41:02.033 --> 00:41:04.102
The name held religious significance

00:41:04.102 --> 00:41:06.438
and underscored the company's intent

00:41:06.438 --> 00:41:08.940
to establish a lasting presence.

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:12.410
As trade flourished, so did the security concerns.

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:13.745
The shifting alliances

00:41:13.745 --> 00:41:16.681
and rivalries among European powers in the region,

00:41:16.681 --> 00:41:18.717
such as the Portuguese and Dutch,

00:41:18.717 --> 00:41:21.019
prompted the company to rethink the nature

00:41:21.019 --> 00:41:22.520
of its trading post.

00:41:22.520 --> 00:41:24.890
The simple structures began to transform

00:41:24.890 --> 00:41:27.392
into more substantial buildings

00:41:27.392 --> 00:41:30.629
and defensive walls started to encircle the settlement.

00:41:30.629 --> 00:41:32.330
This transformation was more

00:41:32.330 --> 00:41:34.299
than just a matter of protection.

00:41:34.299 --> 00:41:36.768
It was a tangible manifestation

00:41:36.768 --> 00:41:39.137
of the company's growing ambitions.

00:41:39.137 --> 00:41:43.441
Fort St. George was becoming more than just a trading post.

00:41:43.441 --> 00:41:46.645
It was a strategic center of influence.

00:41:47.979 --> 00:41:49.447
(dramatic music)

00:41:49.447 --> 00:41:51.616
While back in the Isle of Ireland,

00:41:51.616 --> 00:41:54.452
the Irish Catholics were forced to give up their lands

00:41:54.452 --> 00:41:56.621
to British and Scottish settlers.

00:41:56.621 --> 00:41:58.223
These lands were redistributed

00:41:58.223 --> 00:42:00.292
to English-speaking Protestants

00:42:00.292 --> 00:42:01.426
with the remainder going

00:42:01.426 --> 00:42:05.330
to deserving native Irish lords and clans.

00:42:05.330 --> 00:42:10.001
So, naturally, this led to an Irish rebellion in 1641.

00:42:10.001 --> 00:42:11.903
A faction of the Irish gentry

00:42:11.903 --> 00:42:15.907
led by figures like Rory O'More and Sir Phelim O'Neill

00:42:15.907 --> 00:42:17.676
attempted a coup in Dublin.

00:42:17.676 --> 00:42:20.178
The plan was to seize Dublin Castle,

00:42:20.178 --> 00:42:21.980
a symbol of English power,

00:42:21.980 --> 00:42:23.615
but the plot was discovered,

00:42:23.615 --> 00:42:26.484
forcing the conspirators to act prematurely,

00:42:26.484 --> 00:42:28.553
leading to ultimate failure.

00:42:28.553 --> 00:42:31.389
However, O'Neill and the Catholics were not done.

00:42:31.389 --> 00:42:34.192
In November 1641, the rebels tried

00:42:34.192 --> 00:42:37.262
to attack the town of Lisnagarvey, but failed.

00:42:37.262 --> 00:42:40.131
Upset and angry, they lashed out in Portadown,

00:42:40.131 --> 00:42:42.701
a town that was once home to the McCann clan

00:42:42.701 --> 00:42:45.603
that was now resettled with new settlers.

00:42:45.603 --> 00:42:49.174
The Irish forces managed to overpower the British defenses,

00:42:49.174 --> 00:42:52.610
and in the aftermath, anger got the best of the British.

00:42:52.610 --> 00:42:54.212
On that chilling day,

00:42:54.212 --> 00:42:57.849
the Irish forced the Protestant prisoners to a wooden bridge

00:42:57.849 --> 00:43:00.385
that was intentionally broken in the middle.

00:43:00.385 --> 00:43:02.487
The Protestant prisoners were stripped

00:43:02.487 --> 00:43:05.991
and forced off the bridge into the cold river below.

00:43:05.991 --> 00:43:09.728
Those who tried to swim to safety were shot with muskets.

00:43:09.728 --> 00:43:12.364
It's estimated that around 100 settlers

00:43:12.364 --> 00:43:14.733
met this grim fade at the bridge,

00:43:14.733 --> 00:43:18.570
their cries echoing long after the waters had silenced them.

00:43:18.570 --> 00:43:20.872
In retaliation, in Islandmagee,

00:43:20.872 --> 00:43:24.275
two dozen Catholics were murdered in retaliation.

00:43:24.275 --> 00:43:27.278
The arrival of a Scottish Covenanter army in Ulster

00:43:27.278 --> 00:43:29.314
in April 1642

00:43:29.314 --> 00:43:31.783
led to further such atrocities.

00:43:31.783 --> 00:43:35.153
On Rathlin Island, Scottish soldiers from Clan Campbell

00:43:35.153 --> 00:43:37.522
were encouraged by their commanding officer,

00:43:37.522 --> 00:43:38.990
Sir Duncan Campbell,

00:43:38.990 --> 00:43:41.526
to kill the local Catholic MacDonalds,

00:43:41.526 --> 00:43:42.360
who were related

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:45.964
to the Campbell's enemies in Scotland, Clan MacDonald.

00:43:45.964 --> 00:43:48.933
They threw hundreds of MacDonald women over cliffs

00:43:48.933 --> 00:43:50.068
to their deaths.

00:43:50.068 --> 00:43:52.837
The killings were brought under some degree of control

00:43:52.837 --> 00:43:54.472
by Owen Row O'Neill,

00:43:54.472 --> 00:43:57.709
who, in July 1642, was given command

00:43:57.709 --> 00:43:59.477
of Irish forces in Ulster

00:43:59.477 --> 00:44:02.814
and hanged several rebels for attacking civilians.

00:44:02.814 --> 00:44:05.583
There was no unity among the Catholic leaders.

00:44:05.583 --> 00:44:07.285
They all acted upon their will.

00:44:07.285 --> 00:44:10.088
In order to win a war, you need to work together,

00:44:10.088 --> 00:44:13.124
so that's when all the Catholic leaders met in Kilkelly,

00:44:13.124 --> 00:44:16.361
where the Confederate Catholics of Ireland were born.

00:44:16.361 --> 00:44:17.962
Their goal was clear:

00:44:17.962 --> 00:44:20.131
to create an Irish Catholic state

00:44:20.131 --> 00:44:22.967
loyal to the English King Charles I,

00:44:22.967 --> 00:44:24.969
but autonomous in its functioning

00:44:24.969 --> 00:44:27.972
because they knew it was their best chance for peace.

00:44:27.972 --> 00:44:31.376
The confederation crafted its own governmental structure:

00:44:31.376 --> 00:44:34.045
an assembly to debate and make decisions,

00:44:34.045 --> 00:44:37.148
a council to oversee administrative functions,

00:44:37.148 --> 00:44:40.351
and a military arm to protect their interests.

00:44:40.351 --> 00:44:42.921
One of the confederation's defining moments

00:44:42.921 --> 00:44:44.823
was the creation of an oath.

00:44:44.823 --> 00:44:47.725
This oath symbolized their dual loyalty

00:44:47.725 --> 00:44:51.262
to the Catholic church and King Charles I.

00:44:51.262 --> 00:44:54.833
Members swore to uphold the rights of the church in Ireland,

00:44:54.833 --> 00:44:57.502
ensuring its prominence and protection.

00:44:57.502 --> 00:45:00.138
Within a few months of the rebellion's outbreak,

00:45:00.138 --> 00:45:02.874
almost all Catholic gentry joined it.

00:45:02.874 --> 00:45:04.642
Local lords and landowners

00:45:04.642 --> 00:45:06.711
raised armed units of their dependents

00:45:06.711 --> 00:45:09.380
to control the violence that engulfed the country,

00:45:09.380 --> 00:45:11.783
fearing that after the settlers were gone,

00:45:11.783 --> 00:45:14.652
the Irish peasantry would also turn on them.

00:45:14.652 --> 00:45:18.323
Secondly, the Long Parliament, the Irish administration,

00:45:18.323 --> 00:45:20.492
and King Charles made it clear

00:45:20.492 --> 00:45:23.962
that Irish Catholics who did not demonstrate their loyalty

00:45:23.962 --> 00:45:26.364
would be held responsible for the rebellion

00:45:26.364 --> 00:45:28.032
and killings of settlers

00:45:28.032 --> 00:45:29.934
and would confiscate their lands

00:45:29.934 --> 00:45:33.872
as stated in the Adventures Act of 1642.

00:45:33.872 --> 00:45:36.741
This apparent act of appeasement would not last, though,

00:45:36.741 --> 00:45:39.544
as the British Isles were now at war.

00:45:40.512 --> 00:45:43.448
(dramatic music)

00:45:43.448 --> 00:45:46.918
On the fateful day of January 4th, 1642,

00:45:46.918 --> 00:45:50.288
King Charles attempted to arrest five members of Parliament.

00:45:50.288 --> 00:45:53.424
These five members, John Pym, John Hampden,

00:45:53.424 --> 00:45:56.861
Denzil Holles, Arthur Haselrig, and William Strode,

00:45:56.861 --> 00:45:59.697
were known for opposing the king's policies

00:45:59.697 --> 00:46:02.100
and support for parliamentary rights.

00:46:02.100 --> 00:46:06.004
Charles I accused them of treason and other offenses,

00:46:06.004 --> 00:46:09.440
which led to a standoff between the king and parliament.

00:46:09.440 --> 00:46:13.745
On June 4th, 1642, Parliament members sent a demand letter

00:46:13.745 --> 00:46:17.448
to King Charles called the Nineteen Propositions,

00:46:17.448 --> 00:46:19.317
which would reform how Parliament

00:46:19.317 --> 00:46:21.186
and the monarchy would work.

00:46:21.186 --> 00:46:23.621
Parliament would grow in power if passed

00:46:23.621 --> 00:46:25.924
while the monarchy would be weakened.

00:46:25.924 --> 00:46:27.625
Within the propositions,

00:46:27.625 --> 00:46:30.295
Parliament is demanding various line items,

00:46:30.295 --> 00:46:33.831
such as number two, "Matters that concern the public

00:46:33.831 --> 00:46:35.934
must be debated in Parliament,

00:46:35.934 --> 00:46:39.437
not decided based upon the advice of private advisors."

00:46:39.437 --> 00:46:42.740
6, "Laws against Jesuits, Catholic priests,

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:46.244
and Catholic recusants must be strictly enforced."

00:46:46.244 --> 00:46:49.981
7, "The vote of Catholic lords shall be taken away,

00:46:49.981 --> 00:46:51.449
and the children of Catholics

00:46:51.449 --> 00:46:54.185
must receive a Protestant education."

00:46:54.185 --> 00:46:56.554
18, "Charles must clear

00:46:56.554 --> 00:46:58.890
the five members of the House of Commons,

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:00.725
along with Lord Kimbolton,

00:47:00.725 --> 00:47:02.427
of any wrongdoing."

00:47:02.427 --> 00:47:04.896
Though the Catholics in the Irish confederation

00:47:04.896 --> 00:47:06.831
may be loyal to Charles,

00:47:06.831 --> 00:47:10.268
Parliament was angered by Charles' blatant disregard

00:47:10.268 --> 00:47:11.903
for the Anglican church,

00:47:11.903 --> 00:47:15.039
so they demanded he change his stance.

00:47:15.039 --> 00:47:17.108
In response, Charles would write,

00:47:17.108 --> 00:47:19.844
"For all these reasons to all these demands,

00:47:19.844 --> 00:47:24.249
our answer is Nolumus Leges Angliae mutari.

00:47:24.249 --> 00:47:27.652
We are unwilling to change the laws of England."

00:47:27.652 --> 00:47:29.354
With tensions escalating,

00:47:29.354 --> 00:47:33.224
both sides began to gather support and muster their forces.

00:47:33.224 --> 00:47:36.261
By autumn, the rolling countryside near Edgehill

00:47:36.261 --> 00:47:38.830
became the stage for a pivotal clash

00:47:38.830 --> 00:47:42.433
between the Royalist forces loyal to King Charles I

00:47:42.433 --> 00:47:44.302
and the Parliamentarian troops

00:47:44.302 --> 00:47:47.572
supporting the cause of parliamentary supremacy.

00:47:47.572 --> 00:47:50.208
As the sun rose on October 23rd,

00:47:50.208 --> 00:47:52.377
the two sides arrayed against each other

00:47:52.377 --> 00:47:54.846
in a tense and charged atmosphere.

00:47:54.846 --> 00:47:58.316
The Royalist cavalry led by Prince Rupert of the Rhine

00:47:58.316 --> 00:48:01.552
was known for their daring and fearless charges.

00:48:01.552 --> 00:48:04.689
On the opposite, Robert Devereux, the Earl of Essex,

00:48:04.689 --> 00:48:06.291
a seasoned general,

00:48:06.291 --> 00:48:08.326
commanded the Parliamentarians.

00:48:08.326 --> 00:48:11.496
Rupert's Cavaliers launched a ferocious charge

00:48:11.496 --> 00:48:14.365
that shattered the parliamentarian left flank

00:48:14.365 --> 00:48:15.900
as the battle commenced.

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:18.503
The Royalists gained the upper hand.

00:48:18.503 --> 00:48:21.139
However, the Royalist infantry was unable

00:48:21.139 --> 00:48:23.841
to capitalize on the cavalry's success.

00:48:23.841 --> 00:48:26.944
The Parliamentarian forces, while in disarray,

00:48:26.944 --> 00:48:29.347
managed to regroup and counterattack.

00:48:29.347 --> 00:48:32.817
The battle raged with fierce hand-to-hand combat,

00:48:32.817 --> 00:48:36.054
pitting brother against brother and friend against friend.

00:48:36.054 --> 00:48:38.423
But yet, after two days of fighting,

00:48:38.423 --> 00:48:40.224
there was no decisive winner.

00:48:40.224 --> 00:48:42.060
The war was set in motion

00:48:42.060 --> 00:48:44.462
with neither side willing to relent.

00:48:44.462 --> 00:48:45.563
The following year,

00:48:45.563 --> 00:48:49.734
the Royalists, buoyed by early optimism, tasted victory.

00:48:49.734 --> 00:48:51.703
In the South, at Braddock Down,

00:48:51.703 --> 00:48:54.505
they swiftly defeated the Parliamentarians.

00:48:54.505 --> 00:48:56.607
Further success followed at Stratton,

00:48:56.607 --> 00:48:59.143
consolidating their hold over Cornwall.

00:48:59.143 --> 00:49:01.713
Riding this wave, Prince Rupert showcased

00:49:01.713 --> 00:49:04.682
his military prowess at Chalgrove Field.

00:49:04.682 --> 00:49:06.451
Even though the event was marred

00:49:06.451 --> 00:49:10.054
by the death of the Parliamentarian icon John Hampden,

00:49:10.054 --> 00:49:13.157
the Royalist cause seemed unstoppable,

00:49:13.157 --> 00:49:15.727
and this was further confirmed with their victories

00:49:15.727 --> 00:49:18.529
at Adwalton Moor and Roundway Down.

00:49:18.529 --> 00:49:19.764
By the end of the year,

00:49:19.764 --> 00:49:24.035
even the key city of Bristol had fallen into their hands.

00:49:24.035 --> 00:49:27.171
However, 1644 marked a shift.

00:49:27.171 --> 00:49:29.874
The Parliamentarians, learning from their defeats,

00:49:29.874 --> 00:49:31.309
mounted a challenge.

00:49:31.309 --> 00:49:33.845
Their efforts culminated at Marston Moor,

00:49:33.845 --> 00:49:37.515
a vast expanse that bore witness to a dramatic turnaround.

00:49:37.515 --> 00:49:39.283
Here, under the watchful eyes

00:49:39.283 --> 00:49:41.419
of generals like Oliver Cromwell,

00:49:41.419 --> 00:49:44.422
the Royalist forces faced a crushing defeat,

00:49:44.422 --> 00:49:47.091
relinquishing their grip over the north.

00:49:47.091 --> 00:49:49.360
Later that year, the two sides met again

00:49:49.360 --> 00:49:51.262
at the First Battle of Newbury.

00:49:51.262 --> 00:49:54.499
Much like Edgehill, neither could claim an outright win.

00:49:54.499 --> 00:49:57.902
However, a turning point was on the horizon,

00:49:57.902 --> 00:49:59.937
the Battle of Naseby.

00:49:59.937 --> 00:50:03.441
As dawn broke on June 14th, 1645,

00:50:03.441 --> 00:50:05.843
a palpable tension filled the air.

00:50:05.843 --> 00:50:09.680
Both armies faced each other a mere few miles apart.

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:11.949
The Royalists, confident and seasoned

00:50:11.949 --> 00:50:13.351
from earlier victories,

00:50:13.351 --> 00:50:15.253
anticipated another win.

00:50:15.253 --> 00:50:18.589
The Parliamentarians, however, had been reorganizing

00:50:18.589 --> 00:50:21.159
and were now more formidable than ever,

00:50:21.159 --> 00:50:24.362
especially with Oliver Cromwell's New Model Army,

00:50:24.362 --> 00:50:28.266
a force known for its discipline and strategic prowess.

00:50:28.266 --> 00:50:31.803
The battle commenced with the customary roar of cannons

00:50:31.803 --> 00:50:35.006
sending plumes of smoke into the morning sky.

00:50:35.006 --> 00:50:38.409
Initially, the Royalists seemed to have the upper hand

00:50:38.409 --> 00:50:40.645
with their horsemen charging effectively

00:50:40.645 --> 00:50:43.047
against the Parliamentarian flanks.

00:50:43.047 --> 00:50:45.716
But Cromwell, with his strategic acumen,

00:50:45.716 --> 00:50:49.287
had a card up his sleeve, his Ironsides,

00:50:49.287 --> 00:50:52.557
a cavalry regiment known for its staunch discipline

00:50:52.557 --> 00:50:54.525
and unwavering courage.

00:50:54.525 --> 00:50:57.762
As the Royalist cavalry believed they were gaining ground,

00:50:57.762 --> 00:50:59.964
they were met with a fierce counter charge

00:50:59.964 --> 00:51:01.566
by the Ironsides.

00:51:01.566 --> 00:51:04.368
The Parliamentarians, with resounding shouts

00:51:04.368 --> 00:51:06.437
and unparalleled coordination,

00:51:06.437 --> 00:51:08.105
began to turn the tide.

00:51:08.105 --> 00:51:10.208
Cromwell's forces pushed back,

00:51:10.208 --> 00:51:12.210
cutting through the Royalist ranks,

00:51:12.210 --> 00:51:16.314
capturing King Charles himself and making him a prisoner.

00:51:16.314 --> 00:51:19.217
Charles was later put on trial for high treason.

00:51:19.217 --> 00:51:20.551
In Westminster Hall,

00:51:20.551 --> 00:51:22.787
Charles the first defended his actions,

00:51:22.787 --> 00:51:25.356
but the trial ended with a guilty verdict.

00:51:25.356 --> 00:51:26.691
On a winter morning,

00:51:26.691 --> 00:51:29.927
the fallen monarch faced the executioner's blade,

00:51:29.927 --> 00:51:32.463
marking the shift from absolutism

00:51:32.463 --> 00:51:34.765
to a new era of governance,

00:51:34.765 --> 00:51:38.102
the era of Oliver Cromwell.

00:51:38.102 --> 00:51:41.205
(bright music)

00:51:41.205 --> 00:51:43.341
Oliver Cromwell was a Puritan,

00:51:43.341 --> 00:51:45.776
and, like his brethren in Massachusetts,

00:51:45.776 --> 00:51:49.280
believed that the Anglican Church was corrupted by Charles

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:51.082
and the way of the Royalists.

00:51:51.082 --> 00:51:54.652
So in the new parliament, known as the Rump Parliament,

00:51:54.652 --> 00:51:56.721
Cromwell was able to be a general

00:51:56.721 --> 00:51:58.890
to attack the Irish Confederacy.

00:51:58.890 --> 00:52:01.058
In his mind, the Catholic belief

00:52:01.058 --> 00:52:03.561
was denying the primacy of the Bible

00:52:03.561 --> 00:52:05.263
and needed to be quelled.

00:52:05.263 --> 00:52:09.467
After he landed in Dublin on August 15th, 1649,

00:52:09.467 --> 00:52:11.769
Cromwell took the fortified port towns

00:52:11.769 --> 00:52:13.671
of Drogheda and Wexford

00:52:13.671 --> 00:52:16.507
to secure logistical supplies from England.

00:52:16.507 --> 00:52:20.077
At the Siege of Drogheda in September 1649,

00:52:20.077 --> 00:52:23.481
his troops killed nearly 3,500 people

00:52:23.481 --> 00:52:25.249
after the town's capture,

00:52:25.249 --> 00:52:28.586
around 2,700 Royalist soldiers,

00:52:28.586 --> 00:52:31.088
including some civilians, prisoners,

00:52:31.088 --> 00:52:33.057
and Roman Catholic priests.

00:52:33.057 --> 00:52:36.661
In October, another massacre took place in Wexford

00:52:36.661 --> 00:52:41.666
and killed 2,000 Irish troops and 1,500 Irish civilians.

00:52:41.699 --> 00:52:44.368
Wexford was burned to ashes.

00:52:44.368 --> 00:52:47.104
Cromwell left Ireland in May 1650,

00:52:47.104 --> 00:52:49.807
after Scotland proclaimed Charles II,

00:52:49.807 --> 00:52:52.376
the son of Charles I, to be King.

00:52:52.376 --> 00:52:54.812
With this act of so-called treason,

00:52:54.812 --> 00:52:57.848
Cromwell felt the only action was war.

00:52:57.848 --> 00:52:59.116
On September 3rd, 1650,

00:53:00.284 --> 00:53:04.355
unexpectedly, Cromwell smashed the main Scottish army

00:53:04.355 --> 00:53:06.023
at the Battle of Dunbar,

00:53:06.023 --> 00:53:09.126
killing 4,000 Scottish soldiers,

00:53:09.126 --> 00:53:11.629
taking another 10,000 prisoners,

00:53:11.629 --> 00:53:15.232
and then capturing the Scottish capital of Edinburgh.

00:53:15.232 --> 00:53:18.502
The following year, Charles II and his Scottish allies

00:53:18.502 --> 00:53:21.238
attempted to invade England and capture London

00:53:21.238 --> 00:53:23.741
while Cromwell was engaged in Scotland.

00:53:23.741 --> 00:53:25.610
Cromwell followed the south

00:53:25.610 --> 00:53:29.647
and caught them at Worcester on September 3rd, 1651,

00:53:29.647 --> 00:53:31.282
and his forces destroyed

00:53:31.282 --> 00:53:34.385
the last major Scottish Royalist army

00:53:34.385 --> 00:53:36.320
at the Battle of Worcester.

00:53:36.320 --> 00:53:39.256
Under the Generals Henry Ireton and Edmund Ludlow

00:53:39.256 --> 00:53:40.458
back in Ireland,

00:53:40.458 --> 00:53:43.461
the Irish were sieged into oblivion.

00:53:43.461 --> 00:53:45.930
The last Catholic held town, Galway,

00:53:45.930 --> 00:53:48.532
surrendered in April 1652,

00:53:48.532 --> 00:53:51.602
and the latest Irish Catholic troops capitulated

00:53:51.602 --> 00:53:54.972
on April 1653 in County Cavan.

00:53:54.972 --> 00:53:57.141
In the wake of the Commonwealth's conquest

00:53:57.141 --> 00:53:58.676
of the island of Ireland,

00:53:58.676 --> 00:54:02.146
the public practice of Roman Catholicism was banned

00:54:02.146 --> 00:54:04.915
and Catholic priests were killed when captured.

00:54:04.915 --> 00:54:07.451
All Catholic-owned land was confiscated

00:54:07.451 --> 00:54:11.389
under the Act for the Settlement of Ireland of 1652

00:54:11.389 --> 00:54:13.891
and given to Scottish and English settlers,

00:54:13.891 --> 00:54:15.826
Parliament's financial creditors,

00:54:15.826 --> 00:54:17.962
and parliamentary soldiers.

00:54:17.962 --> 00:54:21.132
Presbyterianism was deemed illegal in Scotland

00:54:21.132 --> 00:54:24.268
and they were forced to be a part of the Anglican church.

00:54:24.268 --> 00:54:29.073
Oliver Cromwell was decorated as Lord Protectorate in 1653.

00:54:29.073 --> 00:54:30.307
With his position,

00:54:30.307 --> 00:54:32.410
he tried to make the rest of the British Isles

00:54:32.410 --> 00:54:33.944
more like England.

00:54:33.944 --> 00:54:36.480
He hated the Scottish clan system

00:54:36.480 --> 00:54:38.949
up in the partial jungle of the Highlands,

00:54:38.949 --> 00:54:40.685
so he destroyed it.

00:54:40.685 --> 00:54:43.054
Before Cromwell, there was no idea

00:54:43.054 --> 00:54:45.556
of land ownership in the Highlands.

00:54:45.556 --> 00:54:47.258
A clan would live on the land

00:54:47.258 --> 00:54:48.693
and together they would survive

00:54:48.693 --> 00:54:50.594
off the resources communally.

00:54:50.594 --> 00:54:52.563
Together, they would have a chief.

00:54:52.563 --> 00:54:54.932
However, that would often change.

00:54:54.932 --> 00:54:58.869
However, Cromwell gave the titles of land to these chiefs,

00:54:58.869 --> 00:55:01.706
saying that they individually owned the land

00:55:01.706 --> 00:55:03.441
rather than the whole group.

00:55:03.441 --> 00:55:06.877
This, in turn, created a Scottish noble class

00:55:06.877 --> 00:55:09.914
of those who arbitrarily got the deed to the land

00:55:09.914 --> 00:55:13.984
and built a castle of impoverished non-land-owning Scotsman.

00:55:13.984 --> 00:55:17.855
This changed the entire function of Scottish society.

00:55:17.855 --> 00:55:20.024
The landowners wanted to make a profit

00:55:20.024 --> 00:55:22.126
rather than survive as a community.

00:55:22.126 --> 00:55:23.994
Following English ideals,

00:55:23.994 --> 00:55:26.197
the landowners wanted to make as much profit

00:55:26.197 --> 00:55:27.932
as humanly possible,

00:55:27.932 --> 00:55:32.002
so they started cutting down giant swaths of Scottish trees.

00:55:32.002 --> 00:55:34.672
This once prospering rainforest

00:55:34.672 --> 00:55:38.709
turned into a hilly, grassy field seemingly overnight.

00:55:38.709 --> 00:55:40.344
Then came the sheep.

00:55:40.344 --> 00:55:43.781
Over time, with these bare grass mountainous fields,

00:55:43.781 --> 00:55:46.383
the landowners realized they could make more profit

00:55:46.383 --> 00:55:48.719
by raising sheep than by farming.

00:55:48.719 --> 00:55:51.989
So sheep were given endless land to graze

00:55:51.989 --> 00:55:53.357
while the old clan members

00:55:53.357 --> 00:55:57.027
were forced to work parts of the land and were impoverished.

00:55:57.027 --> 00:55:59.997
Cromwell thought that making Scotland more English

00:55:59.997 --> 00:56:02.266
would be more civilized and enlightened,

00:56:02.266 --> 00:56:05.302
that English society is just so perfect

00:56:05.302 --> 00:56:07.972
that it must be spread all across the world

00:56:07.972 --> 00:56:09.740
to truly help those people

00:56:09.740 --> 00:56:12.977
who live in a world filled with cultural differences,

00:56:12.977 --> 00:56:16.447
that the English way is the only way.

00:56:16.447 --> 00:56:19.216
Cromwell thought he was doing Scotland a favor,

00:56:19.216 --> 00:56:23.621
but some see it as he ruined their entire society instead.

00:56:23.621 --> 00:56:26.724
He wouldn't be the last Brit to do just that.

00:56:27.625 --> 00:56:30.594
While most of Cromwell focused on the British Isles,

00:56:30.594 --> 00:56:32.196
he still wanted to have control

00:56:32.196 --> 00:56:34.431
against the Spanish in South America,

00:56:34.431 --> 00:56:38.369
so he launched the Western Design armada in the Caribbean.

00:56:38.369 --> 00:56:42.006
In April 1655, General Robert Venables

00:56:42.006 --> 00:56:43.574
led the English armada

00:56:43.574 --> 00:56:47.945
in an attack on Spain's fort at Santo Domingo, Hispaniola.

00:56:47.945 --> 00:56:50.014
However, the Spanish quickly defended

00:56:50.014 --> 00:56:53.617
against this poorly executed siege of Santo Domingo

00:56:53.617 --> 00:56:57.354
and the English troops were soon decimated by disease.

00:56:57.354 --> 00:56:59.723
Venables, not wanting to be a failure,

00:56:59.723 --> 00:57:02.359
went to the only Spanish colony in the area

00:57:02.359 --> 00:57:05.095
that did not have defensive capabilities,

00:57:05.095 --> 00:57:08.365
the sparsely populated island of Jamaica.

00:57:08.365 --> 00:57:13.370
In May 1655, around 7,000 English soldiers landed

00:57:13.370 --> 00:57:15.639
near Jamaica's Spanish Town capital.

00:57:15.639 --> 00:57:18.042
The English invasion force soon overwhelmed

00:57:18.042 --> 00:57:20.444
the 2,500 residents

00:57:20.444 --> 00:57:23.147
and it became an English colony.

00:57:23.147 --> 00:57:26.016
Of course, the Spanish wanted to regain the island,

00:57:26.016 --> 00:57:28.018
but were ultimately never able

00:57:28.018 --> 00:57:30.321
to gain a foothold in the island.

00:57:30.321 --> 00:57:33.224
Cromwell used the island to send prisoners of war

00:57:33.224 --> 00:57:35.392
and anyone who disobeyed his rule

00:57:35.392 --> 00:57:37.595
by making them indentured servants,

00:57:37.595 --> 00:57:41.098
forced to help grow the island's sugarcane production.

00:57:41.098 --> 00:57:43.968
However, tropical disease and harsh conditions

00:57:43.968 --> 00:57:46.270
made it hard for the colony to grow.

00:57:46.270 --> 00:57:50.274
In the year 1660, the reign of Cromwell was over

00:57:50.274 --> 00:57:53.911
and the colonization race was on under new leadership.

00:57:54.812 --> 00:57:57.514
(dramatic music)

00:57:57.514 --> 00:57:59.884
King Charles II was given power

00:57:59.884 --> 00:58:02.286
and the British monarchy was restored.

00:58:02.286 --> 00:58:04.221
Charles II was dead set

00:58:04.221 --> 00:58:06.957
on bringing England to the rest of the world.

00:58:06.957 --> 00:58:08.425
In Africa, he established

00:58:08.425 --> 00:58:11.562
the Company of Royal Adventurers Trading into Africa.

00:58:11.562 --> 00:58:13.430
Charles II granted the company

00:58:13.430 --> 00:58:15.866
a complete monopoly of the gold trade,

00:58:15.866 --> 00:58:20.871
and in 1663, access to the ever lucrative slave trade.

00:58:20.871 --> 00:58:22.172
While in the Americas,

00:58:22.172 --> 00:58:24.942
Charles established the province of Carolina,

00:58:24.942 --> 00:58:26.710
which he named after himself.

00:58:26.710 --> 00:58:29.780
The charter gave eight English nobles land access

00:58:29.780 --> 00:58:32.449
to lands that were part of modern-day Alabama,

00:58:32.449 --> 00:58:34.952
Florida, Georgia, Mississippi,

00:58:34.952 --> 00:58:38.322
North Carolina, South Carolina, and Tennessee.

00:58:38.322 --> 00:58:39.690
It was set up to be a buffer

00:58:39.690 --> 00:58:42.092
between the growing Spanish land grab

00:58:42.092 --> 00:58:43.694
in the swamps of Florida.

00:58:43.694 --> 00:58:46.230
Back in Africa, the English weren't the only ones

00:58:46.230 --> 00:58:49.433
trying to pillage Africa for their resources.

00:58:49.433 --> 00:58:51.802
The Dutch had established many settlements

00:58:51.802 --> 00:58:53.570
across the lucrative coast

00:58:53.570 --> 00:58:55.639
and the English did not like it.

00:58:55.639 --> 00:58:57.875
Captain Robert Holmes was given authority

00:58:57.875 --> 00:59:00.411
to take over any Dutch fort he could.

00:59:00.411 --> 00:59:03.981
So on January 22nd, 1664,

00:59:03.981 --> 00:59:05.883
he took the Fort of Goree.

00:59:05.883 --> 00:59:08.652
On March 28th, he took over Walcheren.

00:59:08.652 --> 00:59:11.855
On April 10th, he captured the principal Dutch base,

00:59:11.855 --> 00:59:14.591
Cape Coast Castle in West Africa.

00:59:14.591 --> 00:59:17.361
Slightly after, in America, the English were looking

00:59:17.361 --> 00:59:20.397
to overtake the Dutch colony of New Amsterdam,

00:59:20.397 --> 00:59:23.000
situated on the southern tip of Manhattan.

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:25.703
On May 25th, 1664,

00:59:25.703 --> 00:59:28.038
Colonel Richard Nichols set out from Portsmouth

00:59:28.038 --> 00:59:31.375
with four warships and 300 soldiers.

00:59:31.375 --> 00:59:33.577
When they arrived on August 27th,

00:59:33.577 --> 00:59:36.580
he sent Dutch director Governor Peter Stuyvesant

00:59:36.580 --> 00:59:39.216
a letter of lenient terms of surrender.

00:59:39.216 --> 00:59:42.019
The Dutch colonists would still be guaranteed possession

00:59:42.019 --> 00:59:43.454
of their property rights,

00:59:43.454 --> 00:59:45.255
enjoyment of religious freedom,

00:59:45.255 --> 00:59:47.658
and that all pubs would remain open.

00:59:47.658 --> 00:59:48.859
They would not have to follow

00:59:48.859 --> 00:59:52.029
the Puritanical rules of Massachusetts.

00:59:52.029 --> 00:59:54.298
Rather, they would be their own colony.

00:59:54.298 --> 00:59:56.600
The people of New Amsterdam accepted

00:59:56.600 --> 00:59:59.203
and the colony was renamed to New York.

00:59:59.203 --> 01:00:01.171
The Dutch in Europe were unhappy

01:00:01.171 --> 01:00:02.873
with this English conquering,

01:00:02.873 --> 01:00:04.641
so they sent out experienced

01:00:04.641 --> 01:00:07.044
Naval Lieutenant Admiral Michiel de Ruyter

01:00:07.044 --> 01:00:08.712
to defeat the English.

01:00:08.712 --> 01:00:10.547
First he started in Africa

01:00:10.547 --> 01:00:13.550
where he quickly re-conquered all former Dutch forts

01:00:13.550 --> 01:00:16.387
the English conquered, except Cape Coast.

01:00:16.387 --> 01:00:19.223
After that, he sailed over to the Americas.

01:00:19.223 --> 01:00:23.327
In April 1665, he arrived off the coast of Barbados,

01:00:23.327 --> 01:00:26.163
destroying various English ships on the way.

01:00:26.163 --> 01:00:28.365
However, his army was weakened,

01:00:28.365 --> 01:00:31.168
and even though he was ordered to retake New York,

01:00:31.168 --> 01:00:33.570
he knew that his fleet could not handle it.

01:00:33.570 --> 01:00:36.340
Fighting that battle would result in imminent death.

01:00:36.340 --> 01:00:40.310
So in 1665, he went back to the Netherlands.

01:00:40.310 --> 01:00:43.714
In 1667, the Treaty of Breda was signed

01:00:43.714 --> 01:00:45.816
where the English would have an absolute claim

01:00:45.816 --> 01:00:48.052
of the former New Netherlands,

01:00:48.052 --> 01:00:51.422
while the Dutch would regain control of the colony Surinam,

01:00:51.422 --> 01:00:53.157
which is in South America.

01:00:53.157 --> 01:00:55.025
With the Netherlands out of the picture,

01:00:55.025 --> 01:00:57.828
the path to further colonization in the Americas

01:00:57.828 --> 01:00:59.329
was at its forefront,

01:00:59.329 --> 01:01:03.067
but it wasn't without its controversies,

01:01:03.067 --> 01:01:03.901
(dramatic music)

01:01:03.901 --> 01:01:06.303
because up in the no man's land of Canada

01:01:06.303 --> 01:01:09.740
laid the unambitious French colony of Montreal.

01:01:09.740 --> 01:01:11.241
The French were more hesitant

01:01:11.241 --> 01:01:13.911
to expand outside their predefined areas.

01:01:13.911 --> 01:01:16.313
They had their places where they would hunt furs

01:01:16.313 --> 01:01:18.182
and they were to stay on that path.

01:01:18.182 --> 01:01:20.884
The French sustained all their colonial efforts

01:01:20.884 --> 01:01:23.987
from fur trading, which was in high demand in Europe.

01:01:23.987 --> 01:01:26.457
However, two French fur traders,

01:01:26.457 --> 01:01:29.793
Pierre-Esprit Radisson and Medard des Groseilliers,

01:01:29.793 --> 01:01:31.862
learned from the native Cree peoples

01:01:31.862 --> 01:01:34.665
that the ultimate place for premium fur pellets

01:01:34.665 --> 01:01:37.701
was in the north and west of Lake Superior.

01:01:37.701 --> 01:01:39.837
The duo knew their opportunity,

01:01:39.837 --> 01:01:41.371
and if they wanted to be rich,

01:01:41.371 --> 01:01:44.274
they would have to go against the will of the French.

01:01:44.274 --> 01:01:47.077
As they set off into this mysterious land,

01:01:47.077 --> 01:01:49.046
most thought they wouldn't make it,

01:01:49.046 --> 01:01:51.415
but when they returned a year later to Montreal

01:01:51.415 --> 01:01:52.883
with premium furs,

01:01:52.883 --> 01:01:55.986
evidence of the potential of the Hudson Bay region,

01:01:55.986 --> 01:01:58.188
they were arrested by French authorities

01:01:58.188 --> 01:02:00.891
for trading without a license and fined

01:02:00.891 --> 01:02:03.727
and their furs were confiscated by the government.

01:02:03.727 --> 01:02:07.264
Determined to establish trade in the Hudson Bay area,

01:02:07.264 --> 01:02:09.500
Radisson and Groseilliers approached a group

01:02:09.500 --> 01:02:12.870
of English colonial merchants in Boston, Massachusetts,

01:02:12.870 --> 01:02:15.239
to help finance their explorations.

01:02:15.239 --> 01:02:16.740
Eventually, the two met

01:02:16.740 --> 01:02:19.143
and gained the sponsorship of Prince Rupert,

01:02:19.143 --> 01:02:21.578
the cousin of King Charles II.

01:02:21.578 --> 01:02:25.983
In 1668, the English expedition acquired two ships,

01:02:25.983 --> 01:02:27.951
the Nonsuch and the Eaglet,

01:02:27.951 --> 01:02:30.621
to explore possible trade into Hudson Bay.

01:02:30.621 --> 01:02:32.756
Grosser sailed on the Nonsuch

01:02:32.756 --> 01:02:35.425
commanded by Captain Zachariah Gillam,

01:02:35.425 --> 01:02:38.662
while the Eaglet was commanded by Captain William Stannard

01:02:38.662 --> 01:02:40.364
and accompanied by Radisson.

01:02:40.364 --> 01:02:44.001
On June 5th, 1668, both ships left port

01:02:44.001 --> 01:02:45.302
at Deptford, England,

01:02:45.302 --> 01:02:47.271
but the Eaglet was forced to turn back

01:02:47.271 --> 01:02:48.805
off the coast of Ireland.

01:02:48.805 --> 01:02:51.308
The Nonsuch continued to James Bay,

01:02:51.308 --> 01:02:53.510
the southern portion of Hudson Bay,

01:02:53.510 --> 01:02:56.346
where its explorers founded in 1668

01:02:56.346 --> 01:02:59.716
the first fort on Hudson Bay, Charles Fort,

01:02:59.716 --> 01:03:01.552
at the mouth of the Rupert River.

01:03:01.552 --> 01:03:03.987
After a successful trading expedition

01:03:03.987 --> 01:03:06.590
over the winter of 1669,

01:03:06.590 --> 01:03:10.427
Nonsuch returned to England on October 9th, 1669,

01:03:10.427 --> 01:03:12.529
with the first cargo of fur

01:03:12.529 --> 01:03:14.798
resulting from trade in Hudson Bay.

01:03:14.798 --> 01:03:16.366
The bulk of this haul was sold

01:03:16.366 --> 01:03:19.670
to London's most prominent furrier, Thomas Glover,

01:03:19.670 --> 01:03:22.806
for 1,233 pounds.

01:03:22.806 --> 01:03:24.608
Calculating for inflation,

01:03:24.608 --> 01:03:28.545
the value of the furs would be worth 188,000

01:03:28.545 --> 01:03:30.214
in today's pounds.

01:03:30.214 --> 01:03:31.982
After establishing viability

01:03:31.982 --> 01:03:33.884
and profitability in the company,

01:03:33.884 --> 01:03:37.221
King Charles II granted a monopoly over the region,

01:03:37.221 --> 01:03:40.991
drained by all rivers and streams flowing into Hudson Bay,

01:03:40.991 --> 01:03:42.960
to the Hudson Bay Company,

01:03:42.960 --> 01:03:46.630
a company that still exists today.

01:03:46.630 --> 01:03:48.198
(dramatic music)

01:03:48.198 --> 01:03:49.132
While back in New England,

01:03:49.132 --> 01:03:50.834
the English colony started to grow

01:03:50.834 --> 01:03:53.203
at an increasingly accelerated rate.

01:03:53.203 --> 01:03:56.540
In 1624, the Massachusetts Bay Colony

01:03:56.540 --> 01:03:59.176
only was home to 180 people.

01:03:59.176 --> 01:04:04.181
Now, in 1675, it was the home of 64,000.

01:04:04.348 --> 01:04:05.482
With more people,

01:04:05.482 --> 01:04:09.353
the demand for more space, resources, and food increased.

01:04:09.353 --> 01:04:11.321
So the colonists began expanding

01:04:11.321 --> 01:04:13.056
outside their tiny settlements

01:04:13.056 --> 01:04:14.558
to produce what they needed.

01:04:14.558 --> 01:04:16.493
Their defacto capital, Plymouth,

01:04:16.493 --> 01:04:19.229
was right in the center of the ancestral lands

01:04:19.229 --> 01:04:23.133
of the Wampanoag Confederacy, a Native American tribe.

01:04:23.133 --> 01:04:26.637
At first, the Wampanoag were friendly towards pilgrims,

01:04:26.637 --> 01:04:29.640
but their relationship began to sour over time.

01:04:29.640 --> 01:04:32.542
They tried to negotiate territorial boundaries.

01:04:32.542 --> 01:04:34.611
However, their fundamental differences

01:04:34.611 --> 01:04:38.515
in how land and property worked made it nearly impossible.

01:04:38.515 --> 01:04:40.417
The English viewed land as something

01:04:40.417 --> 01:04:42.986
an individual with the right deed could own

01:04:42.986 --> 01:04:46.123
while the Natives believed land was a communal resource

01:04:46.123 --> 01:04:47.491
to be shared for all.

01:04:47.491 --> 01:04:51.561
So when the English tried to buy land from the Natives,

01:04:51.561 --> 01:04:54.698
it was met with confusion and a lack of understanding.

01:04:54.698 --> 01:04:56.500
For all the Wampanoag knew,

01:04:56.500 --> 01:04:59.169
their new neighbors stole their land unjustly.

01:04:59.169 --> 01:05:03.940
In 1675, a single event ignited the powder keg.

01:05:03.940 --> 01:05:07.711
Three Wampanoag men were executed by English authorities,

01:05:07.711 --> 01:05:08.945
accused of the murder

01:05:08.945 --> 01:05:12.816
of a Christianized Native American named John Sassamon.

01:05:12.816 --> 01:05:15.652
This series of executions caused outrage

01:05:15.652 --> 01:05:17.120
among the Wampanoags,

01:05:17.120 --> 01:05:20.957
led by Metacom, with the English name of King Philip.

01:05:20.957 --> 01:05:22.793
Metacom led his warriors

01:05:22.793 --> 01:05:24.594
and attacked the Plymouth colony,

01:05:24.594 --> 01:05:25.829
starting at Swansea

01:05:25.829 --> 01:05:28.999
and going to Taunton, Brookfield, and Deerfield.

01:05:28.999 --> 01:05:31.902
The winter months did little to quell the conflict.

01:05:31.902 --> 01:05:34.137
Both sides endured harsh conditions,

01:05:34.137 --> 01:05:37.307
facing disease, starvation, and exposure.

01:05:37.307 --> 01:05:40.110
Battles raged with Native American tribes

01:05:40.110 --> 01:05:43.580
joining Metacom's alliance against the colonists.

01:05:43.580 --> 01:05:45.615
The English launched counterattacks,

01:05:45.615 --> 01:05:48.518
leading to the infamous Battle of Great Swamp,

01:05:48.518 --> 01:05:50.787
where a Narragansett fort was captured

01:05:50.787 --> 01:05:53.523
with heavy casualties on both sides.

01:05:53.523 --> 01:05:55.459
As the conflict escalated,

01:05:55.459 --> 01:05:58.395
alliances shifted like sand in the wind.

01:05:58.395 --> 01:06:00.530
English authorities negotiated a treaty

01:06:00.530 --> 01:06:01.898
with the Mohawk tribe

01:06:01.898 --> 01:06:04.067
hoping to gain a strategic advantage

01:06:04.067 --> 01:06:06.069
against Metacom's forces.

01:06:06.069 --> 01:06:09.172
Native American villages were razed, lives lost,

01:06:09.172 --> 01:06:10.774
and families torn apart.

01:06:10.774 --> 01:06:13.610
Metacom's leadership kept the alliance together,

01:06:13.610 --> 01:06:17.647
but his death in 1676 marked a turning point.

01:06:17.647 --> 01:06:18.682
He was assassinated

01:06:18.682 --> 01:06:21.651
by one of his best friends, John Alderman,

01:06:21.651 --> 01:06:23.954
who was known as the praying Indian

01:06:23.954 --> 01:06:26.123
because of his Christian beliefs.

01:06:26.123 --> 01:06:27.491
With Metacom's death,

01:06:27.491 --> 01:06:31.228
the Native American alliance faltered, resistance dwindled,

01:06:31.228 --> 01:06:33.330
and the war began to wind down.

01:06:33.330 --> 01:06:37.000
In August 1676, the war officially ended,

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:39.169
leaving both Native American communities

01:06:39.169 --> 01:06:41.872
and English settlements devastated.

01:06:41.872 --> 01:06:44.608
Lives were lost, property destroyed,

01:06:44.608 --> 01:06:46.943
and cultures forever altered.

01:06:46.943 --> 01:06:49.212
The war ended with the Treaty of Casco,

01:06:49.212 --> 01:06:52.649
which allowed the English to remain on all native lands.

01:06:52.649 --> 01:06:54.284
However, they were required

01:06:54.284 --> 01:06:57.487
to pay a light tribute of one peck of corn

01:06:57.487 --> 01:07:00.757
per English family settled on native land.

01:07:00.757 --> 01:07:03.927
A peck is equivalent to two dry gallons

01:07:03.927 --> 01:07:05.996
or 16 dry pints,

01:07:05.996 --> 01:07:08.498
a relatively insignificant amount

01:07:08.498 --> 01:07:10.801
for the farmers of Massachusetts Bay.

01:07:11.935 --> 01:07:13.437
While back in England,

01:07:13.437 --> 01:07:15.572
another religious group was challenging

01:07:15.572 --> 01:07:18.642
the tenets of Anglicanism, the Quakers.

01:07:18.642 --> 01:07:20.977
One of their most controversial ideas

01:07:20.977 --> 01:07:23.079
was the concept of inner light,

01:07:23.079 --> 01:07:25.615
which states that there is a divine spark

01:07:25.615 --> 01:07:27.150
within each individual

01:07:27.150 --> 01:07:30.053
that allows for direct communication with God

01:07:30.053 --> 01:07:33.623
without needing a state appointed bishop or a king.

01:07:33.623 --> 01:07:36.293
They also rejected all formal titles

01:07:36.293 --> 01:07:38.962
spanning from Your Highness to mother.

01:07:38.962 --> 01:07:42.065
Every Quaker was to be referred to by their first name

01:07:42.065 --> 01:07:43.900
regardless of status.

01:07:43.900 --> 01:07:47.137
King Charles would be referred to as Charles.

01:07:47.137 --> 01:07:50.340
Quaker kids would call their mother by their first name.

01:07:50.340 --> 01:07:53.910
This mere concept of rejecting hierarchical titles

01:07:53.910 --> 01:07:56.713
put them on the outskirts of British society.

01:07:56.713 --> 01:07:59.115
So William Penn made it his mission

01:07:59.115 --> 01:08:01.384
to find a place for his church to go.

01:08:01.384 --> 01:08:04.221
It also helped that King Charles II was indebted

01:08:04.221 --> 01:08:07.958
to William Penn's father for 16,000 pounds

01:08:07.958 --> 01:08:11.261
or 2.8 million pounds today.

01:08:11.261 --> 01:08:12.929
Instead of receiving cash,

01:08:12.929 --> 01:08:15.332
William Penn asked for land in the New World

01:08:15.332 --> 01:08:17.133
to house his fellow Quakers.

01:08:17.133 --> 01:08:20.804
On March 4th, 1681, Charles signed the order,

01:08:20.804 --> 01:08:23.306
creating the Colony of Pennsylvania.

01:08:23.306 --> 01:08:26.510
When William Penn arrived at his colony on the ship Welcome

01:08:26.510 --> 01:08:28.545
in October 1682,

01:08:28.545 --> 01:08:30.013
he went to a tiny settlement

01:08:30.013 --> 01:08:32.883
and named it in Greek Phileo Adelphos,

01:08:32.883 --> 01:08:34.718
which would translate into English

01:08:34.718 --> 01:08:36.620
the city of brotherly love,

01:08:36.620 --> 01:08:38.054
a city where all people

01:08:38.054 --> 01:08:40.257
regardless of race, creed, religion,

01:08:40.257 --> 01:08:42.459
or gender could prosper.

01:08:42.459 --> 01:08:45.862
A place where no one would be unfairly prosecuted.

01:08:45.862 --> 01:08:49.065
A place, in theory, where a white man and a Black man

01:08:49.065 --> 01:08:50.867
could shake hands as equals.

01:08:50.867 --> 01:08:54.404
As Penn would refer to it, this was a holy experiment

01:08:54.404 --> 01:08:57.374
because he believed in a famous Quaker tenet

01:08:57.374 --> 01:09:01.411
that all people are equal under the eyes of God.

01:09:01.411 --> 01:09:04.314
(dramatic music)

01:09:04.314 --> 01:09:07.884
However, the English empire was in turmoil once again

01:09:07.884 --> 01:09:11.888
after King Charles II died in 1685.

01:09:11.888 --> 01:09:15.926
His successor, James II, was a staunch Roman Catholic

01:09:15.926 --> 01:09:17.060
who took the throne.

01:09:17.060 --> 01:09:18.194
He thought it was important

01:09:18.194 --> 01:09:21.231
to grant rights of religious freedom across the land.

01:09:21.231 --> 01:09:24.034
However, the Anglican majority were livid

01:09:24.034 --> 01:09:27.437
when James appointed Catholics to powerful positions,

01:09:27.437 --> 01:09:28.939
violating the Test Act

01:09:28.939 --> 01:09:32.175
which made that very act illegal to do so.

01:09:32.175 --> 01:09:35.912
But the birth of an heir truly set the kingdom on edge.

01:09:35.912 --> 01:09:38.748
James's second wife, Mary of Modena,

01:09:38.748 --> 01:09:39.983
bore him a son,

01:09:39.983 --> 01:09:41.484
a Catholic heir who threatened

01:09:41.484 --> 01:09:43.320
to establish a line of monarchs

01:09:43.320 --> 01:09:45.322
devoted to the Catholic faith.

01:09:45.322 --> 01:09:48.358
Fears of a Catholic dynasty ran rampant,

01:09:48.358 --> 01:09:51.328
shaking the Protestant establishment's core.

01:09:51.328 --> 01:09:54.531
In the shadows, a group of nobles and political leaders

01:09:54.531 --> 01:09:56.533
known as the Immortal Seven

01:09:56.533 --> 01:09:58.368
whispered their concerns.

01:09:58.368 --> 01:10:01.671
They felt the kingdom was hurling towards absolutism

01:10:01.671 --> 01:10:04.641
with the monarchy overshadowing the power of parliament

01:10:04.641 --> 01:10:05.909
and the rule of law.

01:10:05.909 --> 01:10:09.379
They knew something had to be done to protect their beliefs.

01:10:09.379 --> 01:10:11.881
Their hopes turned to Prince William of Orange,

01:10:11.881 --> 01:10:13.850
James's Protestant son-in-law,

01:10:13.850 --> 01:10:16.052
to quell his father-in-law's desire

01:10:16.052 --> 01:10:17.821
for religious acceptance.

01:10:17.821 --> 01:10:21.891
In 1688, William's fleet sailed to the shores of England.

01:10:21.891 --> 01:10:25.495
His arrival was met with a surprising lack of resistance

01:10:25.495 --> 01:10:28.865
as many of James's supporters defected to his side.

01:10:28.865 --> 01:10:31.701
James II's grasp on power weakened

01:10:31.701 --> 01:10:33.370
as his supporters dwindled.

01:10:33.370 --> 01:10:34.771
Fearing for his safety,

01:10:34.771 --> 01:10:36.806
he fled to France in the dead of night,

01:10:36.806 --> 01:10:40.176
leaving a kingdom in turmoil and an uncertain future.

01:10:40.176 --> 01:10:41.478
With the throne vacant,

01:10:41.478 --> 01:10:44.914
William and Mary, Protestantism's chosen protectors,

01:10:44.914 --> 01:10:46.950
accepted the leadership mantle.

01:10:46.950 --> 01:10:50.453
Parliament seized the moment to enact lasting change.

01:10:50.453 --> 01:10:53.456
In 1689, they passed the Bill of Rights,

01:10:53.456 --> 01:10:56.526
a cornerstone of constitutional principles

01:10:56.526 --> 01:10:58.895
that established the supremacy of parliament

01:10:58.895 --> 01:11:00.163
over the monarchy,

01:11:00.163 --> 01:11:01.731
curbed the monarch's power,

01:11:01.731 --> 01:11:04.067
and protected individual rights.

01:11:04.067 --> 01:11:07.003
However, once the news spread to America,

01:11:07.003 --> 01:11:09.305
the Protestants were ready to revolt.

01:11:09.305 --> 01:11:13.743
In April 1689, news of the glorious revolution in England

01:11:13.743 --> 01:11:15.712
reached the American colonies.

01:11:15.712 --> 01:11:18.114
Protestant settlers in New York revolted

01:11:18.114 --> 01:11:20.717
against the Catholic Governor Jacob Leisler,

01:11:20.717 --> 01:11:23.086
seizing control of Fort James.

01:11:23.086 --> 01:11:25.522
They established a provisional government

01:11:25.522 --> 01:11:27.390
in the name of William and Mary.

01:11:27.390 --> 01:11:29.759
Around the same time in Massachusetts,

01:11:29.759 --> 01:11:31.828
the English in Boston overthrew

01:11:31.828 --> 01:11:34.631
the Catholic Governor Sir Edmund Andros,

01:11:34.631 --> 01:11:37.267
who had imposed unpopular policies.

01:11:37.267 --> 01:11:38.635
They arrested Andros

01:11:38.635 --> 01:11:41.304
and restored their previous political structure,

01:11:41.304 --> 01:11:44.007
declaring loyalty to William and Mary.

01:11:45.442 --> 01:11:46.743
The French Catholics,

01:11:46.743 --> 01:11:48.645
seeing this as an attack on their faith

01:11:48.645 --> 01:11:50.180
and the will of the papacy,

01:11:50.180 --> 01:11:51.715
decided to fight back.

01:11:51.715 --> 01:11:54.117
However, much to France's surprise,

01:11:54.117 --> 01:11:56.686
most of Europe was pinned against them.

01:11:56.686 --> 01:11:58.321
England, the Dutch Republic,

01:11:58.321 --> 01:12:02.192
the Holy Roman Empire, and Spain were all aligned

01:12:02.192 --> 01:12:03.059
to stop the French

01:12:03.059 --> 01:12:06.663
in what was referred to as the Grand Alliance.

01:12:06.663 --> 01:12:09.065
On a bloody day in 1690,

01:12:09.065 --> 01:12:11.901
the Battle of Fleurus saw the French secure victory

01:12:11.901 --> 01:12:13.970
against the Grand Alliance forces

01:12:13.970 --> 01:12:15.772
in the Spanish Netherlands.

01:12:15.772 --> 01:12:18.174
This battle solidified France's hold

01:12:18.174 --> 01:12:20.243
on key territories in the region.

01:12:20.243 --> 01:12:22.212
Across the seas in Ireland,

01:12:22.212 --> 01:12:24.347
the Battle of the Boyne marked a clash

01:12:24.347 --> 01:12:28.218
between the forces of the deposed Catholic King James II

01:12:28.218 --> 01:12:32.088
and those of his Protestant successor King William III.

01:12:32.088 --> 01:12:33.990
William emerged victorious,

01:12:33.990 --> 01:12:37.193
securing his hold on the English and Irish Thrones.

01:12:37.193 --> 01:12:40.630
However, the war was not just a European battle.

01:12:40.630 --> 01:12:43.133
It spanned the entire world.

01:12:43.133 --> 01:12:46.402
In 1690, a series of clashes erupted,

01:12:46.402 --> 01:12:48.438
including the Battle of Port Royal.

01:12:48.438 --> 01:12:49.739
English forces attempted

01:12:49.739 --> 01:12:52.342
to capture the French stronghold in Acadia,

01:12:52.342 --> 01:12:54.110
present-day Nova Scotia,

01:12:54.110 --> 01:12:55.945
but their efforts were thwarted.

01:12:55.945 --> 01:12:58.581
French and Abenaki forces launched raids

01:12:58.581 --> 01:13:01.551
against English settlements in the province of Maine,

01:13:01.551 --> 01:13:04.854
sowing fear and uncertainty among the settlers.

01:13:04.854 --> 01:13:07.457
Battles like the Siege of Pemaquid showcased

01:13:07.457 --> 01:13:09.726
the complexities of alliances

01:13:09.726 --> 01:13:12.796
as indigenous tribes aligned with European powers

01:13:12.796 --> 01:13:14.564
to further their interests.

01:13:14.564 --> 01:13:17.901
In the Battle of Quebec, saw an English expedition attempt

01:13:17.901 --> 01:13:21.004
to capture the critical French stronghold in Canada.

01:13:21.004 --> 01:13:22.338
Despite their efforts,

01:13:22.338 --> 01:13:25.642
the English forces were unsuccessful in their endeavor,

01:13:25.642 --> 01:13:29.579
creating a firm boundary between the two nation's colonies.

01:13:29.579 --> 01:13:32.415
On September 20th, 1697,

01:13:32.415 --> 01:13:34.384
the Treaty of Ryswick was signed,

01:13:34.384 --> 01:13:36.953
marking the end of the Nine Years' War.

01:13:36.953 --> 01:13:39.322
In this treaty, it was officially declared

01:13:39.322 --> 01:13:42.325
that William of Orange was the leader of England.

01:13:42.325 --> 01:13:45.061
It also stopped the French offensive.

01:13:46.763 --> 01:13:50.333
While the Nine Year was underway in Europe and the Americas,

01:13:50.333 --> 01:13:53.002
the English were in their first war in India

01:13:53.002 --> 01:13:54.370
because at the time,

01:13:54.370 --> 01:13:57.407
the English East India Company had a trade monopoly

01:13:57.407 --> 01:13:58.341
in the area.

01:13:58.341 --> 01:14:01.411
The company wanted to obtain ownership of Chittagong,

01:14:01.411 --> 01:14:04.614
establish a fortified enclave throughout the region,

01:14:04.614 --> 01:14:07.150
and attain independence of the surrounding subah

01:14:07.150 --> 01:14:08.818
from the Mughal territory

01:14:08.818 --> 01:14:10.520
by bringing the local governors

01:14:10.520 --> 01:14:13.156
and the Hooghly River to their control.

01:14:13.156 --> 01:14:16.125
However, Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb refused

01:14:16.125 --> 01:14:18.394
these desired English terms.

01:14:18.394 --> 01:14:20.597
So the East India Company navy

01:14:20.597 --> 01:14:22.532
blockaded several Mughal ports

01:14:22.532 --> 01:14:24.200
on the western coast of India

01:14:24.200 --> 01:14:26.569
and engaged the Mughal army in battle.

01:14:26.569 --> 01:14:28.371
The blockade started to affect cities

01:14:28.371 --> 01:14:31.307
like Chittagong, Madras, and Bombay,

01:14:31.307 --> 01:14:34.611
which resulted in the intervention of Emperor Aurangzeb,

01:14:34.611 --> 01:14:36.980
who seized all the factories of the company

01:14:36.980 --> 01:14:39.983
and arrested members of the East India Company army.

01:14:39.983 --> 01:14:42.852
In 1690, the Mughal fleet from Janjira

01:14:42.852 --> 01:14:44.587
commanded by Sidi Yaqub

01:14:44.587 --> 01:14:47.991
blockaded the East India Company fort in Bombay.

01:14:47.991 --> 01:14:50.793
After a year of resistance and famine in the fort,

01:14:50.793 --> 01:14:52.328
the company surrendered

01:14:52.328 --> 01:14:55.231
and the company sent envoys to Aurangzeb's court

01:14:55.231 --> 01:14:58.001
to plead for a pardon and to renew the trade.

01:14:58.001 --> 01:15:00.737
The company's envoys had a prostrate themselves

01:15:00.737 --> 01:15:03.773
before the emperor paid a hefty imperial fine

01:15:03.773 --> 01:15:06.409
of 150,000 rupees,

01:15:06.409 --> 01:15:09.679
the equivalent of 4.4 million today.

01:15:09.679 --> 01:15:12.382
Emperor Aurangzeb then ordered Sidi Yaqub

01:15:12.382 --> 01:15:14.484
to lift the siege of Bombay,

01:15:14.484 --> 01:15:18.187
and the company subsequently reestablished itself in Bombay

01:15:18.187 --> 01:15:21.324
and set up a new base in Calcutta.

01:15:21.324 --> 01:15:24.494
(dramatic music)

01:15:24.494 --> 01:15:26.062
While back over in England,

01:15:26.062 --> 01:15:29.365
when Queen Anne took over for William in 1702,

01:15:29.365 --> 01:15:32.035
the structure of the government within the British Isles

01:15:32.035 --> 01:15:33.336
was quite unique.

01:15:33.336 --> 01:15:35.738
There were four kingdoms, three parliaments,

01:15:35.738 --> 01:15:37.040
and one Monarch.

01:15:37.040 --> 01:15:39.742
Scotland had their own parliament and set of laws

01:15:39.742 --> 01:15:41.210
while they were still under the power

01:15:41.210 --> 01:15:42.578
of the British monarch.

01:15:42.578 --> 01:15:44.781
Ireland also had their own parliament

01:15:44.781 --> 01:15:47.817
with statutes in still abiding the British monarch.

01:15:47.817 --> 01:15:50.019
England and Wales shared a parliament

01:15:50.019 --> 01:15:53.089
as Wales was more assimilated into English culture.

01:15:53.089 --> 01:15:56.092
That, of course, still followed the British monarch.

01:15:56.092 --> 01:15:58.895
In 1707, though, Scotland was dealing

01:15:58.895 --> 01:16:03.232
with the economic turmoil of corruption, resource depletion,

01:16:03.232 --> 01:16:05.735
and an increasingly powerful elite.

01:16:05.735 --> 01:16:08.338
The wealthy knew that they could increase their power

01:16:08.338 --> 01:16:10.006
if they combined parliament.

01:16:10.006 --> 01:16:12.241
Many Scottish officials were bribed,

01:16:12.241 --> 01:16:14.911
such as Earl of Glasgow David Boyle

01:16:14.911 --> 01:16:17.981
and second Duke of Queensbury James Douglas,

01:16:17.981 --> 01:16:20.783
who received around 20,000 pounds,

01:16:20.783 --> 01:16:22.852
four million pounds today,

01:16:22.852 --> 01:16:25.021
to end the Scottish parliament.

01:16:25.021 --> 01:16:28.024
The poor hated this, but they were ignored.

01:16:28.024 --> 01:16:30.560
So on May 1st, 1707,

01:16:30.560 --> 01:16:32.996
the Scottish and English parliament combined

01:16:32.996 --> 01:16:35.331
to form the Parliament of Great Britain

01:16:35.331 --> 01:16:37.233
based in the palace of Westminster,

01:16:37.233 --> 01:16:39.569
which housed the old English parliament.

01:16:39.569 --> 01:16:42.905
As any semblance of Scottish independence was gone,

01:16:42.905 --> 01:16:44.974
anger spread throughout Scotland,

01:16:44.974 --> 01:16:46.642
but nothing was done about it.

01:16:46.642 --> 01:16:49.545
However, for England, this uniting of parliament

01:16:49.545 --> 01:16:51.547
created the term Great Britain,

01:16:51.547 --> 01:16:54.017
was the beginning of the empire.

01:16:54.951 --> 01:16:58.054
(dramatic music)

01:16:58.054 --> 01:17:00.890
Though the Treaty of Ryswick was designed to keep the peace

01:17:00.890 --> 01:17:02.692
between England and France,

01:17:02.692 --> 01:17:04.127
it was shortlived.

01:17:04.127 --> 01:17:06.629
In 1707, they were again fighting

01:17:06.629 --> 01:17:08.331
over the colonies in America

01:17:08.331 --> 01:17:10.833
due to a succession issue in Spain.

01:17:10.833 --> 01:17:14.303
The Spanish King Charles II was dying of ill health

01:17:14.303 --> 01:17:15.671
without any children.

01:17:15.671 --> 01:17:19.175
Two rival claims emerged to seize the Spanish crown,

01:17:19.175 --> 01:17:22.745
Archduke Charles of Austria, a Habsburg scion,

01:17:22.745 --> 01:17:25.548
and Philip of Anjou, a Bourbon prince

01:17:25.548 --> 01:17:29.485
and possible successor to France's King Louis XIV.

01:17:29.485 --> 01:17:33.022
The English feared a united French and Spanish throne

01:17:33.022 --> 01:17:36.559
because it would increase Catholicism's power worldwide.

01:17:36.559 --> 01:17:39.362
So the English staunchly declared war.

01:17:39.362 --> 01:17:40.696
Even though this war started

01:17:40.696 --> 01:17:42.832
about who should be king of Spain,

01:17:42.832 --> 01:17:46.436
it ended by restructuring European colonization.

01:17:46.436 --> 01:17:49.672
The first battle on American soil was in Fort Albany,

01:17:49.672 --> 01:17:52.842
where French commander Claude de Ramezay and his men

01:17:52.842 --> 01:17:55.611
wanted to knock out the English trading post.

01:17:55.611 --> 01:17:59.182
Fort Albany's wooden walls and palisades stood as barriers

01:17:59.182 --> 01:18:02.151
separating the defenders from the impending storm.

01:18:02.151 --> 01:18:05.254
Inside the fort, English traders and soldiers braced

01:18:05.254 --> 01:18:07.890
for the confrontation that was about to unfold.

01:18:07.890 --> 01:18:11.394
But the fort was no match to heavy French cannon fire

01:18:11.394 --> 01:18:14.063
and was later surrendered to the French.

01:18:14.063 --> 01:18:16.132
However, the English weren't done

01:18:16.132 --> 01:18:18.468
because English and French settlers wrestled

01:18:18.468 --> 01:18:20.136
over territorial boundaries

01:18:20.136 --> 01:18:22.438
in the rugged wilderness of Acadia.

01:18:22.438 --> 01:18:23.773
Upon leaving England,

01:18:23.773 --> 01:18:27.477
Commanders Francis Nicholson and Samuel Vetch came to Acadia

01:18:27.477 --> 01:18:29.745
to gain the territory for the Crown.

01:18:29.745 --> 01:18:32.081
Upon the rocky shores of Port Royal,

01:18:32.081 --> 01:18:34.550
the battle for dominance unfolded.

01:18:34.550 --> 01:18:37.186
English warships loomed on the horizon,

01:18:37.186 --> 01:18:39.021
their cannons primed and ready.

01:18:39.021 --> 01:18:41.457
The colonial troops, resolute in purpose,

01:18:41.457 --> 01:18:44.360
embarked upon a siege of the French stronghold.

01:18:44.360 --> 01:18:46.095
Within the fortifications,

01:18:46.095 --> 01:18:48.231
Governor Daniel d'Auger de Subercase

01:18:48.231 --> 01:18:50.500
led a valiant French garrison.

01:18:50.500 --> 01:18:53.302
Days turned to nights as the siege pressed on,

01:18:53.302 --> 01:18:54.670
the thought of cannonballs

01:18:54.670 --> 01:18:57.607
and the roar of muskets reverberating through the air.

01:18:57.607 --> 01:19:00.576
Amid the chaos, negotiations began.

01:19:00.576 --> 01:19:02.278
On a crisp October day,

01:19:02.278 --> 01:19:05.781
white flags of truce fluttered above the ramparts.

01:19:05.781 --> 01:19:10.019
Governor Subercase, recognizing the inevitable, surrendered.

01:19:10.019 --> 01:19:14.857
On October 5th, 1710, the gates of Port Royal swung open

01:19:14.857 --> 01:19:17.260
and the English entered victorious.

01:19:17.260 --> 01:19:20.630
The French colors lowered, replaced by the Union Jack.

01:19:20.630 --> 01:19:24.767
Acadia, once French, was now under English control.

01:19:24.767 --> 01:19:26.802
Annapolis Royal it was named,

01:19:26.802 --> 01:19:28.037
a tribute to the queen

01:19:28.037 --> 01:19:31.040
whose reign witnessed this turning point in history.

01:19:31.040 --> 01:19:32.508
As the war was ending,

01:19:32.508 --> 01:19:35.444
the Treaty of Utrecht was signed in the Netherlands

01:19:35.444 --> 01:19:37.346
declaring King Philip V

01:19:37.346 --> 01:19:39.815
the rightful king of the Spanish throne.

01:19:39.815 --> 01:19:43.486
However, the other provision, the Asiento de Negros,

01:19:43.486 --> 01:19:46.389
gave the English immense economic power.

01:19:46.389 --> 01:19:49.258
For context, the Spanish were never really the people

01:19:49.258 --> 01:19:50.493
who went through the process

01:19:50.493 --> 01:19:53.396
of transferring enslaved people from Africa.

01:19:53.396 --> 01:19:55.698
Instead, they exported the labor of it

01:19:55.698 --> 01:19:58.734
in a monopoly called Asiento de Negros.

01:19:58.734 --> 01:20:01.504
Before the treaty, the French had the contract,

01:20:01.504 --> 01:20:03.005
but part of the peace deal,

01:20:03.005 --> 01:20:05.074
that contract went to the English

01:20:05.074 --> 01:20:06.742
so they could be a leader

01:20:06.742 --> 01:20:10.213
in the lucrative and dehumanizing practice

01:20:10.213 --> 01:20:12.615
of the transatlantic slave trade.

01:20:12.615 --> 01:20:15.384
The treaty caused the French to cede the territories

01:20:15.384 --> 01:20:17.720
of Nova Scotia, Newfoundland,

01:20:17.720 --> 01:20:20.790
and territories in Rupert's Land in North America.

01:20:20.790 --> 01:20:23.593
The Spanish ceded the colonies of Gibraltar

01:20:23.593 --> 01:20:25.995
and Menorca in the Caribbean.

01:20:25.995 --> 01:20:28.164
While global politics were being discussed

01:20:28.164 --> 01:20:29.165
in the Netherlands,

01:20:29.165 --> 01:20:31.734
the Carolinas reshaped their society.

01:20:31.734 --> 01:20:34.604
Instead of being one united Carolina,

01:20:34.604 --> 01:20:37.573
they split up into a North and South Carolina.

01:20:37.573 --> 01:20:39.342
South Carolina was fertile,

01:20:39.342 --> 01:20:41.344
great for sugar cane production,

01:20:41.344 --> 01:20:43.913
and had access to more raw materials.

01:20:43.913 --> 01:20:47.183
North Carolina, on the other hand, was slightly less fertile

01:20:47.183 --> 01:20:49.418
and economically less valuable.

01:20:49.418 --> 01:20:53.356
So South Carolina became a jewel for the British Empire,

01:20:53.356 --> 01:20:54.323
which led to the need

01:20:54.323 --> 01:20:57.426
for more and more production of raw goods.

01:20:57.426 --> 01:20:58.761
To produce these goods,

01:20:58.761 --> 01:21:01.731
they needed to increase their power over slaves.

01:21:01.731 --> 01:21:04.900
So in 1712, South Carolina passed

01:21:04.900 --> 01:21:08.571
the notorious Slave Codes of 1712.

01:21:08.571 --> 01:21:10.706
Though it is quite hard to hear,

01:21:10.706 --> 01:21:13.509
this nasty document outlined the viewpoints

01:21:13.509 --> 01:21:15.611
of slave-owning colonists

01:21:15.611 --> 01:21:18.080
and what they felt they had the right to do.

01:21:18.080 --> 01:21:21.250
The code states, "Negroes and other slaves

01:21:21.250 --> 01:21:24.654
brought unto the people of this province for that purpose

01:21:24.654 --> 01:21:27.823
are of barbarous, wild, savage natures,

01:21:27.823 --> 01:21:31.460
and such as renders them wholly unqualified to be governed

01:21:31.460 --> 01:21:35.665
by the laws, customs, and practices of this province."

01:21:35.665 --> 01:21:38.401
This code created a quite harsh set of rules

01:21:38.401 --> 01:21:41.671
that included practices such as: slaves were forbidden

01:21:41.671 --> 01:21:43.306
to leave the owner's property

01:21:43.306 --> 01:21:45.741
unless they were accompanied by a white person

01:21:45.741 --> 01:21:47.243
or had permission;

01:21:47.243 --> 01:21:50.346
if a slave leaves the owner's property without permission,

01:21:50.346 --> 01:21:52.715
every white person is required

01:21:52.715 --> 01:21:56.152
to chastise, whip, such slaves;

01:21:56.152 --> 01:21:59.055
any slave attempting to run away and leave the colony

01:21:59.055 --> 01:22:01.257
receives the death penalty;

01:22:01.257 --> 01:22:04.460
any slave who evades capture for 20 days or more

01:22:04.460 --> 01:22:07.563
is to be publicly whipped for the first offense,

01:22:07.563 --> 01:22:10.132
branded with the letter R on the right cheek

01:22:10.132 --> 01:22:11.701
for the second offense,

01:22:11.701 --> 01:22:16.639
and lose one ear if absent for 30 days for the third offense

01:22:16.639 --> 01:22:19.542
and castrated for the fourth offense.

01:22:19.542 --> 01:22:22.611
This code became the forefront of slave treatment

01:22:22.611 --> 01:22:24.447
within the American colonies

01:22:24.447 --> 01:22:26.048
and the rest of the world.

01:22:26.048 --> 01:22:27.750
To the people of Carolinas,

01:22:27.750 --> 01:22:30.686
slaves were nothing more than tools for farmland

01:22:30.686 --> 01:22:32.955
to make a profit for their owners.

01:22:32.955 --> 01:22:37.159
At the time, though, there were approximately 40,000 slaves

01:22:37.159 --> 01:22:38.561
in North America.

01:22:40.329 --> 01:22:42.665
However, down south in the Caribbean islands

01:22:42.665 --> 01:22:45.534
of Barbados, Jamaica, and the Leeward Islands,

01:22:45.534 --> 01:22:49.138
the need for slaves in British colonies grew exponentially

01:22:49.138 --> 01:22:50.406
because of the profitable,

01:22:50.406 --> 01:22:53.142
yet labor intensive crop of sugar cane.

01:22:53.142 --> 01:22:55.978
To cultivate a simple stock of sugar cane,

01:22:55.978 --> 01:22:58.080
first slaves would have to clear the space

01:22:58.080 --> 01:23:01.617
of all other vegetation in 100-plus degree heat,

01:23:01.617 --> 01:23:03.185
38 degree Celsius,

01:23:03.185 --> 01:23:05.721
to create a clear farming surface.

01:23:05.721 --> 01:23:08.357
Then you had to put little sugar cane stalks

01:23:08.357 --> 01:23:10.192
into the soil repeatedly.

01:23:10.192 --> 01:23:12.561
Once planted, slaves would have to weed, hoe,

01:23:12.561 --> 01:23:15.698
and maintain the crops on a massive plantation

01:23:15.698 --> 01:23:18.134
that spanned hundreds of acres.

01:23:18.134 --> 01:23:20.302
Slaves would also have to build canals

01:23:20.302 --> 01:23:23.239
to ensure the sugar cane was adequately hydrated

01:23:23.239 --> 01:23:25.941
while they barely had enough to drink.

01:23:25.941 --> 01:23:28.210
Then after 12 to 18 months,

01:23:28.210 --> 01:23:30.713
slaves used machetes to cut off the stalks

01:23:30.713 --> 01:23:32.681
and farm an adult sugar cane.

01:23:32.681 --> 01:23:35.484
This process was so physically grueling

01:23:35.484 --> 01:23:37.820
as they were often malnourished, overheated,

01:23:37.820 --> 01:23:40.556
and forced to work 18-hour-plus days

01:23:40.556 --> 01:23:42.992
that slaves would die left and right.

01:23:42.992 --> 01:23:45.561
That's why the English would enslave and transport

01:23:45.561 --> 01:23:50.499
around 200,000 Africans from 1710 to 1720

01:23:50.499 --> 01:23:51.734
to the Americans

01:23:51.734 --> 01:23:54.470
so they could always have fresh labor.

01:23:54.470 --> 01:23:57.873
Sugar doesn't always taste that sweet.

01:23:57.873 --> 01:24:00.876
(dramatic music)

01:24:00.876 --> 01:24:02.378
While back in England,

01:24:02.378 --> 01:24:04.613
James Oglethorpe wanted to create a colony

01:24:04.613 --> 01:24:06.715
home to the worthy poor,

01:24:06.715 --> 01:24:09.652
individuals who struggled financially in England,

01:24:09.652 --> 01:24:12.354
so that they could have a fresh start overseas.

01:24:12.354 --> 01:24:15.591
English citizens convicted of owing debt had a choice:

01:24:15.591 --> 01:24:18.627
go to prison or go to the swamps of Georgia.

01:24:18.627 --> 01:24:23.632
In November 1732, 144 colonists, including Oglethorpe,

01:24:23.966 --> 01:24:26.569
boarded the Anne in Gravesend English

01:24:26.569 --> 01:24:30.773
and sailed to Savannah on February 12th, 1733.

01:24:30.773 --> 01:24:32.775
Unlike their neighbors in the Carolinas,

01:24:32.775 --> 01:24:35.711
Georgia banned all slavery in the colony.

01:24:35.711 --> 01:24:38.614
Instead of having these massive plantations,

01:24:38.614 --> 01:24:41.150
Georgians would farm their own small farms

01:24:41.150 --> 01:24:43.719
where they could make enough food for their families.

01:24:43.719 --> 01:24:45.421
Oglethorpe wanted the colonists

01:24:45.421 --> 01:24:47.089
to create a comfortable living

01:24:47.089 --> 01:24:49.325
but not be incredibly wealthy.

01:24:49.325 --> 01:24:51.560
The other main fear of introducing slavery

01:24:51.560 --> 01:24:54.530
would be that the Spanish colony of Florida offered freedom

01:24:54.530 --> 01:24:56.131
to any African slave

01:24:56.131 --> 01:24:58.367
who went to their border and joined their army.

01:24:58.367 --> 01:25:01.370
If slavery was permitted, there would be very little

01:25:01.370 --> 01:25:04.173
to stop the slaves from feeding the Spanish army

01:25:04.173 --> 01:25:07.243
and expanding their American interests.

01:25:08.177 --> 01:25:09.311
(dramatic music)

01:25:09.311 --> 01:25:11.747
However, that wouldn't stop the two nations

01:25:11.747 --> 01:25:13.048
from going to war

01:25:13.048 --> 01:25:17.152
because before Georgia was even a colony in 1731,

01:25:17.152 --> 01:25:19.955
British merchant Robert Jenkins was notorious

01:25:19.955 --> 01:25:23.392
for raiding Spanish ships and stealing their resources.

01:25:23.392 --> 01:25:26.428
One day, a Spanish privateer captured Jenkins

01:25:26.428 --> 01:25:29.298
and, as punishment, severed his ear.

01:25:29.298 --> 01:25:32.501
Jenkins then proceeded to present the ear to Parliament

01:25:32.501 --> 01:25:35.804
and the outraged English demanded retribution.

01:25:35.804 --> 01:25:36.872
For eight years,

01:25:36.872 --> 01:25:39.942
the two nations tried to solve this conflict peacefully,

01:25:39.942 --> 01:25:43.779
but in January 1740, Oglethorpe and his men invaded

01:25:43.779 --> 01:25:46.015
and seized two Spanish forts,

01:25:46.015 --> 01:25:49.251
Fort Picolata and Fort San Francisco de Pupo.

01:25:49.251 --> 01:25:52.187
The Georgian general wanted to go further in Florida

01:25:52.187 --> 01:25:54.156
and capture Fort St. Augustine,

01:25:54.156 --> 01:25:57.026
but quickly realized he didn't have enough forces

01:25:57.026 --> 01:25:58.761
and retreated back to Georgia.

01:25:58.761 --> 01:26:01.130
All Oglethorpe could do was fortify

01:26:01.130 --> 01:26:03.465
and prepare for the incoming invasion.

01:26:03.465 --> 01:26:06.802
That assault came in the summer of 1742.

01:26:06.802 --> 01:26:09.805
After landing on the southern tip of St. Simons Island,

01:26:09.805 --> 01:26:10.940
the Spanish assembled

01:26:10.940 --> 01:26:13.409
to attack the English fort of Frederica.

01:26:13.409 --> 01:26:15.911
English rangers encountered a scouting party

01:26:15.911 --> 01:26:19.281
and Oglethorpe led the charge against the Spanish soldiers,

01:26:19.281 --> 01:26:21.083
who hastily fled the scene.

01:26:21.083 --> 01:26:23.419
While Oglethorpe returned to Frederica,

01:26:23.419 --> 01:26:25.588
his men fortified the road to the fort

01:26:25.588 --> 01:26:27.656
to prevent further incursions.

01:26:27.656 --> 01:26:29.792
A second skirmish ensued,

01:26:29.792 --> 01:26:32.561
an event later known as the Battle of Bloody Marsh,

01:26:32.561 --> 01:26:35.130
when the Spanish advanced another regiment.

01:26:35.130 --> 01:26:38.734
English forces sent the Spanish fleeing to the coastline,

01:26:38.734 --> 01:26:41.837
and from there, retreating to St. Augustine.

01:26:41.837 --> 01:26:43.372
(dramatic music)

01:26:43.372 --> 01:26:46.942
The War of Jenkins Ear wasn't just an American affair.

01:26:46.942 --> 01:26:49.411
It also spanned over to the Carnatic region

01:26:49.411 --> 01:26:50.746
of southern India.

01:26:50.746 --> 01:26:54.083
The English, with their Indian allies led by Anwaruddin,

01:26:54.083 --> 01:26:56.785
supported the claim to the Carnatic throne.

01:26:56.785 --> 01:26:57.920
On the other side,

01:26:57.920 --> 01:26:58.821
under the leadership

01:26:58.821 --> 01:27:01.724
of the ambitious Governor-General Dupleix,

01:27:01.724 --> 01:27:04.927
the French had forged an alliance with Chanda Sahib,

01:27:04.927 --> 01:27:07.496
a contender for the throne of the Carnatic.

01:27:07.496 --> 01:27:10.466
The tensions escalated in 1744

01:27:10.466 --> 01:27:14.303
when a spark ignited the powder keg of colonial rivalry.

01:27:14.303 --> 01:27:16.639
The Battle of Adyar was a pivotal moment

01:27:16.639 --> 01:27:18.907
where the French defeated the English forces

01:27:18.907 --> 01:27:21.543
with their superior military tactics.

01:27:21.543 --> 01:27:24.446
It was a resounding victory for the French,

01:27:24.446 --> 01:27:28.384
and their influence in the Carnatic seemed unstoppable.

01:27:28.384 --> 01:27:30.152
Buoyed by their success,

01:27:30.152 --> 01:27:31.387
the French laid siege

01:27:31.387 --> 01:27:35.824
to the English controlled city of Madras in 1746.

01:27:35.824 --> 01:27:39.261
The English, outnumbered and outmaneuvered, had no choice

01:27:39.261 --> 01:27:42.564
but to surrender the city to the triumphant French.

01:27:42.564 --> 01:27:43.832
(dramatic music)

01:27:43.832 --> 01:27:45.668
But all of this was about to change

01:27:45.668 --> 01:27:47.269
because of the primary battle

01:27:47.269 --> 01:27:49.738
in the disputed territory of Austria.

01:27:49.738 --> 01:27:52.341
The Prussians, Dutch, Spanish, French,

01:27:52.341 --> 01:27:55.544
and independence movements claimed this territory.

01:27:55.544 --> 01:27:57.980
The English, not wanting to be left out of it,

01:27:57.980 --> 01:27:59.948
decided to ally with the Dutch

01:27:59.948 --> 01:28:01.784
and try to put them in power.

01:28:01.784 --> 01:28:06.055
In the summer of 1747, the Battle of Lauffeld occurred

01:28:06.055 --> 01:28:08.390
where the British, Dutch, and Austrian forces

01:28:08.390 --> 01:28:09.892
led by Duke Cumberland

01:28:09.892 --> 01:28:12.294
tried to infiltrate the French defense.

01:28:12.294 --> 01:28:15.230
However, they could not go through the French security

01:28:15.230 --> 01:28:17.099
led by Maurice de Saxe,

01:28:17.099 --> 01:28:19.535
allowing the battle to end in stalemate.

01:28:19.535 --> 01:28:22.304
But nevertheless, diplomacy is sometimes

01:28:22.304 --> 01:28:24.373
where the real battles are fought.

01:28:24.373 --> 01:28:27.910
By the time all parties were done fighting in 1748,

01:28:27.910 --> 01:28:30.512
a favorable peace deal for the British emerged

01:28:30.512 --> 01:28:32.915
with the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle.

01:28:32.915 --> 01:28:36.285
They agreed to restore almost all territorial shifts

01:28:36.285 --> 01:28:38.654
to their pre-war status quo.

01:28:38.654 --> 01:28:41.290
This means Madras was back in English hands,

01:28:41.290 --> 01:28:43.025
even though they lost it in battle.

01:28:43.025 --> 01:28:45.260
The peace treaty also officially created

01:28:45.260 --> 01:28:48.664
an English and French border between Georgia and Florida

01:28:48.664 --> 01:28:51.533
and the St. Johns River in the Americas.

01:28:51.533 --> 01:28:53.302
Also, Austria succeeded

01:28:53.302 --> 01:28:54.803
and became its own country

01:28:54.803 --> 01:28:57.406
under the leadership of Maria Teresa.

01:28:58.974 --> 01:29:00.876
After the war, in Georgia,

01:29:00.876 --> 01:29:03.946
the question of slavery was returned to the table.

01:29:03.946 --> 01:29:07.816
Oglethorpe remained adamant that slavery not be allowed,

01:29:07.816 --> 01:29:09.685
but with the unenforceable nature

01:29:09.685 --> 01:29:13.222
of the illegal importation of slaves from South Carolina,

01:29:13.222 --> 01:29:15.390
it quickly became a lost cause.

01:29:15.390 --> 01:29:18.861
The worthy poor didn't want to be poor.

01:29:18.861 --> 01:29:21.497
They wanted to be rich like their neighbors.

01:29:21.497 --> 01:29:26.235
So on January 1st, 1751, slavery was permitted

01:29:26.235 --> 01:29:30.806
with a code almost identical to South Carolina's and passed.

01:29:30.806 --> 01:29:34.443
This change, though, ultimately hurt the worthy poor

01:29:34.443 --> 01:29:36.845
Oglethorpe designed Georgia to help

01:29:36.845 --> 01:29:39.381
because the South Carolinian migrants enjoyed

01:29:39.381 --> 01:29:41.416
a significant wealth advantage

01:29:41.416 --> 01:29:43.719
over the original settlers of Georgia.

01:29:43.719 --> 01:29:47.089
They quickly established socioeconomic structures

01:29:47.089 --> 01:29:49.525
and relationships nearly identical

01:29:49.525 --> 01:29:51.960
to those they had known in their colony.

01:29:51.960 --> 01:29:54.830
Within 20 years, some 60 planters

01:29:54.830 --> 01:29:56.598
who owned roughly half the colony's

01:29:56.598 --> 01:29:59.201
rapidly increasing enslaved population

01:29:59.201 --> 01:30:03.539
dominated the apex of Low Country Georgia's rice economy.

01:30:04.439 --> 01:30:07.943
However, not all of America was a slave colony.

01:30:07.943 --> 01:30:11.547
In the forests of North America lay the Ohio Valley,

01:30:11.547 --> 01:30:16.251
a swath of 300,000 acres home to forests, fur pelts,

01:30:16.251 --> 01:30:18.287
and the opportunity to expand.

01:30:18.287 --> 01:30:21.123
Hence, the Ohio Company of Virginia was founded

01:30:21.123 --> 01:30:24.893
by Augustine Washington, George Washington's father,

01:30:24.893 --> 01:30:27.930
to find a way to make a profit from the natural landscape.

01:30:27.930 --> 01:30:29.965
A young George Washington was tasked

01:30:29.965 --> 01:30:32.801
with surveying and mapping the company's land holdings

01:30:32.801 --> 01:30:33.635
in the region.

01:30:33.635 --> 01:30:35.838
What he found, though, was concerning

01:30:35.838 --> 01:30:37.472
from a British perspective.

01:30:37.472 --> 01:30:38.874
The land was already home

01:30:38.874 --> 01:30:41.510
to the Shawnee and Delaware tribes,

01:30:41.510 --> 01:30:42.945
both of which were unhappy

01:30:42.945 --> 01:30:45.681
about the British expansion into the colony.

01:30:45.681 --> 01:30:47.783
The French were also present in the region

01:30:47.783 --> 01:30:50.452
with their lucrative fur trading business.

01:30:50.452 --> 01:30:52.921
The land was littered with French forts,

01:30:52.921 --> 01:30:54.756
such as the Fort Duquesne,

01:30:54.756 --> 01:30:56.358
constructed at the intersection

01:30:56.358 --> 01:30:58.727
of the Allegheny and Monongahela rivers

01:30:58.727 --> 01:31:00.562
in modern-day Pittsburgh.

01:31:00.562 --> 01:31:02.631
By April 1754,

01:31:02.631 --> 01:31:05.868
when tensions between the English and French were boiling,

01:31:05.868 --> 01:31:08.503
22-year-old George Washington was sent out

01:31:08.503 --> 01:31:10.505
with a small detachment of troops

01:31:10.505 --> 01:31:12.641
determined to secure the valley.

01:31:12.641 --> 01:31:14.443
Deep in the heart of the wilderness,

01:31:14.443 --> 01:31:17.646
Washington's party stumbled upon a secluded glen

01:31:17.646 --> 01:31:20.015
known as Jumonville Glen.

01:31:20.015 --> 01:31:21.550
In this hidden grove,

01:31:21.550 --> 01:31:24.987
Washington's men stumbled upon a small French force

01:31:24.987 --> 01:31:28.323
led by a man named Joseph Coulon de Jumonville,

01:31:28.323 --> 01:31:30.125
a French enlisted man.

01:31:30.125 --> 01:31:34.096
Tensions were high and the forest was thick with suspense.

01:31:34.096 --> 01:31:36.164
No one knew what lay ahead.

01:31:36.164 --> 01:31:39.935
On the fateful morning of May 28th, 1754,

01:31:39.935 --> 01:31:42.804
in a way clouded by the mysteries of war,

01:31:42.804 --> 01:31:44.306
Joseph was killed.

01:31:44.306 --> 01:31:47.276
The English would say his death occurred amid battle,

01:31:47.276 --> 01:31:48.410
but the French would say

01:31:48.410 --> 01:31:51.179
it was a calculated assassination attempt.

01:31:51.179 --> 01:31:54.349
The French, seeking revenge for the death of Jumonville,

01:31:54.349 --> 01:31:55.751
were incensed.

01:31:55.751 --> 01:31:57.986
They surrounded Washington and his men,

01:31:57.986 --> 01:32:01.690
who had retreated to a makeshift fort called Fort Necessity.

01:32:01.690 --> 01:32:03.025
Trapped and outnumbered,

01:32:03.025 --> 01:32:07.663
Washington was forced to surrender on July 3rd, 1754.

01:32:07.663 --> 01:32:09.197
Among the terms of surrender

01:32:09.197 --> 01:32:10.866
was Washington's acknowledgement

01:32:10.866 --> 01:32:13.969
that he had assassinated Jumonville.

01:32:13.969 --> 01:32:16.138
The ball of war was rolling.

01:32:16.138 --> 01:32:17.606
In Saxony, Europe,

01:32:17.606 --> 01:32:20.709
Prussian King Frederick II invaded Saxony,

01:32:20.709 --> 01:32:22.377
which put the world on notice

01:32:22.377 --> 01:32:25.747
as this bloody worldwide conflict began.

01:32:25.747 --> 01:32:28.550
(dramatic music)

01:32:28.550 --> 01:32:31.820
The Seven Years' War was our planet's first world war.

01:32:31.820 --> 01:32:34.089
It expanded over three continents,

01:32:34.089 --> 01:32:36.591
the Americas, Europe, and India.

01:32:36.591 --> 01:32:39.294
The European powers were trying to gain control

01:32:39.294 --> 01:32:42.497
for their civilization to have worldwide influence

01:32:42.497 --> 01:32:45.167
while the local nations were fighting for survival.

01:32:45.167 --> 01:32:46.468
The tides were shifting

01:32:46.468 --> 01:32:49.538
and the world was now completely global.

01:32:50.839 --> 01:32:53.075
The war did not start off great for the British

01:32:53.075 --> 01:32:55.677
when the governor of Bengal, Siraj-ud-Daulah,

01:32:55.677 --> 01:32:57.879
captured Fort William in Calcutta,

01:32:57.879 --> 01:33:00.449
the home of the British East India Company.

01:33:00.449 --> 01:33:02.818
When the Bengalese soldiers entered the fort,

01:33:02.818 --> 01:33:06.989
they imprisoned 146 Englishmen into a tiny dungeon

01:33:06.989 --> 01:33:09.624
where they were supposed to be transferred in the morning.

01:33:09.624 --> 01:33:12.794
However, these conditions were so appalling and dismal

01:33:12.794 --> 01:33:15.998
that according to John Howell, one of the prisoners,

01:33:15.998 --> 01:33:20.969
123 of the 146 people died in that dungeon.

01:33:21.069 --> 01:33:23.705
The smell of death reeked throughout the fort

01:33:23.705 --> 01:33:27.042
as they opened the door to the black hole of Calcutta.

01:33:27.042 --> 01:33:28.377
When the news got around,

01:33:28.377 --> 01:33:30.746
the English were determined to restore the fort

01:33:30.746 --> 01:33:33.782
and gain revenge on the victims of the black hole.

01:33:33.782 --> 01:33:36.351
However, their traction was quickly fleeting

01:33:36.351 --> 01:33:37.986
and they needed to do anything

01:33:37.986 --> 01:33:40.822
to keep their foot on the wheel in India.

01:33:40.822 --> 01:33:43.258
That's when British officer Robert Clive

01:33:43.258 --> 01:33:44.893
rounded up his British soldiers

01:33:44.893 --> 01:33:48.597
to take down Siraj in the village of Plassey in Bengal.

01:33:48.597 --> 01:33:50.332
As the two armies faced each other

01:33:50.332 --> 01:33:52.200
on that fateful day in June,

01:33:52.200 --> 01:33:54.736
Siraj-ud-Daulah held the advantage.

01:33:54.736 --> 01:33:56.671
His forces outnumbered Clive's

01:33:56.671 --> 01:33:58.206
and the heat of the Indian sun

01:33:58.206 --> 01:34:00.275
bore down upon the battlefield.

01:34:00.275 --> 01:34:02.577
But appearances can be deceiving.

01:34:02.577 --> 01:34:06.214
Clive had a secret weapon in his arsenal, betrayal.

01:34:06.214 --> 01:34:08.984
He had forged alliances with local officials

01:34:08.984 --> 01:34:11.620
discontented with Siraj-ud-Daulah's rule.

01:34:11.620 --> 01:34:13.655
Among them was Mir Jafar,

01:34:13.655 --> 01:34:15.824
a man with ambitions of his own.

01:34:15.824 --> 01:34:18.627
The battle began and it quickly became apparent

01:34:18.627 --> 01:34:21.997
that Siraj-ud-Daulah's forces were poorly coordinated.

01:34:21.997 --> 01:34:24.699
Meanwhile, Mir Jafar and his supporters were ready

01:34:24.699 --> 01:34:26.001
to make their move.

01:34:26.001 --> 01:34:29.571
As the battle raged, Mir Jafar's forces defected,

01:34:29.571 --> 01:34:32.441
turning the tide in favor of the British.

01:34:32.441 --> 01:34:35.277
The British forces secured victory that day,

01:34:35.277 --> 01:34:38.780
Siraj-ud-Daulah was captured and promptly executed.

01:34:38.780 --> 01:34:41.450
Mir Jafar was installed as the new governor,

01:34:41.450 --> 01:34:43.985
a puppet ruler under British influence.

01:34:43.985 --> 01:34:46.655
While a few short months later, in September,

01:34:46.655 --> 01:34:49.558
a naval and land battle would occur at Nagapattinam

01:34:49.558 --> 01:34:51.393
within the Maratha territory.

01:34:51.393 --> 01:34:53.595
As the French made their way to Nagapattinam

01:34:53.595 --> 01:34:55.864
under the leadership of Comte de Lally

01:34:55.864 --> 01:34:59.901
the allied English and Maratha forces were ready for action.

01:34:59.901 --> 01:35:02.237
The battle commenced with naval clashes

01:35:02.237 --> 01:35:03.972
off the coast of Nagapattinam

01:35:03.972 --> 01:35:06.508
as the British and French fleets locked horns

01:35:06.508 --> 01:35:10.312
in a fierce contest of cannon fire and naval maneuvering.

01:35:10.312 --> 01:35:12.814
On land, the British and Marathas advanced

01:35:12.814 --> 01:35:15.917
against the well-fortified French positions,

01:35:15.917 --> 01:35:19.921
determined to rest control of the strategic stronghold.

01:35:19.921 --> 01:35:22.224
The combined might of the British and Maratha,

01:35:22.224 --> 01:35:24.226
bolstered by their meticulous planning

01:35:24.226 --> 01:35:27.596
and coordinated attacks, proved overwhelming.

01:35:27.596 --> 01:35:31.433
The superior British naval power, military prowess,

01:35:31.433 --> 01:35:34.736
and the Maratha's formidable presence bore fruit.

01:35:34.736 --> 01:35:36.805
The French were decimated

01:35:36.805 --> 01:35:39.941
and left with a weakened army in the Indian theater.

01:35:40.942 --> 01:35:44.246
While in America, though, the French were ready to defend.

01:35:44.246 --> 01:35:46.348
However, they did not expect the British

01:35:46.348 --> 01:35:48.383
under General Jeffrey Amherst

01:35:48.383 --> 01:35:51.820
to attack Louisbourg on the eastern shores of Canada.

01:35:51.820 --> 01:35:53.822
The naval bombardment began,

01:35:53.822 --> 01:35:56.892
cannonballs tearing through the air with thunderous roars

01:35:56.892 --> 01:35:59.895
as British ships unleashed their fury on the fortress.

01:35:59.895 --> 01:36:03.131
Day after day, the relentless barrage continued,

01:36:03.131 --> 01:36:05.967
breaching walls and weakening the defenders within.

01:36:05.967 --> 01:36:10.739
On June 23rd, 1758, the assault reached its climax.

01:36:10.739 --> 01:36:13.041
British troops stormed the breached walls,

01:36:13.041 --> 01:36:15.510
muskets firing, bayonets fixed.

01:36:15.510 --> 01:36:17.179
The defenders fought bravely,

01:36:17.179 --> 01:36:20.482
but the relentless British advance proved unstoppable.

01:36:20.482 --> 01:36:23.318
Street by street, bastion by bastion,

01:36:23.318 --> 01:36:26.121
the fortress was rested from French hands.

01:36:26.121 --> 01:36:27.989
Two weeks later, on July 8th,

01:36:27.989 --> 01:36:31.660
British General James Abercrombie devised an audacious plan

01:36:31.660 --> 01:36:35.330
to capture the fortress of Carillon in modern-day New York.

01:36:35.330 --> 01:36:38.300
With their large amount of troops and military planning,

01:36:38.300 --> 01:36:40.402
they felt they were ready to take over.

01:36:40.402 --> 01:36:43.438
However, French Commander Louis-Joseph de Montcalm

01:36:43.438 --> 01:36:45.473
had fortified Carillon well.

01:36:45.473 --> 01:36:48.443
The fortress stood amidst a labyrinth of dense woods

01:36:48.443 --> 01:36:49.778
and rugged terrain.

01:36:49.778 --> 01:36:51.713
It was not just a fortress.

01:36:51.713 --> 01:36:53.949
It was a natural stronghold.

01:36:53.949 --> 01:36:56.751
The battle began with a determined British assault.

01:36:56.751 --> 01:36:58.820
Canons roared, muskets cracked,

01:36:58.820 --> 01:37:01.189
and the clash of steel filled the air.

01:37:01.189 --> 01:37:04.226
The British and American colonial troops pressed forward,

01:37:04.226 --> 01:37:06.628
but the French defenses were formidable.

01:37:06.628 --> 01:37:09.598
General Montcalm's troops, fighting with resolve,

01:37:09.598 --> 01:37:10.932
held their ground.

01:37:10.932 --> 01:37:12.601
The British and colonial forces

01:37:12.601 --> 01:37:14.803
could not breach the French defenses

01:37:14.803 --> 01:37:16.671
despite repeated attempts.

01:37:16.671 --> 01:37:19.941
The fortress of Carillon remained impregnable.

01:37:19.941 --> 01:37:21.443
As casualties mounted,

01:37:21.443 --> 01:37:24.846
Major General Abercrombie made a difficult decision

01:37:24.846 --> 01:37:26.348
to order a retreat.

01:37:26.348 --> 01:37:30.619
Next year, in 1759, the British were back at Fort Carillon,

01:37:30.619 --> 01:37:34.589
determined to take it over, this time under General Amherst,

01:37:34.589 --> 01:37:36.691
and through meticulous planning and luck,

01:37:36.691 --> 01:37:39.160
the English could take over the fort easily

01:37:39.160 --> 01:37:41.730
and renamed it Fort Ticonderoga.

01:37:41.730 --> 01:37:45.200
This created a new target for the British, Quebec.

01:37:45.200 --> 01:37:47.636
At first, Major General James Wolfe

01:37:47.636 --> 01:37:49.271
and Admiral Charles Saunders

01:37:49.271 --> 01:37:51.506
tried to besiege the city of Quebec.

01:37:51.506 --> 01:37:54.376
However, they were unprepared and retreated.

01:37:54.376 --> 01:37:57.612
Within Quebec, Montcalm's French defenders prepared

01:37:57.612 --> 01:37:59.481
for the inevitable showdown.

01:37:59.481 --> 01:38:03.885
The fateful day came on September 13th, 1759.

01:38:03.885 --> 01:38:06.288
Wolfe hatched a daring plan.

01:38:06.288 --> 01:38:07.622
Under the cover of night,

01:38:07.622 --> 01:38:11.459
British troops scaled these seemingly insurmountable cliffs

01:38:11.459 --> 01:38:15.363
and descended upon the Plains of Abraham like ghosts.

01:38:15.363 --> 01:38:17.632
The Battle of the Plains of Abraham began

01:38:17.632 --> 01:38:19.134
in the dim light of dawn

01:38:19.134 --> 01:38:21.636
in a brief but furious clash.

01:38:21.636 --> 01:38:24.105
The fate of Quebec hung in the balance.

01:38:24.105 --> 01:38:26.875
Both leaders, Wolfe and Montcalm, fell wounded

01:38:26.875 --> 01:38:28.109
in the heat of the battle.

01:38:28.109 --> 01:38:29.944
Wolfe, mortally injured,

01:38:29.944 --> 01:38:33.982
gazed upon the victory he had secured with his last breath.

01:38:33.982 --> 01:38:35.317
As the dust settled,

01:38:35.317 --> 01:38:38.420
news reached Wolfe that the British had emerged triumphant.

01:38:38.420 --> 01:38:40.789
The Plains of Abraham were theirs.

01:38:40.789 --> 01:38:42.891
But it came at a heavy cost.

01:38:42.891 --> 01:38:45.760
Wolfe had given his life for victory.

01:38:45.760 --> 01:38:49.064
With their city surrounded and supplies dwindling,

01:38:49.064 --> 01:38:51.900
the French forces had no choice but to surrender.

01:38:51.900 --> 01:38:54.669
On September 18th, 1759,

01:38:54.669 --> 01:38:57.305
Quebec, the bastion of New France,

01:38:57.305 --> 01:38:59.040
fell into British hands.

01:38:59.040 --> 01:39:02.610
India, while all the way across the world in Madras,

01:39:02.610 --> 01:39:03.445
the French,

01:39:03.445 --> 01:39:06.147
under General Thomas Lally Tollendal's leadership,

01:39:06.147 --> 01:39:09.150
sought to eliminate England from the continent.

01:39:09.150 --> 01:39:10.285
The French forces,

01:39:10.285 --> 01:39:13.455
bolstered by Indian allies from the Mysore kingdom,

01:39:13.455 --> 01:39:14.856
descended upon the city

01:39:14.856 --> 01:39:18.159
with a fervor matched only by the sweltering heat.

01:39:18.159 --> 01:39:20.528
Cannons roared, muskets crackled,

01:39:20.528 --> 01:39:22.130
and the battlefield was enveloped

01:39:22.130 --> 01:39:24.966
in a tumultuous cloud of smoke and dust.

01:39:24.966 --> 01:39:27.502
The fate of Madras hung in the balance.

01:39:27.502 --> 01:39:29.904
Under the command of Colonel Eyre Coote,

01:39:29.904 --> 01:39:33.508
the British defenders put up a tenacious resistance.

01:39:33.508 --> 01:39:35.643
Wave after wave of French assaults

01:39:35.643 --> 01:39:38.079
crashed against their determined ranks.

01:39:38.079 --> 01:39:40.482
The battle raged on for hours

01:39:40.482 --> 01:39:42.884
and the outcome remained uncertain.

01:39:42.884 --> 01:39:44.786
As the sun began its descent,

01:39:44.786 --> 01:39:47.021
a momentous turning point occurred.

01:39:47.021 --> 01:39:50.492
A British counterattack led by Colonel Coote struck

01:39:50.492 --> 01:39:52.427
at the heart of the French lines.

01:39:52.427 --> 01:39:54.095
The British soldiers' resolve,

01:39:54.095 --> 01:39:56.698
their disciplined musket fire volleys,

01:39:56.698 --> 01:39:59.934
and the cannons' thunder broke the French advance.

01:39:59.934 --> 01:40:02.103
The French forces, battered and weary,

01:40:02.103 --> 01:40:03.838
were forced to withdraw.

01:40:03.838 --> 01:40:05.073
As the year turned,

01:40:05.073 --> 01:40:07.342
the battleground shifted to Wandiwash,

01:40:07.342 --> 01:40:08.977
a region in southern India.

01:40:08.977 --> 01:40:10.945
Now a seasoned commander,

01:40:10.945 --> 01:40:13.882
General Eyre Coote faced off against the French,

01:40:13.882 --> 01:40:16.851
under Comte de Lally Tollendal yet again.

01:40:16.851 --> 01:40:19.821
Despite their determination, the French were weakened

01:40:19.821 --> 01:40:22.824
by attrition, disease, and dwindling resources

01:40:22.824 --> 01:40:25.126
from the prolonged siege of Wandiwash.

01:40:25.126 --> 01:40:27.228
General Coote, seizing the moment,

01:40:27.228 --> 01:40:30.165
orchestrated a well-coordinated assault.

01:40:30.165 --> 01:40:33.701
The British forces pressed forward with unwavering resolve.

01:40:33.701 --> 01:40:37.272
As the day drew to a close, the outcome became clear.

01:40:37.272 --> 01:40:39.040
The French defenses crumbled

01:40:39.040 --> 01:40:41.543
before the relentless British advance.

01:40:41.543 --> 01:40:44.145
Comte de Lally Tollendal was captured.

01:40:45.246 --> 01:40:47.816
The only remaining French city in North America

01:40:47.816 --> 01:40:50.118
was the stronghold of Montreal,

01:40:50.118 --> 01:40:52.487
which was the target of attack a year later.

01:40:52.487 --> 01:40:54.589
British General Jeffery Amherst planned

01:40:54.589 --> 01:40:57.959
a multi-pronged campaign to encircle Montreal.

01:40:57.959 --> 01:41:00.662
Columns of British troops moved precisely,

01:41:00.662 --> 01:41:03.164
one advancing along the St. Lawrence River,

01:41:03.164 --> 01:41:05.266
another ascending Lake Champlain,

01:41:05.266 --> 01:41:08.303
and a third pushing northward from Lake Ontario.

01:41:08.303 --> 01:41:11.172
However, the French were easily outnumbered.

01:41:11.172 --> 01:41:13.341
The noose tightened around Montreal

01:41:13.341 --> 01:41:15.310
as days turned into weeks.

01:41:15.310 --> 01:41:17.412
Weary and without hope of relief,

01:41:17.412 --> 01:41:19.747
the French garrison finally capitulated

01:41:19.747 --> 01:41:22.417
on September 8th, 1760,

01:41:22.417 --> 01:41:26.621
marking the end of French colonial rule in Canada.

01:41:26.621 --> 01:41:29.390
While a similar fate was in store for the French

01:41:29.390 --> 01:41:31.392
in the Indian subcontinent,

01:41:31.392 --> 01:41:33.795
as in the heart of the Coromandel Coast,

01:41:33.795 --> 01:41:35.530
the British forces laid siege

01:41:35.530 --> 01:41:37.866
to the mighty city of Pondicherry.

01:41:37.866 --> 01:41:41.002
The city was fortified, its defenses formidable,

01:41:41.002 --> 01:41:44.839
but as months and the siege continued relentlessly,

01:41:44.839 --> 01:41:48.309
British cannons bombarded the city over and over again

01:41:48.309 --> 01:41:51.679
until January 15th, 1761,

01:41:51.679 --> 01:41:53.948
when Pondicherry was capitulated.

01:41:53.948 --> 01:41:56.251
Later, the army would continue capturing

01:41:56.251 --> 01:42:00.021
the nearby French enclaves of Karaikal and Yanam.

01:42:00.021 --> 01:42:01.523
The British army would continue

01:42:01.523 --> 01:42:04.926
through the Malabar Coast near the Arabian Sea,

01:42:04.926 --> 01:42:07.195
capturing the French town of Mahe.

01:42:07.195 --> 01:42:08.863
While in the Mysore region,

01:42:08.863 --> 01:42:11.065
British forces in the kingdom of Hyderabad

01:42:11.065 --> 01:42:13.902
clashed with the French and Mysorean troops

01:42:13.902 --> 01:42:15.737
near Seringapatam.

01:42:15.737 --> 01:42:16.871
Upon the outcome was clear,

01:42:16.871 --> 01:42:19.641
the British and their allies emerged triumphant,

01:42:19.641 --> 01:42:22.377
eliminating French power in the subcontinent.

01:42:23.278 --> 01:42:25.914
However, the British were not done.

01:42:25.914 --> 01:42:27.749
In the Caribbean, the British were able

01:42:27.749 --> 01:42:30.652
to capture the islands of Guadalupe, Dominica,

01:42:30.652 --> 01:42:34.522
Martinique, Saint Lucia, and Grenada from the French

01:42:34.522 --> 01:42:36.524
and Havana from the Spanish.

01:42:36.524 --> 01:42:38.026
It was clear to the world

01:42:38.026 --> 01:42:41.195
that the English were the ones to be in control.

01:42:41.195 --> 01:42:44.065
From the Caribbean to North America to India,

01:42:44.065 --> 01:42:47.635
the world was British, flying under the Union Jack.

01:42:47.635 --> 01:42:50.572
(dramatic music)

01:42:50.572 --> 01:42:52.407
Due to their military success,

01:42:52.407 --> 01:42:54.142
the British was quite triumphant

01:42:54.142 --> 01:42:56.544
when it came to peace talks in Paris.

01:42:56.544 --> 01:42:59.714
France agreed to cede Canada to the British Empire

01:42:59.714 --> 01:43:00.848
as long as the rights

01:43:00.848 --> 01:43:04.018
of French Roman Catholics in Canada were protected.

01:43:04.018 --> 01:43:06.788
The Spanish, still wanting to control Havana,

01:43:06.788 --> 01:43:09.524
made a trade England couldn't refuse.

01:43:09.524 --> 01:43:11.960
Havana would return to Spanish control

01:43:11.960 --> 01:43:14.562
in exchange for the swamplands of Florida

01:43:14.562 --> 01:43:16.164
in the American South.

01:43:16.164 --> 01:43:19.267
For India, the treaty reaffirmed British control

01:43:19.267 --> 01:43:21.970
of Bengal, Madras, and Bombay.

01:43:21.970 --> 01:43:25.039
The British were on top of the world.

01:43:26.674 --> 01:43:29.777
The English, reeling in debt and collectively weak,

01:43:29.777 --> 01:43:33.081
wanted to maintain peace in North America with the natives.

01:43:33.081 --> 01:43:36.951
So they passed the proclamation of 1763,

01:43:36.951 --> 01:43:38.453
which created a boundary line

01:43:38.453 --> 01:43:40.388
across the Appalachian mountains

01:43:40.388 --> 01:43:42.523
from Nova Scotia to Florida.

01:43:42.523 --> 01:43:45.994
Westward expansion by American colonists beyond this line

01:43:45.994 --> 01:43:47.729
was strictly prohibited.

01:43:47.729 --> 01:43:50.298
The British hoped to avoid costly conflicts

01:43:50.298 --> 01:43:53.635
with Native American tribes by creating a buffer zone.

01:43:53.635 --> 01:43:56.871
However, the Ohio company under George Washington

01:43:56.871 --> 01:43:59.440
blatantly ignored such regulations

01:43:59.440 --> 01:44:01.643
because they were already there.

01:44:01.643 --> 01:44:04.479
Nevertheless, the English parliament was right

01:44:04.479 --> 01:44:07.749
because the war chief of the Odawa tribe, Pontiac,

01:44:07.749 --> 01:44:10.952
and his allies were gearing up to attack.

01:44:10.952 --> 01:44:14.822
In May 1763, the Native Americans laid siege

01:44:14.822 --> 01:44:16.090
to Fort Detroit,

01:44:16.090 --> 01:44:18.059
which would be followed by the sieging

01:44:18.059 --> 01:44:20.862
of Fort Michilimackinac and Fort Sandusky.

01:44:20.862 --> 01:44:22.263
The British were stunned

01:44:22.263 --> 01:44:25.700
by the coordination and ferocity of these attacks.

01:44:25.700 --> 01:44:27.368
As the conflict escalated,

01:44:27.368 --> 01:44:30.738
the British under Colonel Henry Bouquet devised a plan

01:44:30.738 --> 01:44:34.542
to break the siege at Fort Pitt, formerly Fort Duquesne.

01:44:34.542 --> 01:44:38.680
The Battle of Bushy Run in 1763 was fierce,

01:44:38.680 --> 01:44:40.982
but it showcased British resilience

01:44:40.982 --> 01:44:43.484
and signaled that they could effectively counter

01:44:43.484 --> 01:44:45.319
Native American assaults.

01:44:45.319 --> 01:44:48.189
Pontiac, however, was not just a warrior.

01:44:48.189 --> 01:44:49.691
He was a diplomat as well.

01:44:49.691 --> 01:44:51.392
He crisscrossed the wilderness,

01:44:51.392 --> 01:44:54.262
forging alliances and building a loose coalition

01:44:54.262 --> 01:44:55.663
among the tribes.

01:44:55.663 --> 01:44:57.865
His leadership was instrumental

01:44:57.865 --> 01:44:59.867
in keeping the rebellion alive.

01:44:59.867 --> 01:45:04.372
By 1764, the rebellion began to lose momentum.

01:45:04.372 --> 01:45:07.575
Many tribal leaders recognized that continued fighting

01:45:07.575 --> 01:45:10.078
might not achieve their desired outcomes.

01:45:10.078 --> 01:45:14.949
Negotiations commenced, and eventually there was peace.

01:45:14.949 --> 01:45:18.052
(gentle music)

01:45:18.052 --> 01:45:19.754
After over a hundred years

01:45:19.754 --> 01:45:22.290
of dealing with the British East India Company,

01:45:22.290 --> 01:45:25.059
the Mughal Empire was in a state of decline

01:45:25.059 --> 01:45:26.427
and near collapse,

01:45:26.427 --> 01:45:29.063
while the English were able to get rights to India

01:45:29.063 --> 01:45:30.732
through the Treaty of Paris.

01:45:30.732 --> 01:45:35.503
Hence, in 1765, England signed the Treaty of Allahabad

01:45:35.503 --> 01:45:37.004
with the Mughal Empire,

01:45:37.004 --> 01:45:40.341
which changed British relations in the subcontinent.

01:45:40.341 --> 01:45:41.309
This treaty granted

01:45:41.309 --> 01:45:44.545
the English East India Company Diwani rights,

01:45:44.545 --> 01:45:47.315
or the right to collect taxes.

01:45:47.315 --> 01:45:49.250
This means the company was given the right

01:45:49.250 --> 01:45:52.353
to collect revenue, land revenue administration,

01:45:52.353 --> 01:45:55.790
on behalf of the Mughal Emperor Shah Alam II

01:45:55.790 --> 01:45:59.293
in the provinces of Bengal, Bihar, and Orissa.

01:45:59.293 --> 01:46:01.562
Essentially, the company gained control

01:46:01.562 --> 01:46:03.364
over these territories' economic

01:46:03.364 --> 01:46:05.366
and financial administration.

01:46:05.366 --> 01:46:07.235
In return for the Diwani rights,

01:46:07.235 --> 01:46:09.170
the British East India Company agreed

01:46:09.170 --> 01:46:12.974
to pay an annual tribute of 2.6 million rupees

01:46:12.974 --> 01:46:14.642
to the Mughal Emperor.

01:46:14.642 --> 01:46:16.644
This was seen as a symbolic gesture

01:46:16.644 --> 01:46:19.547
to maintain the appearance of Mughal sovereignty.

01:46:19.547 --> 01:46:23.518
In principle, though, they were now colonies of the British.

01:46:24.786 --> 01:46:26.621
Even with the Treaty of Allahabad,

01:46:26.621 --> 01:46:28.156
the British were in financial debt

01:46:28.156 --> 01:46:29.624
after the Seven Years' War.

01:46:29.624 --> 01:46:33.995
So in America, they passed the Stamp Act of 1765,

01:46:33.995 --> 01:46:35.830
which required American colonists

01:46:35.830 --> 01:46:38.065
to place an embossed revenue stamp

01:46:38.065 --> 01:46:40.802
on virtually all printed documents.

01:46:40.802 --> 01:46:43.204
The way to receive this stamp is by paying money

01:46:43.204 --> 01:46:46.741
directly to the British government as direct tax.

01:46:46.741 --> 01:46:49.477
The purpose of this act was for the British military

01:46:49.477 --> 01:46:52.380
to pay their troops after the Seven Year War.

01:46:52.380 --> 01:46:55.383
However, the colonists detested this new policy,

01:46:55.383 --> 01:46:57.118
so they came up with a slogan,

01:46:57.118 --> 01:47:00.254
"No taxation without representation,"

01:47:00.254 --> 01:47:03.491
since they were not included in the English Parliament.

01:47:03.491 --> 01:47:06.394
Due to this immediate backlash from the tax,

01:47:06.394 --> 01:47:09.530
it was repealed and replaced by the Declaratory Act,

01:47:09.530 --> 01:47:11.566
which says, "Parliament had hath,

01:47:11.566 --> 01:47:13.501
and of right ought to have,

01:47:13.501 --> 01:47:16.737
full power and authority to make laws and statutes

01:47:16.737 --> 01:47:19.273
of sufficient force and validity

01:47:19.273 --> 01:47:22.043
to bind the colonies and people of America

01:47:22.043 --> 01:47:24.478
in all cases whatsoever."

01:47:24.478 --> 01:47:25.880
The British felt they had the right

01:47:25.880 --> 01:47:28.583
to do whatever they wanted with their colonies.

01:47:28.583 --> 01:47:30.084
The question remained,

01:47:30.084 --> 01:47:32.987
what would the American colonies do about it?

01:47:34.488 --> 01:47:37.091
While the Americans were upset about taxation,

01:47:37.091 --> 01:47:39.293
the English were not done expanding.

01:47:39.293 --> 01:47:43.865
When James Cook in 1768 embarked on the HMS Endeavour,

01:47:43.865 --> 01:47:44.999
he was sent on a mission

01:47:44.999 --> 01:47:48.369
to explore the mysterious and vast South Pacific.

01:47:48.369 --> 01:47:50.304
With sails billowing in the wind,

01:47:50.304 --> 01:47:51.505
Cook and his crew departed

01:47:51.505 --> 01:47:53.608
from Plymouth, England, in August.

01:47:53.608 --> 01:47:56.210
Their destination was the farthest reaches

01:47:56.210 --> 01:47:57.678
of the known world

01:47:57.678 --> 01:48:00.314
where the boundaries of science and discovery

01:48:00.314 --> 01:48:03.351
blurred into the infinite blue horizon.

01:48:03.351 --> 01:48:05.987
After years of arduous sea travel,

01:48:05.987 --> 01:48:07.889
they made it to the Southern Hemisphere,

01:48:07.889 --> 01:48:10.358
where, in April 1770,

01:48:10.358 --> 01:48:13.194
they discovered an unexpected landmass.

01:48:13.194 --> 01:48:14.395
Before this part,

01:48:14.395 --> 01:48:17.899
explorers thought they had the entire world figured out,

01:48:17.899 --> 01:48:20.668
but yet, James Cook just stumbled upon

01:48:20.668 --> 01:48:23.037
the continent of Australia.

01:48:23.037 --> 01:48:25.406
Cook and his crew made their first landfall

01:48:25.406 --> 01:48:27.975
at a place now known as Botany Bay

01:48:27.975 --> 01:48:30.878
in what would become New South Wales, Australia.

01:48:30.878 --> 01:48:33.414
Stepping ashore, they encountered a landscape

01:48:33.414 --> 01:48:35.750
unlike any they had seen before.

01:48:35.750 --> 01:48:38.386
Exotic flora and fauna greeted them,

01:48:38.386 --> 01:48:40.021
as did the Indigenous people

01:48:40.021 --> 01:48:42.390
who had called this land home for millennia.

01:48:42.390 --> 01:48:45.359
Cook's mission was not just to claim the land for Britain,

01:48:45.359 --> 01:48:47.595
but also to record the area.

01:48:47.595 --> 01:48:50.464
Cook and his crew spent months meticulously charting

01:48:50.464 --> 01:48:53.334
the eastern coastline of this vast continent.

01:48:53.334 --> 01:48:54.602
They sailed northward,

01:48:54.602 --> 01:48:57.805
their maps growing more detailed with each passing day.

01:48:57.805 --> 01:48:59.473
Cook was a skilled navigator

01:48:59.473 --> 01:49:03.377
whose precise measurements in cartography were unrivaled.

01:49:03.377 --> 01:49:04.979
As they ventured farther north,

01:49:04.979 --> 01:49:07.048
they encountered a range of environments,

01:49:07.048 --> 01:49:11.285
from dense rainforests to pristine beaches and coral reefs,

01:49:11.285 --> 01:49:13.821
to kangaroos and koalas,

01:49:13.821 --> 01:49:16.190
to venomous snakes and crocodiles.

01:49:16.190 --> 01:49:17.258
The world's newest

01:49:17.258 --> 01:49:20.461
and most dangerous frontier was discovered.

01:49:20.461 --> 01:49:22.129
With the east coast of Australia

01:49:22.129 --> 01:49:23.764
thoroughly mapped and explored,

01:49:23.764 --> 01:49:25.433
Cook formally claimed possession

01:49:25.433 --> 01:49:27.635
of the eastern shore for Great Britain,

01:49:27.635 --> 01:49:29.270
naming it New South Wales

01:49:29.270 --> 01:49:32.273
with hopes of one day making it a formal colony.

01:49:32.273 --> 01:49:35.242
His declaration would set in motion a new chapter

01:49:35.242 --> 01:49:37.211
in the history of this land,

01:49:37.211 --> 01:49:39.847
the empire that spans the world.

01:49:39.847 --> 01:49:42.850
This newfound discovery has made the British Empire

01:49:42.850 --> 01:49:44.618
a pinnacle for the world.

01:49:44.618 --> 01:49:46.854
As an Irishman and the governor of Grenada,

01:49:46.854 --> 01:49:48.356
George Macartney would write,

01:49:48.356 --> 01:49:51.692
"This vast empire on which the sun never sets,

01:49:51.692 --> 01:49:54.628
and whose bounds nature has not yet ascertained."

01:49:54.628 --> 01:49:56.964
From the French-speaking colony of Quebec

01:49:56.964 --> 01:49:59.033
to the Quaker city of Philadelphia,

01:49:59.033 --> 01:50:01.535
to the slave plantations of Georgia,

01:50:01.535 --> 01:50:03.971
to the islands of Grenada and Jamaica,

01:50:03.971 --> 01:50:05.639
to the neighbor of Ireland,

01:50:05.639 --> 01:50:07.475
to the homeland of England,

01:50:07.475 --> 01:50:11.012
to Cape Coast in Africa, to the province of Bengal,

01:50:11.012 --> 01:50:14.482
to the newly discovered land of New South Wales,

01:50:14.482 --> 01:50:15.816
wherever you go,

01:50:15.816 --> 01:50:19.120
the sun will always shine on the British Empire.

01:50:19.120 --> 01:50:21.856
(dramatic music)

01:50:23.824 --> 01:50:26.794
But sometimes the sun can shine too bright,

01:50:26.794 --> 01:50:29.230
because a revolution was on the horizon

01:50:29.230 --> 01:50:31.899
in the 13 colonies of America.

01:50:31.899 --> 01:50:34.869
On July 4th, 1776,

01:50:34.869 --> 01:50:36.404
a famous letter was signed

01:50:36.404 --> 01:50:38.406
in Independence Hall in Philadelphia

01:50:38.406 --> 01:50:41.709
titled The Declaration of Independence

01:50:41.709 --> 01:50:44.779
with the words that echo throughout America today,

01:50:44.779 --> 01:50:47.381
"We hold these truths to be self-evident

01:50:47.381 --> 01:50:49.350
that all men are created equal,

01:50:49.350 --> 01:50:51.285
that they are endowed by their creator

01:50:51.285 --> 01:50:53.587
with certain unalienable rights,

01:50:53.587 --> 01:50:56.090
that among these are life, liberty,

01:50:56.090 --> 01:50:57.958
and the pursuit of happiness."

01:50:57.958 --> 01:51:01.028
However, this document wasn't just a battle cry

01:51:01.028 --> 01:51:02.897
for the American colonists.

01:51:02.897 --> 01:51:05.332
Rather, it was a scathing letter

01:51:05.332 --> 01:51:07.701
directed towards King George III

01:51:07.701 --> 01:51:11.205
with 27 reasons why they were revolting.

01:51:11.205 --> 01:51:13.541
As the American founding fathers would put it,

01:51:13.541 --> 01:51:15.509
the colonies of the Americas were founded

01:51:15.509 --> 01:51:17.378
on the principles of freedom.

01:51:17.378 --> 01:51:19.580
The original colonists moved to America

01:51:19.580 --> 01:51:20.748
because they objected

01:51:20.748 --> 01:51:23.384
to the current religious or economic situation

01:51:23.384 --> 01:51:25.086
within the British mainland.

01:51:25.086 --> 01:51:27.521
They were the ones who rejected their rules.

01:51:27.521 --> 01:51:30.257
They were the ones who wanted to create their own way.

01:51:30.257 --> 01:51:34.061
And so when John Hancock signed his name in giant letters

01:51:34.061 --> 01:51:36.864
followed by 55 of his compatriots,

01:51:36.864 --> 01:51:39.467
a war for freedom was on.

01:51:39.467 --> 01:51:41.635
General George Washington and his men

01:51:41.635 --> 01:51:43.370
were in Long Island, New York,

01:51:43.370 --> 01:51:45.806
desperate to defend the American home front.

01:51:45.806 --> 01:51:47.208
His Continental Army,

01:51:47.208 --> 01:51:50.277
composed mainly of civilians turned soldiers,

01:51:50.277 --> 01:51:53.514
now bore the weight of America's newfound freedom.

01:51:53.514 --> 01:51:55.983
They held a fervent belief in liberty,

01:51:55.983 --> 01:51:59.887
but lacked the seasoned experience of their adversaries.

01:51:59.887 --> 01:52:03.090
Across the water, British General William Howe prepared

01:52:03.090 --> 01:52:04.692
for a swift victory.

01:52:04.692 --> 01:52:06.026
A professional soldier

01:52:06.026 --> 01:52:08.562
with a record of battlefield successes,

01:52:08.562 --> 01:52:12.566
Howe was determined to put this colonial rebellion to rest.

01:52:12.566 --> 01:52:14.869
With his disciplined British soldiers,

01:52:14.869 --> 01:52:16.670
hired Hessian mercenaries,

01:52:16.670 --> 01:52:18.572
and loyalists supporting him,

01:52:18.572 --> 01:52:22.276
the stage was set for a grand military display.

01:52:22.276 --> 01:52:26.647
As dawn broke on August 27th, 1776,

01:52:26.647 --> 01:52:29.450
the serene landscapes of Brooklyn were ruptured

01:52:29.450 --> 01:52:31.352
by the sounds of warfare.

01:52:31.352 --> 01:52:33.554
Utilizing their superior training,

01:52:33.554 --> 01:52:35.256
the British soldiers executed

01:52:35.256 --> 01:52:37.625
an ingenious flanking maneuver.

01:52:37.625 --> 01:52:40.394
The American defenders were taken by surprise

01:52:40.394 --> 01:52:41.662
and forced to retreat,

01:52:41.662 --> 01:52:44.331
allowing the British to retake New York.

01:52:44.331 --> 01:52:46.133
However, by December,

01:52:46.133 --> 01:52:48.869
George Washington wasn't ready to give up.

01:52:48.869 --> 01:52:52.573
His new target was the Hessian camp in Trenton, New Jersey.

01:52:52.573 --> 01:52:54.942
With 2,400 men in tow,

01:52:54.942 --> 01:52:57.878
Washington began the dangerous crossing.

01:52:57.878 --> 01:53:01.448
Navigating treacherous ice flows and fighting exhaustion,

01:53:01.448 --> 01:53:03.417
they reached New Jersey's shores.

01:53:03.417 --> 01:53:05.319
With the darkness as their cloak,

01:53:05.319 --> 01:53:06.854
they marched towards Trenton,

01:53:06.854 --> 01:53:08.088
muskets at the ready,

01:53:08.088 --> 01:53:09.857
spurred on by the promise of dawn

01:53:09.857 --> 01:53:12.026
and the element of surprise.

01:53:12.026 --> 01:53:14.795
As the first light of December 26th broke,

01:53:14.795 --> 01:53:16.497
the Continental Army descended

01:53:16.497 --> 01:53:18.399
on the sleepy town of Trenton.

01:53:18.399 --> 01:53:20.768
The Hessians, caught entirely off guard,

01:53:20.768 --> 01:53:22.736
scrambled to their positions.

01:53:22.736 --> 01:53:26.140
Their muskets, dampened by the cold, failed to fire.

01:53:26.140 --> 01:53:29.643
While the booming voices of American sergeants echoed orders

01:53:29.643 --> 01:53:31.378
in the early morning air,

01:53:31.378 --> 01:53:34.014
the Hessians, overwhelmed and outmaneuvered,

01:53:34.014 --> 01:53:36.784
surrendered to the resurgent Americans.

01:53:36.784 --> 01:53:39.353
However, the British were not done.

01:53:39.353 --> 01:53:44.325
By September 1777, General John Burgoyne hatched a plan

01:53:44.325 --> 01:53:47.328
to sever New England from the rest of the colonies,

01:53:47.328 --> 01:53:48.495
but the Americans,

01:53:48.495 --> 01:53:50.998
under the leadership of General Horatio Gates

01:53:50.998 --> 01:53:52.233
and Benedict Arnold,

01:53:52.233 --> 01:53:53.667
stood in defiance.

01:53:53.667 --> 01:53:55.569
Saratoga became the stage

01:53:55.569 --> 01:53:58.339
where the fate of two worlds would be decided.

01:53:58.339 --> 01:53:59.673
At Freeman's Farm,

01:53:59.673 --> 01:54:02.610
the first encounter saw the Americans push back,

01:54:02.610 --> 01:54:05.212
but it wasn't a clear victory for Burgoyne.

01:54:05.212 --> 01:54:07.448
His forces were heavily bruised.

01:54:07.448 --> 01:54:09.883
A few weeks later, at Bemis Heights,

01:54:09.883 --> 01:54:12.019
the British would taste the full wrath

01:54:12.019 --> 01:54:13.520
of the American spirit.

01:54:13.520 --> 01:54:16.790
Against the odds, the Continentals held firm,

01:54:16.790 --> 01:54:18.592
repelling the British assault.

01:54:18.592 --> 01:54:22.630
By October 17th, a shocked and humiliated Burgoyne

01:54:22.630 --> 01:54:24.965
surrendered his entire army.

01:54:24.965 --> 01:54:26.867
The Americans won.

01:54:26.867 --> 01:54:29.703
News traveled to the corners of the world,

01:54:29.703 --> 01:54:32.406
including the Versailles' place in Paris.

01:54:32.406 --> 01:54:36.410
King Louis XVI, who was bitter at the French humiliation

01:54:36.410 --> 01:54:38.178
during the Seven Years' War,

01:54:38.178 --> 01:54:41.482
saw his chance to defeat and weaken the British.

01:54:41.482 --> 01:54:44.785
The victory of Saratoga was undeniable proof

01:54:44.785 --> 01:54:47.121
that America could win this war,

01:54:47.121 --> 01:54:49.456
which allowed diplomat Benjamin Franklin

01:54:49.456 --> 01:54:51.625
to convince King Louis XVI

01:54:51.625 --> 01:54:54.928
to join the war against their mutual enemy.

01:54:54.928 --> 01:54:58.465
Their Franco-American alliance was the united front

01:54:58.465 --> 01:54:59.533
of the Americans

01:54:59.533 --> 01:55:03.037
in the siege of Yorktown in 1781.

01:55:03.037 --> 01:55:06.740
The esteemed British General Lord Charles Cornwallis

01:55:06.740 --> 01:55:08.942
had led his troops into Yorktown.

01:55:08.942 --> 01:55:11.912
The peninsula, he believed, was a stronghold.

01:55:11.912 --> 01:55:13.580
Its access to the York River

01:55:13.580 --> 01:55:16.417
meant the British Navy could quickly reinforce

01:55:16.417 --> 01:55:17.818
or evacuate them.

01:55:17.818 --> 01:55:20.721
But as he said about fortifying his position,

01:55:20.721 --> 01:55:23.123
little did he know that the web of fate

01:55:23.123 --> 01:55:25.025
was unweaving against him.

01:55:25.025 --> 01:55:27.861
They knew what to do once General George Washington

01:55:27.861 --> 01:55:30.931
and French General Jean-Baptiste Rochambeau heard

01:55:30.931 --> 01:55:32.933
of Cornwallis' location,

01:55:32.933 --> 01:55:35.169
to lay siege to Yorktown.

01:55:35.169 --> 01:55:36.770
As September wore on,

01:55:36.770 --> 01:55:40.174
Cornwallis began to sense the encroaching danger.

01:55:40.174 --> 01:55:42.242
Washington and Rochambeau's forces

01:55:42.242 --> 01:55:44.144
had begun their relentless march,

01:55:44.144 --> 01:55:46.914
and soon the outskirts of Yorktown echoed

01:55:46.914 --> 01:55:49.416
with the march of thousands of boots.

01:55:49.416 --> 01:55:52.886
But the true shock for Cornwallis came from the water.

01:55:52.886 --> 01:55:54.188
The French had bested

01:55:54.188 --> 01:55:56.990
the mighty British fleet, his lifeline.

01:55:56.990 --> 01:55:58.792
The York River and the Chesapeake Bay

01:55:58.792 --> 01:56:01.228
were no longer his escape routes.

01:56:01.228 --> 01:56:02.629
They were traps.

01:56:02.629 --> 01:56:04.531
The siege began with an intensity

01:56:04.531 --> 01:56:07.901
that shook the very foundations of Yorktown.

01:56:07.901 --> 01:56:11.238
Day after day, the American and French cannons fired,

01:56:11.238 --> 01:56:13.273
weakening the British defenses.

01:56:13.273 --> 01:56:16.043
The morale of Cornwallis' men plummeted

01:56:16.043 --> 01:56:19.113
as provisions ran low and hope grew dimmer.

01:56:19.113 --> 01:56:23.117
By mid-October, the situation for Cornwallis grew desperate.

01:56:23.117 --> 01:56:24.818
His defenses crumbled.

01:56:24.818 --> 01:56:28.422
His men were demoralized and escape routes were sealed.

01:56:28.422 --> 01:56:30.724
On the morning of October 17th,

01:56:30.724 --> 01:56:33.427
a white flag rose over Yorktown.

01:56:33.427 --> 01:56:36.830
Cornwallis sought a ceasefire and surrendered.

01:56:36.830 --> 01:56:40.200
Two years later, the Treaty of Paris 1783

01:56:40.200 --> 01:56:41.902
was signed in Paris

01:56:41.902 --> 01:56:45.005
and America was officially independent,

01:56:45.005 --> 01:56:48.475
creating a physical border between the free Americans

01:56:48.475 --> 01:56:50.878
and the British colonies of Quebec.

01:56:50.878 --> 01:56:54.748
The once enemies are now neighbors.

01:56:54.748 --> 01:56:57.651
(dramatic music)

01:56:57.651 --> 01:56:59.820
The English might have lost America,

01:56:59.820 --> 01:57:02.423
but their power in India was only growing.

01:57:02.423 --> 01:57:05.793
With many Indian provinces, including Bengal,

01:57:05.793 --> 01:57:09.329
going through a famine, the need for financial wealth grew.

01:57:09.329 --> 01:57:13.500
So in 1784, English Prime Minister William Pitt

01:57:13.500 --> 01:57:17.371
could redefine the Anglo-Indian relationship again

01:57:17.371 --> 01:57:22.042
by passing the East India Company Act of 1784.

01:57:22.042 --> 01:57:24.478
The English East India Company was still able

01:57:24.478 --> 01:57:28.882
to retain financial control over Bengal, Madras, and Bombay.

01:57:28.882 --> 01:57:31.819
However, critical political decisions would be left

01:57:31.819 --> 01:57:35.422
for a secret six-person council selected by the king

01:57:35.422 --> 01:57:37.524
to rule over the Indian colonies

01:57:37.524 --> 01:57:41.361
without any form of representation from the Indian people.

01:57:41.361 --> 01:57:45.199
This committee was aptly named the Board of Control.

01:57:45.199 --> 01:57:47.468
Learning from their failures in America,

01:57:47.468 --> 01:57:51.071
they kept it top secret with minimal oversight and records.

01:57:51.071 --> 01:57:54.475
The Board of Control was able to do anything they pleased

01:57:54.475 --> 01:57:57.478
in a continent they barely knew.

01:57:57.478 --> 01:58:00.814
With the Americas officially not a British colony anymore,

01:58:00.814 --> 01:58:02.516
the British needed to find a new place

01:58:02.516 --> 01:58:04.017
to send their prisoners.

01:58:04.017 --> 01:58:05.819
The choice was obvious.

01:58:05.819 --> 01:58:09.890
The inhospitable desert land of Australia was discovered

01:58:09.890 --> 01:58:12.125
just a mere two decades ago.

01:58:12.125 --> 01:58:15.729
Captain Arthur Phillip guided 1,400 people,

01:58:15.729 --> 01:58:17.498
half of whom were convicts,

01:58:17.498 --> 01:58:20.734
to the newly discovered New South Wales.

01:58:20.734 --> 01:58:23.270
So on May 13th, 1787,

01:58:23.270 --> 01:58:26.440
Captain Arthur Phillip, guiding 700 convicts

01:58:26.440 --> 01:58:28.275
and 700 free settlers,

01:58:28.275 --> 01:58:29.877
left Portsmouth, England,

01:58:29.877 --> 01:58:34.882
and took a journey of over 24,000 kilometers in eight months

01:58:35.048 --> 01:58:37.851
to Botany Bay, New South Wales.

01:58:37.851 --> 01:58:40.954
Once they landed, Arthur Phillip quickly realized

01:58:40.954 --> 01:58:43.357
that Botany Bay would be a horrible place

01:58:43.357 --> 01:58:44.825
to set up a settlement.

01:58:44.825 --> 01:58:46.927
The bay was open and unprotected.

01:58:46.927 --> 01:58:48.395
The water was too shallow

01:58:48.395 --> 01:58:50.998
to allow the ships to anchor close to the shore.

01:58:50.998 --> 01:58:54.134
Fresh water was scarce and the soil was poor.

01:58:54.134 --> 01:58:57.538
First contact was made with the local Eora people,

01:58:57.538 --> 01:58:59.873
who seemed suspicious of the newcomers.

01:58:59.873 --> 01:59:03.710
The area was studded with enormously strong trees.

01:59:03.710 --> 01:59:06.847
When the convicts tried to cut them down, their tools broke

01:59:06.847 --> 01:59:07.814
and the tree trunks

01:59:07.814 --> 01:59:10.817
had to be blasted out of the ground with gunpowder.

01:59:10.817 --> 01:59:12.953
Phillip decided to explore further.

01:59:12.953 --> 01:59:14.988
He discovered a more promising spot

01:59:14.988 --> 01:59:16.823
just a few kilometers north,

01:59:16.823 --> 01:59:19.026
Port Jackson at Sydney Cove.

01:59:19.026 --> 01:59:21.295
With its deep waters, sheltered coves,

01:59:21.295 --> 01:59:24.197
and more favorable conditions for a budding settlement,

01:59:24.197 --> 01:59:27.834
Phillip would write it is "the finest harbor in the world,

01:59:27.834 --> 01:59:29.870
in which a thousand sail of the line

01:59:29.870 --> 01:59:32.339
may ride in the most perfect security."

01:59:32.339 --> 01:59:36.643
On January 26th, 1788, the fleet weighed anchor

01:59:36.643 --> 01:59:38.512
and sailed to Port Jackson.

01:59:38.512 --> 01:59:40.347
The site selected for the anchorage

01:59:40.347 --> 01:59:43.483
had deep water close to the shore, was sheltered,

01:59:43.483 --> 01:59:45.752
and had a small stream flowing into it.

01:59:45.752 --> 01:59:47.854
Phillip named it Sydney Cove

01:59:47.854 --> 01:59:51.091
after Lord Sydney, the British Home Secretary.

01:59:51.091 --> 01:59:53.860
This date is celebrated as Australia Day.

01:59:53.860 --> 01:59:56.063
However, this too was not enough

01:59:56.063 --> 01:59:58.165
to stop the incoming famine.

01:59:58.165 --> 01:59:59.900
These Europeans were not used

01:59:59.900 --> 02:00:02.836
to Australia's harsh, unpredictable climate,

02:00:02.836 --> 02:00:05.005
nor knew how to feed themselves.

02:00:05.005 --> 02:00:07.074
The colony struggled to survive.

02:00:07.074 --> 02:00:08.976
But that did not stop the English

02:00:08.976 --> 02:00:11.612
from sending more and more prison hulks

02:00:11.612 --> 02:00:13.580
to the shores of Australia.

02:00:13.580 --> 02:00:16.283
As the colony could not support themselves,

02:00:16.283 --> 02:00:18.986
they continued to grow and struggle.

02:00:18.986 --> 02:00:21.388
(dramatic music)

02:00:21.388 --> 02:00:23.423
The English may have lost America,

02:00:23.423 --> 02:00:26.960
but their stranglehold over the continent was not done.

02:00:26.960 --> 02:00:29.663
As the Americans were creating the Constitution

02:00:29.663 --> 02:00:32.666
and testing out this idea of democracy,

02:00:32.666 --> 02:00:35.302
many of the British loyalists and former slaves

02:00:35.302 --> 02:00:37.404
who disagreed with American ideals

02:00:37.404 --> 02:00:39.806
fled to British colonies of Canada.

02:00:39.806 --> 02:00:43.477
However, Quebec was still home to many French people

02:00:43.477 --> 02:00:44.811
who had their own culture

02:00:44.811 --> 02:00:47.180
and wanted to ensure it was protected.

02:00:47.180 --> 02:00:49.983
Nevertheless, as more and more British loyalists

02:00:49.983 --> 02:00:51.385
were about to move in,

02:00:51.385 --> 02:00:53.887
the French Canadians were ready to fight.

02:00:53.887 --> 02:00:56.423
However, instead of starting a new law,

02:00:56.423 --> 02:01:01.028
the British Parliament created the Constitution Act of 1791,

02:01:01.028 --> 02:01:03.997
which divided Canada into two colonies,

02:01:03.997 --> 02:01:05.799
Upper and Lower Canada.

02:01:05.799 --> 02:01:08.802
Upper Canada, in modern-day southern Ontario

02:01:08.802 --> 02:01:10.737
was quickly anglicized.

02:01:10.737 --> 02:01:13.607
They would adopt British common law, Anglicanism,

02:01:13.607 --> 02:01:16.543
and were home to many escaping loyalists.

02:01:16.543 --> 02:01:18.612
Lower Canada, on the other hand,

02:01:18.612 --> 02:01:21.982
maintained French civil law, French Catholicism,

02:01:21.982 --> 02:01:23.750
and the French language.

02:01:23.750 --> 02:01:26.787
Even though they may be under the rule of the English,

02:01:26.787 --> 02:01:30.123
they were able to keep their culture entirely separate.

02:01:30.123 --> 02:01:32.959
The act also allowed Upper and Lower Canada

02:01:32.959 --> 02:01:36.463
to have a legislative assembly for both colonies.

02:01:36.463 --> 02:01:38.331
However, they still did not have

02:01:38.331 --> 02:01:41.034
any parliamentary representatives.

02:01:42.402 --> 02:01:44.905
For the former slaves who fought for Britain

02:01:44.905 --> 02:01:48.041
in exchange for freedom in the American Revolution,

02:01:48.041 --> 02:01:50.610
found life in Canada to be quite hard.

02:01:50.610 --> 02:01:52.079
They may have been freed.

02:01:52.079 --> 02:01:53.680
They were not equal.

02:01:53.680 --> 02:01:57.417
They were still discriminated against and were quite poor.

02:01:57.417 --> 02:02:00.353
They had expected a better life, better prospects,

02:02:00.353 --> 02:02:01.822
and true freedom.

02:02:01.822 --> 02:02:05.092
That's why in the crisp winter of 1791,

02:02:05.092 --> 02:02:08.428
abolitionist and British Naval officer John Clarkson

02:02:08.428 --> 02:02:11.932
proposed a new African town called Freetown,

02:02:11.932 --> 02:02:14.167
a place where the slaves would not have to deal

02:02:14.167 --> 02:02:16.870
with the cold, harsh Canadian winters

02:02:16.870 --> 02:02:18.972
and even harsher discrimination.

02:02:18.972 --> 02:02:22.709
So on February 26th, 1792,

02:02:22.709 --> 02:02:25.912
more than 1,100 former slaves got on a ship

02:02:25.912 --> 02:02:27.881
that sailed out of Nova Scotia

02:02:27.881 --> 02:02:29.983
back to their ancestral homeland.

02:02:29.983 --> 02:02:32.552
On March 9th, they landed on the coast

02:02:32.552 --> 02:02:34.988
where they created the small town of Freetown

02:02:34.988 --> 02:02:37.457
as part of the Sierra Leone Company.

02:02:38.692 --> 02:02:40.894
While Sierra Leone was being founded,

02:02:40.894 --> 02:02:43.697
the Dutch rule of the Cape Colony was ending.

02:02:43.697 --> 02:02:46.333
The Cape, a seemingly remote outpost

02:02:46.333 --> 02:02:48.168
at the southern tip of Africa,

02:02:48.168 --> 02:02:51.805
was more than just a refreshment station for weary sailors.

02:02:51.805 --> 02:02:54.274
It was the gateway to the East,

02:02:54.274 --> 02:02:58.345
a strategic jewel that every European power coveted.

02:02:58.345 --> 02:03:00.147
For the Dutch, it was home,

02:03:00.147 --> 02:03:01.515
where they had laid roots,

02:03:01.515 --> 02:03:03.517
mingled with indigenous cultures,

02:03:03.517 --> 02:03:06.086
and built a life for over a century.

02:03:06.086 --> 02:03:08.889
But as the winds from the north grew more robust,

02:03:08.889 --> 02:03:11.091
they brought British ships on the horizon.

02:03:11.091 --> 02:03:13.727
Admiral Elphinstone, leading the British fleet,

02:03:13.727 --> 02:03:14.928
knew the stakes.

02:03:14.928 --> 02:03:15.996
Control the Cape

02:03:15.996 --> 02:03:18.732
and you control the seas to the East Indies.

02:03:18.732 --> 02:03:20.333
So the British troops moved in

02:03:20.333 --> 02:03:22.869
and took over the colony from the Dutch.

02:03:22.869 --> 02:03:24.704
(dramatic music)

02:03:24.704 --> 02:03:26.773
Back in Isles, Ireland was tired

02:03:26.773 --> 02:03:29.543
of being under the thumb of British rule yet again.

02:03:29.543 --> 02:03:32.512
The decimation of their ancient language of Gaelic

02:03:32.512 --> 02:03:34.748
and their religious beliefs of Catholicism

02:03:34.748 --> 02:03:36.049
were being stripped.

02:03:36.049 --> 02:03:39.319
In other colonies, the British were becoming more tolerant.

02:03:39.319 --> 02:03:42.622
However, they refused such acceptance in Ireland.

02:03:42.622 --> 02:03:46.827
So in May 1798, the flame of rebellion was lit.

02:03:46.827 --> 02:03:48.728
From the lush fields of Wexford

02:03:48.728 --> 02:03:52.299
to the rocky shores of Antrim, Ireland rose.

02:03:52.299 --> 02:03:55.802
A young farmer named Sean O'Brien led a band of rebels

02:03:55.802 --> 02:03:57.070
fighting pitched battles

02:03:57.070 --> 02:03:59.506
against well-trained British forces.

02:03:59.506 --> 02:04:01.908
They faced victories and defeats,

02:04:01.908 --> 02:04:05.378
moments of comradery and heart-wrenching losses.

02:04:05.378 --> 02:04:07.013
In one poignant moment

02:04:07.013 --> 02:04:09.716
atop Vinegar Hill, after a fierce battle,

02:04:09.716 --> 02:04:12.352
Sean looked over the land, his land.

02:04:12.352 --> 02:04:16.156
Despite the British victory that day, he saw not the end,

02:04:16.156 --> 02:04:19.125
but the beginning of a long struggle for freedom.

02:04:19.125 --> 02:04:21.027
The rebellion reached its climax

02:04:21.027 --> 02:04:24.064
when French forces, allies in the Irish cause,

02:04:24.064 --> 02:04:26.533
landed on the shores of County Mayo.

02:04:26.533 --> 02:04:29.369
It felt as if liberation was within reach,

02:04:29.369 --> 02:04:32.572
but the seasoned British forces proved too formidable.

02:04:32.572 --> 02:04:36.376
The French, along with their Irish allies, suffered defeat,

02:04:36.376 --> 02:04:38.712
another failed Irish rebellion.

02:04:39.713 --> 02:04:42.249
While in the Sultanate of Mysore in India,

02:04:42.249 --> 02:04:44.818
the British were gaining influence and power.

02:04:44.818 --> 02:04:47.587
Tipu Sultan, the leader of the Mysore people,

02:04:47.587 --> 02:04:49.122
contacted the French

02:04:49.122 --> 02:04:51.925
asking to be allies to destroy the English,

02:04:51.925 --> 02:04:53.727
like how they did in America.

02:04:53.727 --> 02:04:55.929
But yet, France did not help this time,

02:04:55.929 --> 02:04:59.032
forcing the Mysorean people to defend for themselves.

02:04:59.032 --> 02:05:01.234
The news of Tipu's secret correspondence

02:05:01.234 --> 02:05:04.437
with the distant French engulfed the world in flames

02:05:04.437 --> 02:05:07.107
due to the British vast spy network.

02:05:07.107 --> 02:05:09.743
The Governor-General Richard Wellesley saw

02:05:09.743 --> 02:05:12.946
the potential danger of a Franco-Mysorean front.

02:05:12.946 --> 02:05:15.081
Determined to nip this threat in the bud,

02:05:15.081 --> 02:05:18.218
the British sought allies in the Nizam of Hyderbad

02:05:18.218 --> 02:05:20.453
and the formidable Marathas.

02:05:20.453 --> 02:05:23.123
As the British and their allies began their march,

02:05:23.123 --> 02:05:25.792
closing in on fortresses and territories,

02:05:25.792 --> 02:05:28.628
the atmosphere in Mysore grew tense.

02:05:28.628 --> 02:05:32.332
The roads leading to Seringapatam, Mysore's proud capital,

02:05:32.332 --> 02:05:34.567
echoed with the march of British boots

02:05:34.567 --> 02:05:36.703
and the rumbles of their cannons.

02:05:36.703 --> 02:05:39.139
Tipu, clad in his royal attire,

02:05:39.139 --> 02:05:41.508
frequently consulted with his generals.

02:05:41.508 --> 02:05:44.210
The map of his empire spread out before him,

02:05:44.210 --> 02:05:46.479
marked with strategies and plans,

02:05:46.479 --> 02:05:49.883
the weight of a kingdom's hope rested on his shoulders.

02:05:49.883 --> 02:05:51.117
The climax approached

02:05:51.117 --> 02:05:53.920
as the British forces, led by General Harris

02:05:53.920 --> 02:05:57.223
and a young yet notable officer Arthur Wellesley,

02:05:57.223 --> 02:05:59.125
surrounded Seringapatam.

02:05:59.125 --> 02:06:01.895
With its stone walls and swirling river,

02:06:01.895 --> 02:06:05.332
the mighty fortress city had stood tall for years.

02:06:05.332 --> 02:06:08.468
Now it was the last bastion of resistance

02:06:08.468 --> 02:06:10.270
against the British advance.

02:06:10.270 --> 02:06:14.541
For days, cannons, gunfire, and battle cries filled the air.

02:06:14.541 --> 02:06:18.244
The people of Mysore prayed for their sultan, their tiger.

02:06:18.244 --> 02:06:22.015
But on May 4th, 1799, tragedy struck.

02:06:22.015 --> 02:06:24.584
As British forces stormed the fortress,

02:06:24.584 --> 02:06:26.619
Tipu Sultan, fighting fiercely

02:06:26.619 --> 02:06:29.155
in defense of his beloved city, fell.

02:06:29.155 --> 02:06:31.791
With his death, the resistance crumbled.

02:06:31.791 --> 02:06:33.293
Mysore was divided,

02:06:33.293 --> 02:06:37.063
with large swaths of its territory taken by the victors.

02:06:37.063 --> 02:06:38.631
The Wodeyar Dynasty,

02:06:38.631 --> 02:06:41.901
once rulers of the region before Tipu's rise,

02:06:41.901 --> 02:06:43.503
were restored to the throne,

02:06:43.503 --> 02:06:47.007
but only as puppet monarchs to the British.

02:06:47.007 --> 02:06:50.243
(dramatic music)

02:06:50.243 --> 02:06:52.545
With the failure of the Irish rebellion,

02:06:52.545 --> 02:06:53.947
the English wanted to find a way

02:06:53.947 --> 02:06:56.916
to ensure the Irish would never revolt again.

02:06:56.916 --> 02:06:58.852
So the United Kingdom Parliament,

02:06:58.852 --> 02:07:02.122
which already involved Wales, England, and Scotland,

02:07:02.122 --> 02:07:04.491
would include Ireland for the first time

02:07:04.491 --> 02:07:07.961
on the eve of January 1st, 1801.

02:07:07.961 --> 02:07:09.929
The Irish parliament was dissolved

02:07:09.929 --> 02:07:12.232
and merged with the rest of Great Britain,

02:07:12.232 --> 02:07:15.502
Wales, England, Scotland, Ireland,

02:07:15.502 --> 02:07:19.239
four kingdoms, one union, one Great Britain.

02:07:21.174 --> 02:07:23.743
Major General Richard Wellesley wasn't done

02:07:23.743 --> 02:07:26.212
expanding the English influence in India.

02:07:26.212 --> 02:07:28.715
On September 23rd, 1803,

02:07:28.715 --> 02:07:32.552
Wellesley and his 7,000 troops crossed the Kaitna River

02:07:32.552 --> 02:07:35.622
and faced the fragmented Maratha Confederacy

02:07:35.622 --> 02:07:38.625
with an army of over 40,000 soldiers

02:07:38.625 --> 02:07:41.561
and an untold amount of battle elephants.

02:07:41.561 --> 02:07:43.963
The British aimed to flank the Marathas,

02:07:43.963 --> 02:07:45.832
but soon realized they were up against

02:07:45.832 --> 02:07:49.969
the entire Maratha force, leading to direct engagement.

02:07:49.969 --> 02:07:52.105
The Marathas were known for their cavalry

02:07:52.105 --> 02:07:54.441
and guerilla warfare tactics.

02:07:54.441 --> 02:07:56.976
The swift charges of the Maratha cavalry

02:07:56.976 --> 02:08:00.680
posed a severe challenge to the British infantry squares.

02:08:00.680 --> 02:08:04.551
Meanwhile, the Maratha artillery relentlessly pounded

02:08:04.551 --> 02:08:06.553
the advancing British troops.

02:08:06.553 --> 02:08:09.055
However, the British had two advantages,

02:08:09.055 --> 02:08:12.225
superior training and discipline of their troops

02:08:12.225 --> 02:08:14.828
and a more coordinated use of artillery.

02:08:14.828 --> 02:08:16.496
As the battle intensified,

02:08:16.496 --> 02:08:19.199
the British artillery began to find its mark,

02:08:19.199 --> 02:08:22.102
wreaking havoc on the Maratha formations.

02:08:22.102 --> 02:08:26.139
As the days went on, both sides had considerable losses,

02:08:26.139 --> 02:08:28.007
but the Marathas had to withdraw

02:08:28.007 --> 02:08:30.110
and sign the Treaty of Deogaon.

02:08:30.110 --> 02:08:33.980
This saw Maratha chieftain Raghoji II give the territory

02:08:33.980 --> 02:08:37.250
situated north of the Wardha, Gawilghur, and Narnala

02:08:37.250 --> 02:08:38.218
to the British,

02:08:38.218 --> 02:08:40.987
along with the District of Cuttack.

02:08:40.987 --> 02:08:42.021
(dramatic music)

02:08:42.021 --> 02:08:43.590
However, back in Europe,

02:08:43.590 --> 02:08:45.492
the British would be put on the defensive

02:08:45.492 --> 02:08:47.360
by Napoleon Bonaparte,

02:08:47.360 --> 02:08:49.195
the ambitious French emperor

02:08:49.195 --> 02:08:51.731
who had his eyes on conquering Europe.

02:08:51.731 --> 02:08:54.100
Napoleon needed control over the waves

02:08:54.100 --> 02:08:56.202
to secure his dominion over Europe,

02:08:56.202 --> 02:08:59.139
which meant breaking the British naval blockade.

02:08:59.139 --> 02:09:01.274
The French and their allied Spanish fleet

02:09:01.274 --> 02:09:03.209
had been harbored in Cadiz.

02:09:03.209 --> 02:09:05.612
Together, they would clear the English channel,

02:09:05.612 --> 02:09:08.314
allowing Napoleon's armies to invade Britain.

02:09:08.314 --> 02:09:11.784
However, Admiral Lord Horatio Nelson was aware

02:09:11.784 --> 02:09:13.419
of their planned attacks.

02:09:13.419 --> 02:09:15.922
So as the sun climbed the horizon,

02:09:15.922 --> 02:09:20.093
Nelson, aboard the HMS Victory, made a daring choice.

02:09:20.093 --> 02:09:22.462
Eschewing traditional naval tactics,

02:09:22.462 --> 02:09:25.098
he ordered his fleet to split into two columns

02:09:25.098 --> 02:09:28.401
and charged directly at the Franco-Spanish line.

02:09:28.401 --> 02:09:32.105
It was a bold move, one that risked everything.

02:09:32.105 --> 02:09:35.375
The thunder of cannons broke the morning silence.

02:09:35.375 --> 02:09:37.043
Amidst the din and smoke,

02:09:37.043 --> 02:09:38.745
the two navies clashed.

02:09:38.745 --> 02:09:41.915
The British ships, notably the Victory and the Temeraire,

02:09:41.915 --> 02:09:43.683
bore down upon the enemy

02:09:43.683 --> 02:09:46.920
with Nelson's tactic aiming to slice through their line,

02:09:46.920 --> 02:09:48.488
creating chaos.

02:09:48.488 --> 02:09:50.123
As the hours wore on,

02:09:50.123 --> 02:09:52.692
the superior training and tactics of the British

02:09:52.692 --> 02:09:54.027
began to tell.

02:09:54.027 --> 02:09:57.664
One by one, Franco-Spanish ships were either captured

02:09:57.664 --> 02:09:59.732
or rendered combat ineffective.

02:09:59.732 --> 02:10:02.268
By sunset, the British had established

02:10:02.268 --> 02:10:03.970
their dominance of Europe.

02:10:03.970 --> 02:10:05.705
When you can't win by fighting,

02:10:05.705 --> 02:10:08.541
you tend to take the battle to the realm of trade.

02:10:08.541 --> 02:10:12.078
In 1806, Napoleon passed the Berlin Decree,

02:10:12.078 --> 02:10:13.980
which declared that the British Isles

02:10:13.980 --> 02:10:16.549
were to be in a constant state of blockade

02:10:16.549 --> 02:10:19.052
and barred all trade with Great Britain.

02:10:19.052 --> 02:10:22.789
In response, Great Britain passed the Orders in Council.

02:10:22.789 --> 02:10:24.691
Any English controlled colony

02:10:24.691 --> 02:10:27.560
was barred from trade with France.

02:10:27.560 --> 02:10:30.096
Also, if you complied with the Berlin Decree

02:10:30.096 --> 02:10:32.699
or tried to evade the British military,

02:10:32.699 --> 02:10:34.701
your ship would be seized.

02:10:34.701 --> 02:10:36.803
As well, any ports that followed

02:10:36.803 --> 02:10:39.239
the Napoleonic decree were blockaded

02:10:39.239 --> 02:10:42.475
and not allowed to have vessels enter and leave.

02:10:42.475 --> 02:10:45.545
The battle of the blockades was on.

02:10:45.545 --> 02:10:47.313
(dramatic music)

02:10:47.313 --> 02:10:49.749
As the English and French fought about trade,

02:10:49.749 --> 02:10:52.151
Great Britain changed the game once again.

02:10:52.151 --> 02:10:54.654
In 1807, the British Parliament passed

02:10:54.654 --> 02:10:57.023
the Abolition of the Slave Trade Act,

02:10:57.023 --> 02:10:59.459
which made it illegal to engage in the slave trade

02:10:59.459 --> 02:11:01.261
within the British colonies.

02:11:01.261 --> 02:11:03.963
However, slavery was still legal.

02:11:03.963 --> 02:11:05.565
You could still own a slave.

02:11:05.565 --> 02:11:08.368
You couldn't trade them internationally.

02:11:08.368 --> 02:11:10.003
(dramatic music)

02:11:10.003 --> 02:11:13.573
Most English fighting during the Napoleonic Wars occurred

02:11:13.573 --> 02:11:15.908
on the Spanish Peninsula in the water,

02:11:15.908 --> 02:11:17.910
such as the Battle of Rolica,

02:11:17.910 --> 02:11:19.178
the Battle of Vimeiro,

02:11:19.178 --> 02:11:20.580
and the battle of Coruna.

02:11:20.580 --> 02:11:23.082
Napoleon, who was spreading out his resources

02:11:23.082 --> 02:11:24.450
across the continent,

02:11:24.450 --> 02:11:26.552
didn't have enough to fight the British.

02:11:26.552 --> 02:11:30.189
He just allowed his navy to get decimated by the British.

02:11:30.189 --> 02:11:32.625
While the British were more successful in battle,

02:11:32.625 --> 02:11:35.628
they still needed more recruits for the Royal Navy.

02:11:35.628 --> 02:11:37.096
Under the Order in Council,

02:11:37.096 --> 02:11:37.997
the British seized

02:11:37.997 --> 02:11:41.301
400 American merchant ships and their cargoes

02:11:41.301 --> 02:11:44.137
between 1807 and 1812

02:11:44.137 --> 02:11:46.272
and drafted them to the Royal Navy.

02:11:46.272 --> 02:11:49.976
Also, France and England creating sanctions for one another

02:11:49.976 --> 02:11:53.813
made it impossible for Americans to receive any trade

02:11:53.813 --> 02:11:55.248
from the rest of Europe.

02:11:55.248 --> 02:11:57.383
(dramatic music)

02:11:57.383 --> 02:12:01.321
So on June 18th, 1812, the young nation of America

02:12:01.321 --> 02:12:04.757
declared war against its former colonizer.

02:12:04.757 --> 02:12:07.060
They wanted their merchant ships to be free

02:12:07.060 --> 02:12:09.195
and to have fair trade across Europe.

02:12:09.195 --> 02:12:12.632
So American General William Hull went into the inlands

02:12:12.632 --> 02:12:15.101
of Upper Canada trying to capture it.

02:12:15.101 --> 02:12:17.070
However, he was unsuccessful

02:12:17.070 --> 02:12:19.339
and retreated back to Fort Detroit.

02:12:19.339 --> 02:12:21.941
This led British Major General Isaac Brock

02:12:21.941 --> 02:12:25.812
and their Shawnee allies under Tecumseh to target Detroit.

02:12:25.812 --> 02:12:28.014
Tecumseh had his warriors parade

02:12:28.014 --> 02:12:30.683
in and out of the woods multiple times,

02:12:30.683 --> 02:12:33.953
creating the illusion of a much larger force.

02:12:33.953 --> 02:12:36.656
This, along with the intimidating war cries

02:12:36.656 --> 02:12:38.458
and other deceptive tactics,

02:12:38.458 --> 02:12:41.461
made Hull believe he was vastly outnumbered.

02:12:41.461 --> 02:12:44.464
Meanwhile, Brock sent a demand for surrender,

02:12:44.464 --> 02:12:47.600
hinting that if a battle began, he might be unable

02:12:47.600 --> 02:12:49.335
to control the Native warriors

02:12:49.335 --> 02:12:53.039
from attacking American civilians and soldiers alike.

02:12:53.039 --> 02:12:56.676
This psychological ploy preyed on Hull's fears.

02:12:56.676 --> 02:12:59.645
Without a shot being fired from the British cannons

02:12:59.645 --> 02:13:01.881
and with minimal direct engagement,

02:13:01.881 --> 02:13:04.450
Hull surrendered Fort Detroit to the British

02:13:04.450 --> 02:13:07.220
on August 16th, 1812.

02:13:07.220 --> 02:13:10.189
The war wouldn't get any easier for the Americans

02:13:10.189 --> 02:13:13.493
because on January 18th, 1813,

02:13:13.493 --> 02:13:16.562
a small American army wanted to reclaim Detroit.

02:13:16.562 --> 02:13:17.930
Initially they did,

02:13:17.930 --> 02:13:21.734
but on January 22nd, British Colonel Henry Proctor,

02:13:21.734 --> 02:13:24.504
leading a combined force of British, Canadians,

02:13:24.504 --> 02:13:25.972
and Native Americans,

02:13:25.972 --> 02:13:30.243
unleashed a fury of gunfire, shouts, and war cries

02:13:30.243 --> 02:13:32.412
shattering the winter silence.

02:13:32.412 --> 02:13:34.480
The Americans were caught off guard,

02:13:34.480 --> 02:13:36.149
especially on their left flank,

02:13:36.149 --> 02:13:38.451
which quickly crumbled under the pressure.

02:13:38.451 --> 02:13:41.821
On January 23rd, the Americans surrendered.

02:13:41.821 --> 02:13:44.524
However, their surrender wasn't accepted

02:13:44.524 --> 02:13:46.759
and they were killed on the spot

02:13:46.759 --> 02:13:49.061
by Native American soldiers.

02:13:49.061 --> 02:13:53.032
The Americans, enraged, attacked the capital city of York,

02:13:53.032 --> 02:13:56.302
modern-day Toronto, on April 27th.

02:13:56.302 --> 02:13:58.438
The American force was quickly able

02:13:58.438 --> 02:14:00.840
to outnumber and defeat the British.

02:14:00.840 --> 02:14:02.275
Upon capturing York,

02:14:02.275 --> 02:14:05.077
the discipline of the American troops broke down.

02:14:05.077 --> 02:14:07.046
Despite the orders of their officers,

02:14:07.046 --> 02:14:09.949
they looted and set fire to several buildings,

02:14:09.949 --> 02:14:12.752
including the parliament of Upper Canada.

02:14:12.752 --> 02:14:15.288
A year later, the British and Canadian armies

02:14:15.288 --> 02:14:16.522
would get their revenge

02:14:16.522 --> 02:14:18.891
when the British and American forces clashed

02:14:18.891 --> 02:14:21.260
at the battle of Bladensburg, Maryland.

02:14:21.260 --> 02:14:24.597
Despite the Americans having a numerical advantage

02:14:24.597 --> 02:14:26.265
and a defensive position,

02:14:26.265 --> 02:14:27.800
they were swiftly defeated

02:14:27.800 --> 02:14:30.903
and the British marched into Washington, D.C.

02:14:30.903 --> 02:14:32.171
Entering the capital,

02:14:32.171 --> 02:14:34.307
the British were initially cautious,

02:14:34.307 --> 02:14:38.044
expecting some trap or a significant American defense.

02:14:38.044 --> 02:14:40.980
But they found Washington largely abandoned.

02:14:40.980 --> 02:14:44.150
Important buildings, including the White House, the Capitol,

02:14:44.150 --> 02:14:46.152
and other government buildings,

02:14:46.152 --> 02:14:47.520
were set alight.

02:14:47.520 --> 02:14:50.323
The fires could be seen miles away.

02:14:50.323 --> 02:14:52.291
The destruction was systematic

02:14:52.291 --> 02:14:54.327
and targeted primarily at public

02:14:54.327 --> 02:14:56.195
and governmental structures.

02:14:56.195 --> 02:14:59.265
The British occupation of Washington was brief

02:14:59.265 --> 02:15:01.334
and they left just a day later.

02:15:01.334 --> 02:15:03.569
As Napoleon was falling apart in Europe

02:15:03.569 --> 02:15:06.072
due to their constant losses against Russia

02:15:06.072 --> 02:15:07.473
and the rest of Europe,

02:15:07.473 --> 02:15:10.409
he signed the Treaty of Paris 1814,

02:15:10.409 --> 02:15:14.247
which restored the French monarchy to King Louis XVIII.

02:15:14.247 --> 02:15:16.449
England thought about sending more forces

02:15:16.449 --> 02:15:18.050
to the American theater.

02:15:18.050 --> 02:15:21.087
However, they knew that the Americans were too rebellious

02:15:21.087 --> 02:15:22.655
to follow their will again.

02:15:22.655 --> 02:15:27.226
So the day before Christmas, on December 24th, 1814,

02:15:27.226 --> 02:15:29.295
the Treaty of Ghent was signed,

02:15:29.295 --> 02:15:32.298
which stated that all territories captured in the war

02:15:32.298 --> 02:15:35.134
would be returned to their pre-war owners,

02:15:35.134 --> 02:15:37.670
which means no borders were to be changed.

02:15:37.670 --> 02:15:41.440
It was also reaffirmed that America was its own nation,

02:15:41.440 --> 02:15:44.477
and Canada would always be separate from that.

02:15:44.477 --> 02:15:46.312
(dramatic music)

02:15:46.312 --> 02:15:49.248
Instead, they focused on the Himalayas

02:15:49.248 --> 02:15:50.917
and the kingdom of Nepal,

02:15:50.917 --> 02:15:53.152
governed by the Gurkha soldiers.

02:15:53.152 --> 02:15:55.521
The Gurkhas, renowned for their courage

02:15:55.521 --> 02:15:56.889
and military prowess,

02:15:56.889 --> 02:15:58.958
had expanded their territories,

02:15:58.958 --> 02:16:01.994
but to their south, another giant was growing,

02:16:01.994 --> 02:16:04.297
the British East India Company,

02:16:04.297 --> 02:16:07.300
which had begun to see Nepal as a strategic buffer

02:16:07.300 --> 02:16:10.169
against potential Chinese incursions.

02:16:10.169 --> 02:16:11.871
The initial spark for conflict

02:16:11.871 --> 02:16:14.574
was the shared interest in the Terai region,

02:16:14.574 --> 02:16:16.809
a fertile belt between the Himalayas

02:16:16.809 --> 02:16:18.244
and the plains of India.

02:16:18.244 --> 02:16:21.781
Border disputes and territorial ambitions from both sides

02:16:21.781 --> 02:16:24.216
culminated in the British East India Company

02:16:24.216 --> 02:16:27.820
declaring war on Nepal in 1814.

02:16:27.820 --> 02:16:30.890
The battle began at Nalapani near Dehradun.

02:16:30.890 --> 02:16:31.991
The fortress there,

02:16:31.991 --> 02:16:35.761
defended by the brilliant Gurkha commander Amar Singh Thapa,

02:16:35.761 --> 02:16:38.497
resisted British advances for over a month,

02:16:38.497 --> 02:16:40.333
giving the Gurkhas their first taste

02:16:40.333 --> 02:16:43.002
of the formidable might they were up against.

02:16:43.002 --> 02:16:46.372
However, the British, unaccustomed to mountain warfare

02:16:46.372 --> 02:16:48.474
and underestimating the Gurkhas,

02:16:48.474 --> 02:16:50.843
found themselves repelled repeatedly.

02:16:50.843 --> 02:16:54.680
The Gurkhas employed guerilla tactics in various encounters,

02:16:54.680 --> 02:16:57.516
leveraging their knowledge of the local terrains.

02:16:57.516 --> 02:17:00.219
However, the British had superior numbers,

02:17:00.219 --> 02:17:03.022
advanced weaponry, and strategic depth.

02:17:03.022 --> 02:17:03.990
Over the months,

02:17:03.990 --> 02:17:07.360
critical areas like the Kathmandu Valley were threatened

02:17:07.360 --> 02:17:09.729
and the Gurkhas felt the strain of the war

02:17:09.729 --> 02:17:12.231
despite their bravery and dedication.

02:17:12.231 --> 02:17:16.168
By early 1815, it was evident that the Gurkhas,

02:17:16.168 --> 02:17:19.105
though fierce and admirable in their resistance,

02:17:19.105 --> 02:17:20.706
couldn't stem the tide.

02:17:20.706 --> 02:17:22.141
Peace talks commenced,

02:17:22.141 --> 02:17:25.811
leading to the Treaty of Sugauli in 1815.

02:17:25.811 --> 02:17:29.015
Nepal was forced to cede a significant portion

02:17:29.015 --> 02:17:32.451
of its western and eastern territories to the British,

02:17:32.451 --> 02:17:35.488
redrawing the borders of the two powers.

02:17:36.689 --> 02:17:39.992
As the Maratha Confederacy was struggling to survive,

02:17:39.992 --> 02:17:42.795
the British saw the chance to knock the final blow

02:17:42.795 --> 02:17:44.330
to this empire.

02:17:44.330 --> 02:17:45.531
The Maratha Peshwa,

02:17:45.531 --> 02:17:50.269
which translates roughly into foremost leader, Baji Rao II,

02:17:50.269 --> 02:17:52.538
knew that his power was relatively minimal

02:17:52.538 --> 02:17:54.306
after the Treaty of Deogaon

02:17:54.306 --> 02:17:55.975
and he was just a pawn.

02:17:55.975 --> 02:17:58.077
The Maratha chiefs, the Holkars of Indore,

02:17:58.911 --> 02:18:02.081
the Bhonsles of Nagpur, the Scindias of Gwalior,

02:18:02.081 --> 02:18:03.916
and the Gaekwads of Baroda,

02:18:03.916 --> 02:18:06.652
had their own ambitions and differences.

02:18:06.652 --> 02:18:09.021
Internal squabbles often overshadowed

02:18:09.021 --> 02:18:10.623
their collective power.

02:18:10.623 --> 02:18:12.291
On the other hand, the British,

02:18:12.291 --> 02:18:14.660
under Governor General Lord Hastings,

02:18:14.660 --> 02:18:17.430
saw an opportunity amidst this discord.

02:18:17.430 --> 02:18:19.799
Baji Rao II, hoping to restore

02:18:19.799 --> 02:18:21.901
some of the lost Maratha prestige,

02:18:21.901 --> 02:18:25.071
began secretly building up his military might

02:18:25.071 --> 02:18:28.641
and tales of his preparations soon reached British ears.

02:18:28.641 --> 02:18:31.143
Their intelligence was impeccable.

02:18:31.143 --> 02:18:34.380
Seeing the Peshwar's actions as a treaty violation,

02:18:34.380 --> 02:18:37.416
which had assured the British of his non-aggression,

02:18:37.416 --> 02:18:40.486
Lord Hastings believed in striking first.

02:18:40.486 --> 02:18:43.656
The Battle of Khadki near Pune saw British forces

02:18:43.656 --> 02:18:47.626
led by General Smith clash fiercely with the Marathas.

02:18:47.626 --> 02:18:49.095
After intense fighting,

02:18:49.095 --> 02:18:51.030
the British emerged victorious,

02:18:51.030 --> 02:18:54.300
capturing Pune and neutralizing Peshwar's power.

02:18:54.300 --> 02:18:56.702
But the war was far from over.

02:18:56.702 --> 02:18:59.038
To the northeast in Nagpur,

02:18:59.038 --> 02:19:03.109
Raghoji II Bhonsle led his forces against the British.

02:19:03.109 --> 02:19:05.377
The Battle of Sitabuldi was brutal

02:19:05.377 --> 02:19:08.114
with both sides taking heavy casualties.

02:19:08.114 --> 02:19:09.982
The Maratha's fought valiantly,

02:19:09.982 --> 02:19:12.785
but the disciplined and well-equipped British troops

02:19:12.785 --> 02:19:15.721
under the command of Colonel Scott prevailed.

02:19:15.721 --> 02:19:18.457
Simultaneously, the Holkars were gearing up

02:19:18.457 --> 02:19:20.826
to face the British in central India.

02:19:20.826 --> 02:19:23.696
The confrontation resulted in several skirmishes

02:19:23.696 --> 02:19:26.766
with neither side gaining a decisive advantage.

02:19:26.766 --> 02:19:29.869
However, the sheer persistence of the British forces

02:19:29.869 --> 02:19:32.671
gradually wore down the Maratha resistance.

02:19:32.671 --> 02:19:35.241
Then there were the Scindias of Gwalior.

02:19:35.241 --> 02:19:38.077
Understanding the overwhelming odds against him,

02:19:38.077 --> 02:19:41.413
Daulat Rao Scindia decided to remain neutral.

02:19:41.413 --> 02:19:44.416
This was a significant blow to the Maratha

02:19:44.416 --> 02:19:46.786
and caused the eventual surrender.

02:19:46.786 --> 02:19:50.389
As they signed the Treaty of Mandeswar in 1818,

02:19:50.389 --> 02:19:53.092
the Maratha Confederacy was dismantled

02:19:53.092 --> 02:19:55.895
and its territories were annexed by the British.

02:19:55.895 --> 02:19:57.997
The Peshwar title was abolished

02:19:57.997 --> 02:20:01.200
and Baji Rao II was exiled to Bithur,

02:20:01.200 --> 02:20:04.069
ending a once great confederacy.

02:20:05.137 --> 02:20:08.207
As the English were expanding, they needed another fort

02:20:08.207 --> 02:20:10.409
to help navigate the waters of Asia.

02:20:10.409 --> 02:20:13.012
So Sir Thomas Stamord Raffles was tasked

02:20:13.012 --> 02:20:16.115
with finding a new place to create a trading fort.

02:20:16.115 --> 02:20:19.251
Eventually, Raffles settled on the island of Singapore

02:20:19.251 --> 02:20:20.452
because of its position

02:20:20.452 --> 02:20:22.888
at the southern tip of the Malay Peninsula

02:20:22.888 --> 02:20:24.690
near the Straits of Malacca

02:20:24.690 --> 02:20:28.561
and its excellent natural harbor, fresh water supplies,

02:20:28.561 --> 02:20:30.763
and timber for repairing ships.

02:20:30.763 --> 02:20:33.232
Raffles expedition arrived in Singapore

02:20:33.232 --> 02:20:36.135
on January 29th, 1819,

02:20:36.135 --> 02:20:40.306
putting this strategic island under British control.

02:20:40.306 --> 02:20:41.807
(dramatic music)

02:20:41.807 --> 02:20:44.543
While in India, the British weren't done expanding.

02:20:44.543 --> 02:20:47.580
They saw the Konbaung dynasty of Burma as a threat

02:20:47.580 --> 02:20:49.081
to British expansion.

02:20:49.081 --> 02:20:51.417
It began with the Burmese occupation

02:20:51.417 --> 02:20:54.687
of the island of Shalpuri in 1824.

02:20:54.687 --> 02:20:56.355
For the British, this was a sign

02:20:56.355 --> 02:20:59.091
of looming Burmese encroachments of Bengal.

02:20:59.091 --> 02:21:01.660
Responding, the British struck decisively

02:21:01.660 --> 02:21:03.629
with a two-pronged invasion,

02:21:03.629 --> 02:21:06.065
quickly capturing the Port of Rangoon.

02:21:06.065 --> 02:21:08.667
They had expected the fall of this significant city

02:21:08.667 --> 02:21:11.403
to bring the Burmese to the negotiating table,

02:21:11.403 --> 02:21:14.139
but the Konbaung dynasty was resilient.

02:21:14.139 --> 02:21:16.242
Rather than engaging in open battle,

02:21:16.242 --> 02:21:18.277
they adopted guerilla warfare,

02:21:18.277 --> 02:21:21.647
relying on the monsoon rains and the dense forests

02:21:21.647 --> 02:21:24.083
to wear down the foreign invaders.

02:21:24.083 --> 02:21:25.718
For nearly two years,

02:21:25.718 --> 02:21:28.654
the jungles of Burma witnessed a strategic game

02:21:28.654 --> 02:21:29.755
of cat and mouse

02:21:29.755 --> 02:21:31.790
with neither side willing to yield.

02:21:31.790 --> 02:21:34.860
Though superior in equipment and naval power,

02:21:34.860 --> 02:21:37.730
the British were tested by the unfamiliar terrain

02:21:37.730 --> 02:21:40.299
and the relentless Burmese resistance.

02:21:40.299 --> 02:21:42.301
Finally, in 1826,

02:21:42.301 --> 02:21:44.703
with both powers exhausted and drained,

02:21:44.703 --> 02:21:47.873
diplomats met to draft the Treaty of Yandabo.

02:21:47.873 --> 02:21:49.909
Burma recognized British claims

02:21:49.909 --> 02:21:53.812
over Assam, Manipur, Cachar, and Jaintia

02:21:53.812 --> 02:21:57.616
while ceding Arakan and Tenasserim's coastal regions.

02:21:57.616 --> 02:22:01.086
A heavy silver indemnity would be paid to the British,

02:22:01.086 --> 02:22:03.756
further straining the Burmese treasury.

02:22:03.756 --> 02:22:05.024
(dramatic music)

02:22:05.024 --> 02:22:06.525
While back in Parliament,

02:22:06.525 --> 02:22:09.895
Great Britain was going through culturally its own troubles.

02:22:09.895 --> 02:22:14.900
In 1829, they passed the Roman Catholic Relief Act of 1829,

02:22:15.100 --> 02:22:17.770
which allowed Catholics legally serving in parliament

02:22:17.770 --> 02:22:19.038
for the first time.

02:22:19.038 --> 02:22:22.007
Within days, Irish Catholic Daniel O'Connell

02:22:22.007 --> 02:22:24.777
was able to take his seat in the House of Commons.

02:22:24.777 --> 02:22:27.079
The countless wars, resettlements,

02:22:27.079 --> 02:22:30.349
and prejudice against Anglicanism and Catholicism

02:22:30.349 --> 02:22:32.151
were starting to be resolved.

02:22:32.151 --> 02:22:35.220
Religious acceptance was growing in the Isles.

02:22:36.388 --> 02:22:40.192
However, acceptance of the Aboriginal people of Australia

02:22:40.192 --> 02:22:41.961
was not part of the plan.

02:22:41.961 --> 02:22:45.831
The island of Van Diemen's Land, now known as Tasmania,

02:22:45.831 --> 02:22:49.068
had been inhabited by the Indigenous Palawa people

02:22:49.068 --> 02:22:50.803
for thousands of years.

02:22:50.803 --> 02:22:52.538
However, the British arrival

02:22:52.538 --> 02:22:55.007
and the ever-increasing number of settlers

02:22:55.007 --> 02:22:58.010
made it hard for the Palawa people to survive.

02:22:58.010 --> 02:23:01.413
This resulted in the Palawa, in their bid for survival,

02:23:01.413 --> 02:23:04.683
occasionally raiding settler farms for food.

02:23:04.683 --> 02:23:06.585
The settlers, feeling threatened,

02:23:06.585 --> 02:23:09.054
often retaliated with violence.

02:23:09.054 --> 02:23:12.624
As time went on, confrontations became more frequent.

02:23:12.624 --> 02:23:15.561
Reports of violent skirmishes, kidnappings,

02:23:15.561 --> 02:23:17.696
and killings became commonplace.

02:23:17.696 --> 02:23:21.700
The settlers termed these confrontations the Black War.

02:23:21.700 --> 02:23:25.070
As tensions escalated, the colonial administration

02:23:25.070 --> 02:23:27.139
under Lieutenant Governor George Arthur

02:23:27.139 --> 02:23:28.841
declared martial law,

02:23:28.841 --> 02:23:32.277
allowing settlers to kill Palawa on sight.

02:23:32.277 --> 02:23:34.913
In a large-scale attempt to resolve the issue,

02:23:34.913 --> 02:23:38.150
1830 saw the formation of the Black Line.

02:23:38.150 --> 02:23:39.485
It was a human chain

02:23:39.485 --> 02:23:42.187
comprising settlers, convicts, and troops

02:23:42.187 --> 02:23:43.522
meant to traverse the island

02:23:43.522 --> 02:23:47.159
and drive the remaining Palawa into the Tasman Peninsula,

02:23:47.159 --> 02:23:48.794
where they would be isolated.

02:23:48.794 --> 02:23:52.598
This line was largely ineffective and costly.

02:23:52.598 --> 02:23:56.602
By 1831, under the guise of Christianity,

02:23:56.602 --> 02:24:00.372
all of the remaining Palawa were moved to Flinder's Island

02:24:00.372 --> 02:24:05.177
where most died due to disease, malnutrition, and despair.

02:24:05.177 --> 02:24:07.079
(gentle music)

02:24:07.079 --> 02:24:09.515
History is never black or white,

02:24:09.515 --> 02:24:12.518
because on August 28th, 1833,

02:24:12.518 --> 02:24:15.354
the Slavery Abolition Act was passed.

02:24:15.354 --> 02:24:17.990
The act gradually emancipated all slaves

02:24:17.990 --> 02:24:20.993
throughout the British Empire within six years.

02:24:20.993 --> 02:24:24.063
Also, the act gave 20 million pounds,

02:24:24.063 --> 02:24:26.932
approximately two billion pounds today,

02:24:26.932 --> 02:24:30.769
to compensate slave owners for losing their property.

02:24:30.769 --> 02:24:32.838
The former slaves did not receive

02:24:32.838 --> 02:24:34.940
any of this money for themselves.

02:24:34.940 --> 02:24:37.643
Instead, they were forced to fend for themselves

02:24:37.643 --> 02:24:39.211
with no assets.

02:24:40.312 --> 02:24:44.349
In 1835 in Australia, a man named John Batman

02:24:44.349 --> 02:24:46.919
found a place unknown to his fellow colonies

02:24:46.919 --> 02:24:49.088
that he aptly named Batmania.

02:24:49.088 --> 02:24:51.723
Under a questionable Batman's Treaty

02:24:51.723 --> 02:24:55.327
with the local Aboriginal people, the Kulin nation,

02:24:55.327 --> 02:24:59.331
Batman claimed to purchase 600,000 acres.

02:24:59.331 --> 02:25:02.468
The dubious agreement involved simple trinkets

02:25:02.468 --> 02:25:04.970
in exchange for vast lands.

02:25:04.970 --> 02:25:08.240
In 1836, the colony of South Australia

02:25:08.240 --> 02:25:10.042
was officially proclaimed,

02:25:10.042 --> 02:25:13.445
and with grand fanfare, Adelaide was born.

02:25:13.445 --> 02:25:15.881
Meanwhile to the east in New South Wales,

02:25:15.881 --> 02:25:18.684
the relentless explorer Major Thomas Mitchell

02:25:18.684 --> 02:25:20.953
ventured further into the southeast,

02:25:20.953 --> 02:25:23.122
painting tales of fertile lands,

02:25:23.122 --> 02:25:26.792
coaxing more settlers to dream of new beginnings.

02:25:26.792 --> 02:25:29.661
1837, the colony of Victoria,

02:25:29.661 --> 02:25:31.363
named after Queen Victoria,

02:25:31.363 --> 02:25:33.198
was officially recognized.

02:25:33.198 --> 02:25:37.069
The name of the city Batmania was changed to Melbourne.

02:25:38.036 --> 02:25:41.473
(dramatic music)

02:25:41.473 --> 02:25:44.143
While in China, the British were facing an issue.

02:25:44.143 --> 02:25:46.945
They loved the taste of Chinese tea.

02:25:46.945 --> 02:25:48.614
All across the empire,

02:25:48.614 --> 02:25:50.916
people wanted to drink the luxurious tea.

02:25:50.916 --> 02:25:52.551
The only problem was that the British

02:25:52.551 --> 02:25:55.954
didn't have anything worth that the Chinese desired,

02:25:55.954 --> 02:25:58.724
except for Indian opium.

02:25:58.724 --> 02:26:01.226
The highly addictive drug ruined lives

02:26:01.226 --> 02:26:04.897
and the Qing Dynasty did not want it in their empire.

02:26:04.897 --> 02:26:07.533
So the Qing dynasty appointed Lin Zexu

02:26:07.533 --> 02:26:10.669
to eradicate all opium trading within China.

02:26:10.669 --> 02:26:12.204
His approach was unwavering,

02:26:12.204 --> 02:26:14.306
confiscate and destroy.

02:26:14.306 --> 02:26:16.942
The beaches of Guangzhou soon bore witness

02:26:16.942 --> 02:26:18.410
to an immense pyre

02:26:18.410 --> 02:26:21.580
with tons of confiscated opium set ablaze,

02:26:21.580 --> 02:26:24.516
sending dark plumes of smoke skywards.

02:26:24.516 --> 02:26:26.051
The message was clear.

02:26:26.051 --> 02:26:29.087
China would no longer be a silent spectator.

02:26:29.087 --> 02:26:31.557
This act was not taken lightly by the British.

02:26:31.557 --> 02:26:33.325
The far-reaching British Empire

02:26:33.325 --> 02:26:36.028
saw it as a violation of trade rights.

02:26:36.028 --> 02:26:40.032
Their navy, bolstered by ironclad steam powered gunboats,

02:26:40.032 --> 02:26:43.702
was sent with an order to protect British interests.

02:26:43.702 --> 02:26:47.039
The waters of China, especially near its treasured ports,

02:26:47.039 --> 02:26:51.109
became a theater of naval skirmishes and confrontations.

02:26:51.109 --> 02:26:53.812
Soon the British forces proved too formidable

02:26:53.812 --> 02:26:55.280
for the Qing dynasty.

02:26:55.280 --> 02:26:57.449
Using their superior naval power,

02:26:57.449 --> 02:27:00.419
they made strategic advancements along the coast.

02:27:00.419 --> 02:27:03.989
The Chinese defenses steeped in traditional warfare

02:27:03.989 --> 02:27:06.291
were ill-equipped against the fire power

02:27:06.291 --> 02:27:07.926
of the British gunboats.

02:27:07.926 --> 02:27:09.595
The two nations found themselves

02:27:09.595 --> 02:27:12.998
at a negotiating table in Nanking as the dust settled.

02:27:12.998 --> 02:27:16.501
The resulting Treaty of Nanking was heavily skewed

02:27:16.501 --> 02:27:18.170
in favor of the British.

02:27:18.170 --> 02:27:20.038
A bitter pill for the Chinese,

02:27:20.038 --> 02:27:23.075
the treaty saw them ceding the island of Hong Kong,

02:27:23.075 --> 02:27:25.210
paying a hefty indemnity,

02:27:25.210 --> 02:27:27.479
and opening up their ports to the British

02:27:27.479 --> 02:27:30.515
so that they could legally sell their opium.

02:27:30.515 --> 02:27:33.085
(bright music)

02:27:35.454 --> 02:27:37.589
Off the coast of Australia lies

02:27:37.589 --> 02:27:39.891
the attractive island of New Zealand.

02:27:39.891 --> 02:27:42.294
Many British settlers moved from Australia

02:27:42.294 --> 02:27:45.297
to the neighboring island to establish their homes.

02:27:45.297 --> 02:27:47.866
However, the islands were not empty.

02:27:47.866 --> 02:27:50.502
They were inhabited by the Maori people,

02:27:50.502 --> 02:27:51.770
an Aboriginal tribe

02:27:51.770 --> 02:27:54.539
that has been there for thousands of years.

02:27:54.539 --> 02:27:57.109
Lieutenant Governor William Hobson had the task

02:27:57.109 --> 02:28:00.078
of securing British sovereignty over New Zealand.

02:28:00.078 --> 02:28:02.180
So he wrote the Treaty of Waitangi

02:28:02.180 --> 02:28:04.616
in a matter of days in English,

02:28:04.616 --> 02:28:08.153
and then shortly after, it was translated into Maori.

02:28:08.153 --> 02:28:12.891
On February 6th, when 500 Maori citizens debated the treaty,

02:28:12.891 --> 02:28:15.560
they thought they discussed the same document.

02:28:15.560 --> 02:28:18.230
However, the translation was inaccurate,

02:28:18.230 --> 02:28:20.165
which caused future tension.

02:28:20.165 --> 02:28:21.667
In the English version,

02:28:21.667 --> 02:28:24.770
Maori cede the sovereignty of New Zealand to Britain,

02:28:24.770 --> 02:28:26.938
Maori give the crown an exclusive right

02:28:26.938 --> 02:28:29.107
to buy lands they wish to sell,

02:28:29.107 --> 02:28:32.377
and in return, are guaranteed full rights of ownership

02:28:32.377 --> 02:28:36.315
of their lands, forests, fisheries and other possessions.

02:28:36.315 --> 02:28:38.717
Maori are given the rights and privileges

02:28:38.717 --> 02:28:40.452
of British subjects.

02:28:40.452 --> 02:28:42.988
However, in the Maori version,

02:28:42.988 --> 02:28:47.025
the word sovereignty was translated as kawanatanga,

02:28:47.025 --> 02:28:49.161
which means governance.

02:28:49.161 --> 02:28:51.229
The Maori people thought they were giving up

02:28:51.229 --> 02:28:52.831
their right to government.

02:28:52.831 --> 02:28:53.932
They did not realize

02:28:53.932 --> 02:28:56.368
they were giving supreme power to the Crown

02:28:56.368 --> 02:28:58.570
to do whatever they pleased.

02:28:58.570 --> 02:29:00.005
Another translation error

02:29:00.005 --> 02:29:02.240
was that the English version guaranteed

02:29:02.240 --> 02:29:05.544
undisturbed possession of all their properties.

02:29:05.544 --> 02:29:06.712
At the same time,

02:29:06.712 --> 02:29:10.949
the Maori version says, "Tino rangatiratanga taonga,"

02:29:10.949 --> 02:29:13.719
which translates into full authority

02:29:13.719 --> 02:29:16.688
over treasures that may be intangible.

02:29:16.688 --> 02:29:18.957
This slight difference meant the British believed

02:29:18.957 --> 02:29:22.294
they had exclusive rights to purchase land from the Maori

02:29:22.294 --> 02:29:24.062
and sell it to settlers.

02:29:24.062 --> 02:29:27.366
However, the Maori thought they would have full authority

02:29:27.366 --> 02:29:29.468
over their land and treasures

02:29:29.468 --> 02:29:31.970
and were not required to do such things.

02:29:31.970 --> 02:29:36.108
40 Maori chiefs, including Hone Heke, signed the treaty

02:29:36.108 --> 02:29:39.945
and the English enforced their version of the treaty.

02:29:39.945 --> 02:29:42.414
As time passed, the English bought the land

02:29:42.414 --> 02:29:44.282
without the Maori understanding

02:29:44.282 --> 02:29:47.419
since the English bought it based on the European system

02:29:47.419 --> 02:29:49.321
and the Maori didn't have the idea

02:29:49.321 --> 02:29:51.923
of land ownership in their society.

02:29:51.923 --> 02:29:55.193
That's when Hone Heke realized signing was a mistake.

02:29:55.193 --> 02:29:57.362
The Maori were no longer independent.

02:29:57.362 --> 02:30:00.232
So in a bold act of defiance,

02:30:00.232 --> 02:30:02.334
Heke, with the help of his allies,

02:30:02.334 --> 02:30:05.070
felled the Union Jack on Maiki Hill

02:30:05.070 --> 02:30:07.739
not once, but four times.

02:30:07.739 --> 02:30:09.875
The Kawiti settlement of Kororareka,

02:30:09.875 --> 02:30:11.309
modern-day Russell,

02:30:11.309 --> 02:30:13.311
soon became the battleground.

02:30:13.311 --> 02:30:15.447
In March, 1845, Hone Heke

02:30:15.447 --> 02:30:20.018
and the formidable chief Te Ruki Kawiti devised a plan.

02:30:20.018 --> 02:30:22.220
As Heke engaged the British forces

02:30:22.220 --> 02:30:23.955
and their Maori allies,

02:30:23.955 --> 02:30:25.724
drawing their gaze and might,

02:30:25.724 --> 02:30:28.460
they were prepared to strike the British directly.

02:30:28.460 --> 02:30:31.563
The battle that ensued saw the streets of Kororareka turn

02:30:31.563 --> 02:30:35.801
from bustling lanes of trade to avenues of conflict.

02:30:35.801 --> 02:30:38.603
The echoes of musket fire reverberated,

02:30:38.603 --> 02:30:41.273
mixing with the thunderous roars of cannons

02:30:41.273 --> 02:30:44.376
from the British naval ship HMS Hazard.

02:30:44.376 --> 02:30:45.911
When the ship's captain met his end

02:30:45.911 --> 02:30:50.182
at the hands of a Maori sniper, the tide began to turn.

02:30:50.182 --> 02:30:52.651
Kororareka, under the weight of the onslaught,

02:30:52.651 --> 02:30:54.052
began to crumble.

02:30:54.052 --> 02:30:57.255
The British, realizing the town's precarious position,

02:30:57.255 --> 02:31:00.692
initiated a retreat, evacuating its residence.

02:31:00.692 --> 02:31:04.329
As they withdrew, flames consumed parts of the city,

02:31:04.329 --> 02:31:06.832
painting the sky a fiery orange.

02:31:06.832 --> 02:31:08.533
After a series of battles,

02:31:08.533 --> 02:31:10.669
the English started to send more troops

02:31:10.669 --> 02:31:15.040
because they knew the fighting with the Maori wasn't done.

02:31:15.040 --> 02:31:16.641
(dramatic music)

02:31:16.641 --> 02:31:18.643
While in the Indian subcontinent,

02:31:18.643 --> 02:31:20.512
the Sikh empire in Punjab

02:31:20.512 --> 02:31:22.881
was going through a succession crisis

02:31:22.881 --> 02:31:25.817
after the death of Maharaja Ranjit Singh.

02:31:25.817 --> 02:31:29.221
The Sikh army called the Khalsa gained all the power

02:31:29.221 --> 02:31:31.523
and turned it into a military state.

02:31:31.523 --> 02:31:33.959
The Khalsa moved towards the Sutlej River,

02:31:33.959 --> 02:31:37.395
the border between the Sikh Empire and British India.

02:31:37.395 --> 02:31:40.131
The British, interpreting this as provocative,

02:31:40.131 --> 02:31:41.867
were quick to respond.

02:31:41.867 --> 02:31:46.671
The first military engagement at Mudki in December 1845

02:31:46.671 --> 02:31:49.541
pitted the British troops led by Sir Hugh Gough

02:31:49.541 --> 02:31:51.743
and Governor General Sir Henry Hardinge

02:31:51.743 --> 02:31:53.111
against the Sikhs.

02:31:53.111 --> 02:31:54.980
With their artillery advantage,

02:31:54.980 --> 02:31:57.349
the British managed to secure a victory,

02:31:57.349 --> 02:32:00.318
but not without considerable losses.

02:32:00.318 --> 02:32:02.420
A few days later at Feroze Shah,

02:32:02.420 --> 02:32:05.490
the British once again faced the Sikh forces.

02:32:05.490 --> 02:32:07.492
This confrontation was intense,

02:32:07.492 --> 02:32:10.028
spanning two days of fierce combat.

02:32:10.028 --> 02:32:12.998
The British faced a grim scenario on the first day

02:32:12.998 --> 02:32:16.268
with their troops exhausted and ammunition low.

02:32:16.268 --> 02:32:17.569
Yet with reinforcements

02:32:17.569 --> 02:32:20.272
and a resolute counterattack on the second day,

02:32:20.272 --> 02:32:22.741
they claimed another hard-fought victory.

02:32:22.741 --> 02:32:25.977
In the aftermath, the Treaty of Lahore was drafted.

02:32:25.977 --> 02:32:28.780
The Sikhs were made to cede the valuable region

02:32:28.780 --> 02:32:32.784
between the Beas and Sutlej Rivers, pay reparations,

02:32:32.784 --> 02:32:35.854
and recognize a British resident in Lahore.

02:32:35.854 --> 02:32:37.856
However, the peace was shortlived

02:32:37.856 --> 02:32:39.224
because under Sikhs leaders,

02:32:39.224 --> 02:32:42.360
Maharaja Duleep Singh and Diwan Mulraj

02:32:42.360 --> 02:32:43.828
wanted their land back.

02:32:43.828 --> 02:32:45.797
After many battles were fought,

02:32:45.797 --> 02:32:48.099
the Battle of Gujrat was underway.

02:32:48.099 --> 02:32:49.668
The British forces unleashed

02:32:49.668 --> 02:32:52.203
a concentrated artillery bombardment

02:32:52.203 --> 02:32:54.172
against the Sikh positions.

02:32:54.172 --> 02:32:55.907
The relentless firepower

02:32:55.907 --> 02:32:59.177
coupled with a coordinated infantry and cavalry assault

02:32:59.177 --> 02:33:00.912
broke the Sikh lines,

02:33:00.912 --> 02:33:03.248
leading to a decisive British victory.

02:33:03.248 --> 02:33:07.485
This led to the second Treaty of Lahore in March 1849.

02:33:07.485 --> 02:33:11.423
Maharaja Duleep Singh, the young ruler of the Sikh Empire,

02:33:11.423 --> 02:33:13.224
was formally deposed

02:33:13.224 --> 02:33:14.826
and the empire was annexed

02:33:14.826 --> 02:33:18.096
into the British East India Company's territories.

02:33:18.096 --> 02:33:21.833
Punjab was officially under British control.

02:33:21.833 --> 02:33:23.001
(dramatic music)

02:33:23.001 --> 02:33:24.436
The British weren't satisfied

02:33:24.436 --> 02:33:26.638
with their dominant control of India.

02:33:26.638 --> 02:33:28.640
They wanted it all.

02:33:28.640 --> 02:33:30.942
That's when the Governor General of India,

02:33:30.942 --> 02:33:32.510
Lord James Dalhousie,

02:33:32.510 --> 02:33:35.080
created the Doctrine of Lapse Policy.

02:33:35.080 --> 02:33:36.348
This policy declared

02:33:36.348 --> 02:33:38.717
that if any ruler of a dependent state died

02:33:38.717 --> 02:33:42.087
without a direct heir or the ruler was incompetent,

02:33:42.087 --> 02:33:45.824
the British would be given full control of the territory.

02:33:45.824 --> 02:33:48.126
He and his queen, Rani Lakshmibai,

02:33:48.126 --> 02:33:51.096
did not have surviving biological children.

02:33:51.096 --> 02:33:52.597
However, before his death,

02:33:52.597 --> 02:33:56.401
the Maharaja adopted a child named Damodar Rao.

02:33:56.401 --> 02:33:59.537
Rani Lakshmibai presented the young Damodar Rao

02:33:59.537 --> 02:34:00.872
to the British officers

02:34:00.872 --> 02:34:03.408
as the heir to the throne of Jhansi.

02:34:03.408 --> 02:34:06.211
However, Governor General Lord Dalhousie,

02:34:06.211 --> 02:34:08.213
invoking the Doctrine of Lapse,

02:34:08.213 --> 02:34:10.949
refused to recognize the adopted child

02:34:10.949 --> 02:34:12.651
as the legitimate heir.

02:34:12.651 --> 02:34:15.086
Instead, they were annexed by the British

02:34:15.086 --> 02:34:17.022
and lost all autonomy.

02:34:17.022 --> 02:34:18.890
Regions and princely states,

02:34:18.890 --> 02:34:23.061
such as Satara, Jaipur, Sambalpur, Nagpur, and Awadh,

02:34:23.061 --> 02:34:25.063
were all annexed this way.

02:34:25.063 --> 02:34:27.866
At the time, the British East India Company Army

02:34:27.866 --> 02:34:30.935
was mostly made of Indian soldiers called sepoy.

02:34:30.935 --> 02:34:34.072
These sepoys were paid less and treated poorly

02:34:34.072 --> 02:34:36.574
and they had enough of being under British rule.

02:34:36.574 --> 02:34:38.743
So in March 1857,

02:34:38.743 --> 02:34:41.713
a sepoy named Mangal Pandey mutinied

02:34:41.713 --> 02:34:44.883
against his British officers at Barrackpore,

02:34:44.883 --> 02:34:47.318
for which he was subsequently hanged.

02:34:47.318 --> 02:34:49.688
However, the spark had been sowed,

02:34:49.688 --> 02:34:54.693
and on May 10th, 1857, in Meerut, 85 sepoys rebelled.

02:34:55.260 --> 02:34:57.328
They broke rank, stormed the jail,

02:34:57.328 --> 02:35:00.465
and released their 85 imprisoned comrades.

02:35:00.465 --> 02:35:02.734
But their rage didn't stop there.

02:35:02.734 --> 02:35:04.969
The mutiny rapidly expanded,

02:35:04.969 --> 02:35:07.939
killing several British officers, Europeans,

02:35:07.939 --> 02:35:10.475
and Christian Indians in the cantonment.

02:35:10.475 --> 02:35:12.210
Buildings were set on fire

02:35:12.210 --> 02:35:14.846
and Meerut was in chaos by nightfall.

02:35:14.846 --> 02:35:17.949
Many of the mutineers decided not to stay in Meerut,

02:35:17.949 --> 02:35:20.385
knowing they couldn't hold the garrison town.

02:35:20.385 --> 02:35:22.520
They began an overnight march to Delhi,

02:35:22.520 --> 02:35:24.622
which they reached the following day.

02:35:24.622 --> 02:35:27.358
Their sudden and unexpected arrival surprised

02:35:27.358 --> 02:35:29.627
the small British garrison in the city.

02:35:29.627 --> 02:35:32.163
The local infantry unit stationed in Delhi

02:35:32.163 --> 02:35:35.033
and a large section of the city's civilian population

02:35:35.033 --> 02:35:36.634
joined the mutineers.

02:35:36.634 --> 02:35:39.637
They targeted British officers, civilians,

02:35:39.637 --> 02:35:41.172
and anyone associated

02:35:41.172 --> 02:35:44.109
with the East India Company's administration.

02:35:44.109 --> 02:35:46.044
The strategic Red Fort,

02:35:46.044 --> 02:35:49.848
the residence of the Mughal Emperor Bahadur Shah Zafar,

02:35:49.848 --> 02:35:51.950
was soon in their control.

02:35:51.950 --> 02:35:54.786
However, the British weren't ready to surrender.

02:35:54.786 --> 02:35:56.988
By early June, British forces,

02:35:56.988 --> 02:36:00.058
a mix of Europeans and loyal Indian regiments,

02:36:00.058 --> 02:36:01.826
assembled outside Delhi.

02:36:01.826 --> 02:36:05.730
General Archdale Wilson, a seasoned military man,

02:36:05.730 --> 02:36:07.532
looked at the formidable city walls

02:36:07.532 --> 02:36:09.801
respectfully and determinedly.

02:36:09.801 --> 02:36:12.103
Delhi had to be retaken.

02:36:12.103 --> 02:36:14.639
For the rebels within, the defense of Delhi

02:36:14.639 --> 02:36:17.542
was more than just a military strategy.

02:36:17.542 --> 02:36:19.310
The city was a symbol.

02:36:19.310 --> 02:36:21.913
It was about honor, a shared legacy,

02:36:21.913 --> 02:36:23.548
and a dream of freedom.

02:36:23.548 --> 02:36:24.916
Under their control,

02:36:24.916 --> 02:36:28.453
the streets resonated with both hope and zeal,

02:36:28.453 --> 02:36:30.922
but this hope was soon to be tested.

02:36:30.922 --> 02:36:34.092
As days progressed, British cannons from The Ridge,

02:36:34.092 --> 02:36:36.761
a strategic high ground north of Delhi,

02:36:36.761 --> 02:36:38.997
began their relentless bombardment.

02:36:38.997 --> 02:36:42.233
The city responded in kind with its own guns roaring,

02:36:42.233 --> 02:36:44.736
painting the sky with trails of smoke.

02:36:44.736 --> 02:36:48.039
Then in early September, the British had their break.

02:36:48.039 --> 02:36:50.141
General John Nicholson led troops

02:36:50.141 --> 02:36:51.943
to storm the Kashmere Gate,

02:36:51.943 --> 02:36:55.446
using explosives to breach this formidable entry point.

02:36:55.446 --> 02:36:59.317
As the dust settled, British forces began pouring in.

02:36:59.317 --> 02:37:02.720
Delhi's narrow alleys turned into mazes of combat.

02:37:02.720 --> 02:37:05.456
Rebel sniper shots from hidden rooftops,

02:37:05.456 --> 02:37:07.358
British bayonet charges,

02:37:07.358 --> 02:37:08.860
and street-to-street combat

02:37:08.860 --> 02:37:11.162
characterized the following days.

02:37:11.162 --> 02:37:13.431
Every corner of Chandni Chowk,

02:37:13.431 --> 02:37:14.799
every gate of the fort,

02:37:14.799 --> 02:37:17.035
became a testament to the bravery

02:37:17.035 --> 02:37:19.103
and the brutality of war.

02:37:19.103 --> 02:37:23.007
By September 20th, the British had a firm grip on Delhi.

02:37:23.007 --> 02:37:25.944
The Red Fort was once again under their control,

02:37:25.944 --> 02:37:29.714
Bahadur Shah Zafar II, the leader of the rebellion,

02:37:29.714 --> 02:37:31.649
was captured shortly after,

02:37:31.649 --> 02:37:34.752
marking a poignant end to the sepoys' rebellion

02:37:34.752 --> 02:37:37.055
and the rule of the Mughal dynasty.

02:37:37.055 --> 02:37:38.156
In the aftermath,

02:37:38.156 --> 02:37:41.359
British retribution was swift and unforgiving.

02:37:41.359 --> 02:37:43.828
Many rebels met their end at the gallows

02:37:43.828 --> 02:37:47.198
and parts of the city were left scarred and desolate.

02:37:47.198 --> 02:37:50.268
The Indian Rebellion wasn't just isolated to Delhi,

02:37:50.268 --> 02:37:52.904
but covered the entire subcontinent.

02:37:52.904 --> 02:37:54.806
However, just like Delhi,

02:37:54.806 --> 02:37:57.842
the British quickly obliterated their opponents

02:37:57.842 --> 02:37:59.577
and forced them to surrender.

02:37:59.577 --> 02:38:01.312
As the gunshots ended,

02:38:01.312 --> 02:38:05.250
Britain passed the Government of India Act 1858,

02:38:05.250 --> 02:38:07.952
which ended the British East India Company

02:38:07.952 --> 02:38:10.388
and replaced it with the British Raj,

02:38:10.388 --> 02:38:13.825
which meant the Indian people were under the direct control

02:38:13.825 --> 02:38:16.227
of the Monarch Queen Victoria.

02:38:16.227 --> 02:38:18.596
There was no illusion of self-governance

02:38:18.596 --> 02:38:20.565
or financial companies.

02:38:20.565 --> 02:38:22.767
They were a colony of Britain.

02:38:22.767 --> 02:38:25.904
Under the Queen, a Council of India was created.

02:38:25.904 --> 02:38:28.373
The council, which consisted of 15 people

02:38:28.373 --> 02:38:31.843
who did not speak any of the native Indian languages,

02:38:31.843 --> 02:38:33.878
were given tyrannical controls

02:38:33.878 --> 02:38:36.848
of all political powers within the colony.

02:38:36.848 --> 02:38:39.183
British individuals were declared governors

02:38:39.183 --> 02:38:40.752
of different regions.

02:38:40.752 --> 02:38:42.053
English schools were set up

02:38:42.053 --> 02:38:44.722
so that the whites in India could still get educated

02:38:44.722 --> 02:38:46.891
and rule over the Indians.

02:38:46.891 --> 02:38:49.460
The English did everything they could

02:38:49.460 --> 02:38:53.932
to be politically, economically, and socially in control.

02:38:53.932 --> 02:38:57.535
In their minds, just by being British, they were superior

02:38:57.535 --> 02:39:00.505
and had the right to rule over all of India.

02:39:00.505 --> 02:39:03.141
Now with the implementation of the Raj,

02:39:03.141 --> 02:39:05.877
their power has only grown.

02:39:05.877 --> 02:39:06.711
(dramatic music)

02:39:06.711 --> 02:39:09.714
In New Zealand, the Maori faced a similar fate

02:39:09.714 --> 02:39:13.051
when, in 1863, the British Empire passed

02:39:13.051 --> 02:39:15.053
the New Zealand Settlements Act,

02:39:15.053 --> 02:39:16.220
which allowed the government

02:39:16.220 --> 02:39:18.823
to confiscate land from the Maori tribes

02:39:18.823 --> 02:39:22.327
deemed to have rebelled against the crown.

02:39:22.327 --> 02:39:25.396
The Maori tried to unite and fend off the Brits

02:39:25.396 --> 02:39:27.732
in battles throughout the Waikato War,

02:39:27.732 --> 02:39:31.102
both the Taranaki Wars and the Te Kooti's War,

02:39:31.102 --> 02:39:34.105
however, nothing could fend off the British.

02:39:35.173 --> 02:39:37.008
Across the world in Jamaica,

02:39:37.008 --> 02:39:40.011
with the abolition of slavery decades ago,

02:39:40.011 --> 02:39:44.115
the island was populated mainly by poor former slaves.

02:39:44.115 --> 02:39:47.151
Due to the right to vote being tied to landowners,

02:39:47.151 --> 02:39:49.787
during the election of 1864,

02:39:49.787 --> 02:39:52.256
fewer than 2,000 Black men could vote

02:39:52.256 --> 02:39:56.427
out of a Black population of 420,000,

02:39:56.427 --> 02:39:59.764
while 10,000 men were given the privilege.

02:39:59.764 --> 02:40:01.933
This happened while Jamaica was in a drought,

02:40:01.933 --> 02:40:04.402
dealing with cholera and smallpox.

02:40:04.402 --> 02:40:08.573
Tensions were high when, on October 11th, 1865,

02:40:08.573 --> 02:40:11.943
a minor altercation outside a courthouse in Morant Bay

02:40:11.943 --> 02:40:14.846
escalated into a major confrontation.

02:40:14.846 --> 02:40:16.314
A Black man was imprisoned

02:40:16.314 --> 02:40:19.751
for trespassing on a long abandoned plantation.

02:40:19.751 --> 02:40:21.953
When a bystander protested the arrest,

02:40:21.953 --> 02:40:25.256
police tried to apprehend him, leading to skirmishes.

02:40:25.256 --> 02:40:28.626
Paul Bogle, a Baptist deacon and activist,

02:40:28.626 --> 02:40:31.529
led a march of hundreds from the village of Stony Gut

02:40:31.529 --> 02:40:32.730
to Morant Bay.

02:40:32.730 --> 02:40:35.133
The protest quickly turned violent

02:40:35.133 --> 02:40:37.368
with the courthouse being burned down

02:40:37.368 --> 02:40:40.571
and several officials and militia members killed.

02:40:40.571 --> 02:40:43.574
Governor Edward John Eyre declared martial law

02:40:43.574 --> 02:40:45.343
in response to the rebellion.

02:40:45.343 --> 02:40:48.846
Over a few weeks, as many as 1,000 Black Jamaicans

02:40:48.846 --> 02:40:50.982
were killed by British forces

02:40:50.982 --> 02:40:53.484
and many more were flogged or punished.

02:40:53.484 --> 02:40:55.720
Paul Bogle and George William Gordon,

02:40:55.720 --> 02:40:58.790
a mixed race legislator and critic of the governor

02:40:58.790 --> 02:41:01.125
accused of conspiring in the rebellion,

02:41:01.125 --> 02:41:04.028
were hastily tried and executed.

02:41:04.028 --> 02:41:05.296
After the rebellion,

02:41:05.296 --> 02:41:06.831
the British government dissolved

02:41:06.831 --> 02:41:08.666
the Jamaican House of Assembly

02:41:08.666 --> 02:41:11.402
and replaced it with a British-appointed governor.

02:41:11.402 --> 02:41:13.971
This allowed Great Britain complete control

02:41:13.971 --> 02:41:17.175
of all Jamaican policies.

02:41:17.175 --> 02:41:19.544
While in Canada, the British restructured

02:41:19.544 --> 02:41:22.146
the six separate colonies of Upper Canada,

02:41:22.146 --> 02:41:24.115
Lower Canada, New Brunswick,

02:41:24.115 --> 02:41:28.119
Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, and British Columbia

02:41:28.119 --> 02:41:31.789
into a singular territory, the Dominion of Canada.

02:41:32.657 --> 02:41:33.724
(dramatic music)

02:41:33.724 --> 02:41:36.794
However, the Ashanti peoples in the Gold Coast,

02:41:36.794 --> 02:41:38.129
modern-day Ghana,

02:41:38.129 --> 02:41:40.498
felt they could take land from the British.

02:41:40.498 --> 02:41:44.202
The Fante region was between the Ashanti and the British,

02:41:44.202 --> 02:41:46.971
a buffer that kept the two empires at bay.

02:41:46.971 --> 02:41:49.407
The Ashanti saw the Fante territories

02:41:49.407 --> 02:41:50.842
as part of their sphere,

02:41:50.842 --> 02:41:53.544
while the British viewed them under their protection.

02:41:53.544 --> 02:41:56.781
This tenuous balance was about to be disrupted.

02:41:56.781 --> 02:41:58.783
Under King Kofi Karikari,

02:41:58.783 --> 02:42:02.720
the Ashanti people lauded a campaign into the Fante lands.

02:42:02.720 --> 02:42:05.723
They laid siege to the coastal ford of Elmina,

02:42:05.723 --> 02:42:09.193
and soon the British colonial capital Cape Coast

02:42:09.193 --> 02:42:12.630
felt the weight of Ashanti ambition pressing upon it.

02:42:12.630 --> 02:42:15.399
It wasn't long before Sir Garner Wolseley,

02:42:15.399 --> 02:42:17.602
a battle-hardened British officer

02:42:17.602 --> 02:42:20.037
armed with modern rifles and cannons,

02:42:20.037 --> 02:42:21.939
landed on the Gold Coast.

02:42:21.939 --> 02:42:24.575
Soon they met at the village of Amofal,

02:42:24.575 --> 02:42:26.844
which the Ashanti had turned into a fortress

02:42:26.844 --> 02:42:28.779
that seemed impenetrable.

02:42:28.779 --> 02:42:30.982
When Wolseley's men reached the village,

02:42:30.982 --> 02:42:33.985
the Ashanti warriors used the dense underbrush

02:42:33.985 --> 02:42:36.187
for stealthy guerilla attacks.

02:42:36.187 --> 02:42:37.889
Their ambushes were deadly.

02:42:37.889 --> 02:42:40.291
Their knowledge of the terrain unparalleled.

02:42:40.291 --> 02:42:41.993
But Wolseley had a plan.

02:42:41.993 --> 02:42:44.529
He dispatched his forces in multiple columns

02:42:44.529 --> 02:42:48.566
to surround and squeeze the Ashanti out of their defenses.

02:42:48.566 --> 02:42:49.834
As dusk approached,

02:42:49.834 --> 02:42:52.803
the village of Amofal came under British control

02:42:52.803 --> 02:42:55.006
after witnessing fierce combat.

02:42:55.006 --> 02:42:57.742
The Ashanti warriors had to retreat.

02:42:57.742 --> 02:42:58.843
The following year,

02:42:58.843 --> 02:43:01.779
Kofi Karikari signed the Treaty of Fomena,

02:43:01.779 --> 02:43:05.483
which renounced the Ashanti claims to the Fante territories

02:43:05.483 --> 02:43:07.451
and that Kofi would abdicate.

02:43:07.451 --> 02:43:10.221
The Ashanti became a British protectorate,

02:43:10.221 --> 02:43:13.591
though they retained some internal autonomy.

02:43:13.591 --> 02:43:17.328
The word of England might have spread like the plague,

02:43:17.328 --> 02:43:20.198
and some kings knew they should voluntarily surrender

02:43:20.198 --> 02:43:22.066
to the English for their people.

02:43:22.066 --> 02:43:25.236
Chief Cakobau, the king of the Fiji islands,

02:43:25.236 --> 02:43:28.072
knew his islands were targets of the British.

02:43:28.072 --> 02:43:30.675
Facing internal pressures, mounting debts,

02:43:30.675 --> 02:43:33.644
and the looming threat of involuntary annexation,

02:43:33.644 --> 02:43:36.247
Cakobau saw a potential solution

02:43:36.247 --> 02:43:38.649
in ceding sovereignty voluntarily.

02:43:38.649 --> 02:43:40.918
He believed becoming a British protectorate

02:43:40.918 --> 02:43:43.054
could ensure internal stability

02:43:43.054 --> 02:43:45.656
and guard against other colonial powers.

02:43:45.656 --> 02:43:49.894
After negotiations, on October 10th, 1874,

02:43:49.894 --> 02:43:53.164
Cakobau formally joined the British Empire.

02:43:54.532 --> 02:43:57.435
Some areas could just be bought with money.

02:43:57.435 --> 02:43:59.203
The Suez Canal was completed

02:43:59.203 --> 02:44:03.207
in a French-Egyptian joint project in 1869.

02:44:03.207 --> 02:44:06.043
The Suez Canal was revolutionary

02:44:06.043 --> 02:44:09.380
because the waterway offered direct maritime passage

02:44:09.380 --> 02:44:12.116
between the Mediterranean and the Red Sea,

02:44:12.116 --> 02:44:14.318
slashing the duration of the voyage

02:44:14.318 --> 02:44:16.420
to the British Raj in India.

02:44:16.420 --> 02:44:20.024
However, building such a canal put Isma'il Pasha,

02:44:20.024 --> 02:44:21.726
the Khedive ruler of Egypt,

02:44:21.726 --> 02:44:23.327
in extraordinary debt.

02:44:23.327 --> 02:44:25.896
So British Prime Minister Benjamin Disraeli

02:44:25.896 --> 02:44:30.901
raised four million pounds to buy 44% of the canal shares.

02:44:30.901 --> 02:44:35.706
The value of this would be 378 million pounds today.

02:44:35.706 --> 02:44:39.277
With the transaction finalized in 1875,

02:44:39.277 --> 02:44:43.347
the balance of power over the Suez Canal tilted decisively

02:44:43.347 --> 02:44:44.615
in Britain's favor.

02:44:45.549 --> 02:44:48.786
Sometimes other countries would be asked to join.

02:44:48.786 --> 02:44:51.022
In December of 1878,

02:44:51.022 --> 02:44:53.991
Sir Henry Bartle Frere sent an ultimatum

02:44:53.991 --> 02:44:55.926
to the Zulu King Cetshwayo.

02:44:55.926 --> 02:44:58.929
Frere felt that Zulus was getting too strong

02:44:58.929 --> 02:45:00.331
and needed to be stopped.

02:45:00.331 --> 02:45:04.368
So he told the Zulu to surrender or go to war.

02:45:04.368 --> 02:45:06.137
Cetshwayo chose to fight.

02:45:06.137 --> 02:45:09.840
So on January 22nd, 1879,

02:45:09.840 --> 02:45:11.542
on the plains of Isandlwana,

02:45:11.542 --> 02:45:15.313
the two forces first clashed with unforgettable fury.

02:45:15.313 --> 02:45:17.682
Using traditional tactics and shields,

02:45:17.682 --> 02:45:20.651
the disciplined impi overran the British camp

02:45:20.651 --> 02:45:22.887
in an unprecedented victory,

02:45:22.887 --> 02:45:26.424
leaving over 1,300 British soldiers lifeless

02:45:26.424 --> 02:45:27.758
on the battlefield.

02:45:27.758 --> 02:45:30.528
However, spears and shields made out of cowhide

02:45:30.528 --> 02:45:33.331
can't beat muskets and helmets in the long run.

02:45:33.331 --> 02:45:37.702
On March 29th, the Zulu warriors faced a setback at Kambula,

02:45:37.702 --> 02:45:40.204
and by April 2nd, at Gingindlovu,

02:45:40.204 --> 02:45:43.574
it was evident that British technological superiority

02:45:43.574 --> 02:45:45.076
was beginning to tell.

02:45:45.076 --> 02:45:48.412
July 4th marked the final act of this drama.

02:45:48.412 --> 02:45:50.581
At the Royal Kraal of Ulundi,

02:45:50.581 --> 02:45:54.051
British and Zulu forces clashed for the last time.

02:45:54.051 --> 02:45:56.187
The British, under Lord Chelmsford,

02:45:56.187 --> 02:45:57.988
dealt a decisive blow,

02:45:57.988 --> 02:45:59.990
capturing the Zulu capital,

02:45:59.990 --> 02:46:04.061
allowing Britain even more control in South Africa.

02:46:05.563 --> 02:46:08.366
However, the British weren't done in South Africa

02:46:08.366 --> 02:46:10.568
because in December 1880,

02:46:10.568 --> 02:46:11.736
the Boers declared

02:46:11.736 --> 02:46:15.406
the gold-rich region of Transvaal independent,

02:46:15.406 --> 02:46:17.708
challenging the might of the British.

02:46:17.708 --> 02:46:20.111
A series of confrontations ensued.

02:46:20.111 --> 02:46:22.613
Using their intimate knowledge of the terrain,

02:46:22.613 --> 02:46:25.750
the Boers ambushed British troops at Bronkhorstspruit,

02:46:25.750 --> 02:46:27.952
delivering a stinging blow.

02:46:27.952 --> 02:46:31.722
The British faced a monumental defeat atop Majuba Hill

02:46:31.722 --> 02:46:33.991
in February 1881,

02:46:33.991 --> 02:46:35.192
losing their commander,

02:46:35.192 --> 02:46:38.095
Major general Sir George Pomeroy Colley.

02:46:38.095 --> 02:46:40.297
The intensity of Boers resistance

02:46:40.297 --> 02:46:43.033
forced the British into reconciliation.

02:46:43.033 --> 02:46:46.704
By March 1881, the Treaty of Pretoria was signed,

02:46:46.704 --> 02:46:48.873
returning the Transvaal to the Boers

02:46:48.873 --> 02:46:51.108
but under British suzerainty.

02:46:51.108 --> 02:46:52.943
(bright music)

02:46:52.943 --> 02:46:55.212
Egypt, the once great country

02:46:55.212 --> 02:46:57.348
filled with pyramids and pharaohs,

02:46:57.348 --> 02:46:59.550
is now in debt to foreign bankers

02:46:59.550 --> 02:47:01.652
with little future prosperity.

02:47:01.652 --> 02:47:04.722
Ahmed Urabi, a young and charismatic officer

02:47:04.722 --> 02:47:05.923
in the Egyptian army,

02:47:05.923 --> 02:47:07.591
was ready for a change.

02:47:07.591 --> 02:47:09.326
Born into a peasant family,

02:47:09.326 --> 02:47:11.695
he had risen through the military ranks,

02:47:11.695 --> 02:47:13.931
not because of any privileged birthright,

02:47:13.931 --> 02:47:16.634
but due to sheer determination and skill.

02:47:16.634 --> 02:47:18.502
He saw the disparity daily,

02:47:18.502 --> 02:47:21.806
the Ottoman and Egyptian elite reveling in luxuries.

02:47:21.806 --> 02:47:25.643
At the same time, ordinary Egyptians toiled hard,

02:47:25.643 --> 02:47:27.411
sweat and blood feeding the elites

02:47:27.411 --> 02:47:29.480
and foreign bankers' dreams.

02:47:29.480 --> 02:47:32.316
Arubi met with fellow officers on a fateful day

02:47:32.316 --> 02:47:34.151
in a discreet tea house.

02:47:34.151 --> 02:47:36.720
Their passionate and heated conversations revolved

02:47:36.720 --> 02:47:39.557
around the pervasive European influence,

02:47:39.557 --> 02:47:41.625
the Suez Canal's control,

02:47:41.625 --> 02:47:44.695
and the need to restore dignity to the Egyptian people.

02:47:44.695 --> 02:47:48.599
That evening, casual musings evolved into an emotional vow

02:47:48.599 --> 02:47:50.034
to spark change.

02:47:50.034 --> 02:47:52.169
As word of his objective spread,

02:47:52.169 --> 02:47:54.138
his cause quickly found resonance

02:47:54.138 --> 02:47:55.973
with the broader population.

02:47:55.973 --> 02:47:58.576
The grievances of the military mirrored that

02:47:58.576 --> 02:48:00.211
of the ordinary Egyptian,

02:48:00.211 --> 02:48:02.279
resentment against the ruling elite

02:48:02.279 --> 02:48:04.982
and the intrusive European powers.

02:48:04.982 --> 02:48:08.486
This broad-based support transformed Arubi's movement

02:48:08.486 --> 02:48:12.656
from a military mutiny into a nationalist revolt.

02:48:12.656 --> 02:48:14.391
The message was clear:

02:48:14.391 --> 02:48:18.395
Egypt for Egyptians free from foreign dominance.

02:48:18.395 --> 02:48:21.131
However, Britain, deeply vested in Egypt

02:48:21.131 --> 02:48:24.001
due to the Suez Canal's strategic importance,

02:48:24.001 --> 02:48:26.871
viewed the Arabi-led movement as a threat.

02:48:26.871 --> 02:48:30.374
In 1882, alarmed by the nationalist fervor,

02:48:30.374 --> 02:48:32.676
British forces launched an intervention.

02:48:32.676 --> 02:48:35.579
The climax came at the battle of Battle of Tel El Kebir,

02:48:35.579 --> 02:48:39.316
where British troops defeated Arubi's army decisively.

02:48:39.316 --> 02:48:41.519
The aftermath was predictable.

02:48:41.519 --> 02:48:43.888
Ahmed Arubi was exiled to India,

02:48:43.888 --> 02:48:47.424
and while Egypt remained ostensibly an Ottoman province,

02:48:47.424 --> 02:48:50.561
it became a defacto British protectorate.

02:48:50.561 --> 02:48:53.797
The geopolitical realities of the Suez Canal

02:48:53.797 --> 02:48:56.000
and Britain's imperial designs meant

02:48:56.000 --> 02:48:59.003
that Egypt would remain under British influence

02:48:59.003 --> 02:49:00.704
for decades to come.

02:49:02.540 --> 02:49:05.242
On November 15th, 1884,

02:49:05.242 --> 02:49:07.878
Chancellor of Germany Otto von Bismarck

02:49:07.878 --> 02:49:10.581
invited 14 representatives to Berlin

02:49:10.581 --> 02:49:14.718
to discuss the looming issue: colonization of Africa.

02:49:14.718 --> 02:49:17.254
At the time, it was politically necessary

02:49:17.254 --> 02:49:19.290
to spread the influence of your country

02:49:19.290 --> 02:49:20.891
over to the lands of another

02:49:20.891 --> 02:49:23.360
because your regime would seem more powerful

02:49:23.360 --> 02:49:25.429
the more ground you could control.

02:49:25.429 --> 02:49:28.866
Since Europe had access to better military technology,

02:49:28.866 --> 02:49:32.336
they readily took over giant swathes of land.

02:49:32.336 --> 02:49:35.205
The issue, at least in the European minds,

02:49:35.205 --> 02:49:37.908
was that they didn't want to go to war with one another.

02:49:37.908 --> 02:49:39.476
Peace within Europe was the best way

02:49:39.476 --> 02:49:41.345
for them to reach prosperity.

02:49:41.345 --> 02:49:45.215
So as the 14 nations met at the Berlin Conference,

02:49:45.215 --> 02:49:48.886
they decided to set the ground rules for how to colonize.

02:49:48.886 --> 02:49:51.455
During the conference, Germany had this idea

02:49:51.455 --> 02:49:52.990
that no colonial power

02:49:52.990 --> 02:49:55.526
should have any legal right to a territory

02:49:55.526 --> 02:49:57.628
unless the state exercised

02:49:57.628 --> 02:50:00.297
solid and effective political control,

02:50:00.297 --> 02:50:03.200
and if so, only for a limited period,

02:50:03.200 --> 02:50:05.769
essentially an occupational force.

02:50:05.769 --> 02:50:08.572
However, since England has been on the continent

02:50:08.572 --> 02:50:13.210
since the days of the slave ships of John Hawkins in 1562,

02:50:13.210 --> 02:50:14.945
they had a different idea.

02:50:14.945 --> 02:50:16.747
Like their colonies in India,

02:50:16.747 --> 02:50:18.315
they wanted to gain as much land

02:50:18.315 --> 02:50:19.817
on the continent as possible

02:50:19.817 --> 02:50:21.552
with minimal responsibility

02:50:21.552 --> 02:50:23.787
to make as much money as possible.

02:50:23.787 --> 02:50:26.857
Britain, represented by Edward Baldwin Malet,

02:50:26.857 --> 02:50:28.359
got the conference to agree

02:50:28.359 --> 02:50:31.929
that any European nation could claim whatever land it liked

02:50:31.929 --> 02:50:33.797
with no repercussions.

02:50:33.797 --> 02:50:35.399
Of course, at this conference,

02:50:35.399 --> 02:50:38.636
there was no representation of Africa.

02:50:38.636 --> 02:50:41.372
No one at the meeting knew of their unique cultures,

02:50:41.372 --> 02:50:43.340
how the different tribes operated,

02:50:43.340 --> 02:50:45.142
and how they weren't all the same.

02:50:45.142 --> 02:50:46.910
At the conference of Berlin,

02:50:46.910 --> 02:50:51.015
Africa was just a map that needed more European flags.

02:50:51.015 --> 02:50:52.082
Trades were made,

02:50:52.082 --> 02:50:55.052
Germany acknowledged Britain's claim over Zanzibar,

02:50:55.052 --> 02:50:58.222
and Britain acknowledged Germany's claim over Tanzania.

02:50:58.222 --> 02:51:00.858
This helped the British gain massive control

02:51:00.858 --> 02:51:02.660
within the African continent.

02:51:02.660 --> 02:51:05.029
The protectorate of Bechuanaland was formed

02:51:05.029 --> 02:51:06.697
in modern-day Botswana.

02:51:06.697 --> 02:51:09.933
The British East African Company oversaw an area

02:51:09.933 --> 02:51:13.170
of 246,000 square miles

02:51:13.170 --> 02:51:15.739
from modern-day Somalia to Kenya.

02:51:15.739 --> 02:51:18.676
While in the south, the British South Africa Company

02:51:18.676 --> 02:51:21.845
wanted to expand the company from Cape to Cairo.

02:51:21.845 --> 02:51:24.715
However, this was never truly realized.

02:51:24.715 --> 02:51:26.050
Instead, they were relegated

02:51:26.050 --> 02:51:29.553
to the lands of modern-day Zimbabwe and Zambia.

02:51:29.553 --> 02:51:31.955
More handshakes and deals were to be made.

02:51:31.955 --> 02:51:34.458
In the Heligoland-Zanzibar Treaty,

02:51:34.458 --> 02:51:37.695
Germany ceded control of the sultanate of Zanzibar,

02:51:37.695 --> 02:51:39.563
territories that would make up Kenya,

02:51:39.563 --> 02:51:41.198
and the kingdom of Uganda

02:51:41.198 --> 02:51:43.200
in exchange for Heligoland,

02:51:43.200 --> 02:51:46.603
an island off the coast of Germany, the Caprivi Strip,

02:51:46.603 --> 02:51:50.541
and large parts of Togoland and Cameroon in west Africa.

02:51:50.541 --> 02:51:53.510
Soon enough, the British found themselves in control

02:51:53.510 --> 02:51:56.814
of the British Nyasaland, present-day Malawi,

02:51:56.814 --> 02:51:59.483
through the British Central Africa Protectorate,

02:51:59.483 --> 02:52:02.453
the formal colonization status of Uganda,

02:52:02.453 --> 02:52:04.822
and the British East Africa company

02:52:04.822 --> 02:52:07.624
to include most of the Kenyan regions.

02:52:07.624 --> 02:52:08.759
(dramatic music)

02:52:08.759 --> 02:52:10.694
As the British drew these lines,

02:52:10.694 --> 02:52:13.964
conflicts with the Native Africans were bound to happen.

02:52:13.964 --> 02:52:17.301
However, when the British forces were holding Maxim guns,

02:52:17.301 --> 02:52:19.670
the predecessor of the machine gun,

02:52:19.670 --> 02:52:22.906
and the Ndebele people, who were famous for their warfare,

02:52:22.906 --> 02:52:26.510
consisted of traditional spears and tall shields,

02:52:26.510 --> 02:52:28.545
the battle would be quickly decided.

02:52:28.545 --> 02:52:30.380
The British, under Cecil Rhodes,

02:52:30.380 --> 02:52:33.350
surrounded the Ndebele capital of Bulawayo

02:52:33.350 --> 02:52:35.719
and renamed the city to Rhodesia.

02:52:35.719 --> 02:52:40.524
The Ndebele people revolted again three years later in 1896

02:52:40.524 --> 02:52:44.061
despite their known technological disadvantage.

02:52:44.061 --> 02:52:46.430
The revolts caught the settlers off guard

02:52:46.430 --> 02:52:49.099
and they took refuge in forts like Rhodesia.

02:52:49.099 --> 02:52:51.802
However, as the months passed, the company,

02:52:51.802 --> 02:52:54.805
bolstered by reinforcements from the British Empire,

02:52:54.805 --> 02:52:56.540
began to turn the tide.

02:52:56.540 --> 02:52:58.942
The rebellion was brutally suppressed,

02:52:58.942 --> 02:53:00.344
leaders were captured,

02:53:00.344 --> 02:53:03.046
and a new era of dominance in Britain.

02:53:04.515 --> 02:53:06.617
The Ndebele people weren't the only ones

02:53:06.617 --> 02:53:09.419
to face the wrath of physical force.

02:53:09.419 --> 02:53:13.724
In 1897, Acting Consul General James Phillips believed

02:53:13.724 --> 02:53:17.194
he could reform the kingdom of Benin, modern-day Nigeria,

02:53:17.194 --> 02:53:20.297
ending practices like human sacrifice.

02:53:20.297 --> 02:53:22.166
Without formal authorization,

02:53:22.166 --> 02:53:25.202
he ventured towards Benin City with a small party,

02:53:25.202 --> 02:53:27.004
even though he was warned of the risks

02:53:27.004 --> 02:53:28.972
during the kingdom's sacred season.

02:53:28.972 --> 02:53:32.476
His audacity met a tragic end at Ugbine village,

02:53:32.476 --> 02:53:36.013
where an ambush led by the Benin warriors claimed his life

02:53:36.013 --> 02:53:38.081
and those of most of his party.

02:53:38.081 --> 02:53:40.918
Britain's response was swift and brutal.

02:53:40.918 --> 02:53:44.721
Admiral Sir Harry Rawson, armed with the Maxim guns,

02:53:44.721 --> 02:53:46.390
marshaled his forces.

02:53:46.390 --> 02:53:49.760
The goal was clear, retribution for Phillips

02:53:49.760 --> 02:53:51.562
and the annexation of the kingdom.

02:53:51.562 --> 02:53:54.331
With their assegais and age-old strategies,

02:53:54.331 --> 02:53:56.500
the Benin warriors stood little chance

02:53:56.500 --> 02:53:58.302
against the British onslaught.

02:53:58.302 --> 02:54:02.272
Within weeks, the once majestic Benin City was aflame.

02:54:02.272 --> 02:54:06.510
Its sacred bronzes pillaged and carried off to faraway lands

02:54:06.510 --> 02:54:08.445
as trophies of conquest.

02:54:08.445 --> 02:54:11.215
Benin was annexed into the British empire.

02:54:12.049 --> 02:54:15.185
However, this line drawing sometimes led to conflict

02:54:15.185 --> 02:54:17.221
with other European powers.

02:54:17.221 --> 02:54:19.823
The remote settlement of Fashoda in Sudan

02:54:19.823 --> 02:54:22.326
was clearly claimed by the British.

02:54:22.326 --> 02:54:23.827
However, that didn't stop

02:54:23.827 --> 02:54:26.296
French Captain Jean-Baptiste Marchand

02:54:26.296 --> 02:54:29.766
from placing the French flag at Fashoda when they arrived.

02:54:29.766 --> 02:54:33.103
When British General Sir Herbert Kitchener saw the flag,

02:54:33.103 --> 02:54:34.938
he knew something had to be done

02:54:34.938 --> 02:54:36.807
because of this transgression.

02:54:36.807 --> 02:54:38.876
A tense standoff ensued.

02:54:38.876 --> 02:54:40.677
Both Marchand and Kitchener,

02:54:40.677 --> 02:54:43.180
representing the interests of their nations,

02:54:43.180 --> 02:54:46.783
realized that a single gunshot on this remote riverbank

02:54:46.783 --> 02:54:50.687
could ignite a war between two of the world's great powers,

02:54:50.687 --> 02:54:53.090
yet neither wished for conflict.

02:54:53.090 --> 02:54:55.792
In the sticky heat, the two commanders met.

02:54:55.792 --> 02:54:59.129
Marchand spoke of France's claim and arduous journey,

02:54:59.129 --> 02:55:02.232
while Kitchener underlined Britain's strategic interests

02:55:02.232 --> 02:55:03.100
in the Nile.

02:55:03.100 --> 02:55:05.402
Despite the gravity of the situation,

02:55:05.402 --> 02:55:08.272
both exhibited a certain respect for each other,

02:55:08.272 --> 02:55:10.107
understanding the stakes at hand.

02:55:10.107 --> 02:55:13.477
Back in Europe, news of the Fashoda Incident sent ripples

02:55:13.477 --> 02:55:15.379
through the corridors of power.

02:55:15.379 --> 02:55:17.114
Neither country wanted war,

02:55:17.114 --> 02:55:19.449
especially over a distant outpost.

02:55:19.449 --> 02:55:22.386
Diplomats scrambled, negotiations began,

02:55:22.386 --> 02:55:25.489
and after some time, an agreement was reached,

02:55:25.489 --> 02:55:27.791
France would withdraw from Fashoda,

02:55:27.791 --> 02:55:31.328
marking the end of their eastward ambitions in Africa.

02:55:32.963 --> 02:55:35.632
Meanwhile, in the grasslands of South Africa,

02:55:35.632 --> 02:55:39.803
the gold was found in the territories of the Boers.

02:55:39.803 --> 02:55:42.139
By October 1899,

02:55:42.139 --> 02:55:45.175
these tensions erupted into open conflict.

02:55:45.175 --> 02:55:47.511
The Boers, leveraging their deep understanding

02:55:47.511 --> 02:55:48.845
of the local terrain,

02:55:48.845 --> 02:55:50.847
adopted guerilla tactics.

02:55:50.847 --> 02:55:52.849
They secured early victories,

02:55:52.849 --> 02:55:55.085
besieging key British-held towns

02:55:55.085 --> 02:55:58.422
like Ladysmith, Kimberley, and Mafeking.

02:55:58.422 --> 02:56:01.325
The British, initially underestimating the Boers,

02:56:01.325 --> 02:56:04.561
found themselves on the defensive as the war raged on.

02:56:04.561 --> 02:56:07.130
The Boers, primarily farmers by trade,

02:56:07.130 --> 02:56:09.299
but fierce fighters by necessity,

02:56:09.299 --> 02:56:11.401
were deft in guerilla warfare,

02:56:11.401 --> 02:56:13.370
striking quickly and melting back

02:56:13.370 --> 02:56:15.772
into the vast South African landscape.

02:56:15.772 --> 02:56:19.376
Traditional military strategies failed against such tactics,

02:56:19.376 --> 02:56:21.044
leading British commanders to believe

02:56:21.044 --> 02:56:23.013
that the key to defeating the Boers

02:56:23.013 --> 02:56:26.283
was to target their logistical and moral support.

02:56:26.283 --> 02:56:27.684
In pursuit of victory,

02:56:27.684 --> 02:56:29.519
Field Marshal Lord Roberts

02:56:29.519 --> 02:56:32.022
and later General Lord Kitchener

02:56:32.022 --> 02:56:35.392
sanctioned a policy called Scorched Earth.

02:56:35.392 --> 02:56:39.029
The strategy involved the widespread burning of Boer farms

02:56:39.029 --> 02:56:41.198
and the destruction of their crops.

02:56:41.198 --> 02:56:43.900
The policy didn't stop at burning farms.

02:56:43.900 --> 02:56:45.869
To ensure that the Boer population

02:56:45.869 --> 02:56:47.571
couldn't aid their fighters,

02:56:47.571 --> 02:56:51.041
the British began relocating Boer civilians,

02:56:51.041 --> 02:56:54.177
predominantly women, children, and the elderly,

02:56:54.177 --> 02:56:56.513
to concentration camps.

02:56:56.513 --> 02:56:59.983
These camps were not designed for large-scale habitation

02:56:59.983 --> 02:57:03.887
and soon became notorious for their deplorable conditions.

02:57:03.887 --> 02:57:06.089
Malnutrition, poor sanitation,

02:57:06.089 --> 02:57:08.258
and diseases like typhoid fever

02:57:08.258 --> 02:57:10.560
decimated the camp populations,

02:57:10.560 --> 02:57:13.897
leading to the deaths of tens of thousands.

02:57:13.897 --> 02:57:16.333
Despite its high humanitarian cost,

02:57:16.333 --> 02:57:20.037
the Scorched Earth policy wore down the Boer resistance.

02:57:20.037 --> 02:57:24.007
In May of 1902, after long, hard-fought years

02:57:24.007 --> 02:57:26.810
and amidst a landscape scarred by war,

02:57:26.810 --> 02:57:28.845
the two sides came together.

02:57:28.845 --> 02:57:31.214
The Treaty of Vereeniging was signed

02:57:31.214 --> 02:57:34.751
and the Boer republics became a part of the British Empire.

02:57:34.751 --> 02:57:36.319
(bright music)

02:57:36.319 --> 02:57:39.289
As the years turned the clock to the 20th century,

02:57:39.289 --> 02:57:43.093
the British Empire spanned all across the globe,

02:57:43.093 --> 02:57:44.728
from the dominion of Canada

02:57:44.728 --> 02:57:47.697
to Jamaica and St. Kitts in the Americas,

02:57:47.697 --> 02:57:51.802
to Cape Colony, the Gold Coast, and Sierra Leone in Africa,

02:57:51.802 --> 02:57:55.839
to British India, to Singapore, to Hong Kong in Asia,

02:57:55.839 --> 02:57:59.443
to Australia, New Zealand, and Fiji in Australia.

02:57:59.443 --> 02:58:03.480
Britain embodied the phrase the sun will never set.

02:58:03.480 --> 02:58:06.850
In 1907, the British tried to change their relationship

02:58:06.850 --> 02:58:09.186
with their subjects with some of their colonies

02:58:09.186 --> 02:58:11.221
during the Imperial Conference.

02:58:11.221 --> 02:58:13.523
The colonies of Canada, Australia,

02:58:13.523 --> 02:58:16.526
New Zealand, South Africa, and Newfoundland

02:58:16.526 --> 02:58:20.097
were given unprecedented rights to rule themselves

02:58:20.097 --> 02:58:22.732
while still being under the prowess of the Crown.

02:58:22.732 --> 02:58:26.770
While in Persia, the Anglo-Russian Convention of 1907

02:58:26.770 --> 02:58:29.606
divided Persia into spheres of influence,

02:58:29.606 --> 02:58:31.475
the north under Russian influence

02:58:31.475 --> 02:58:33.777
and the southeast under British influence

02:58:33.777 --> 02:58:36.146
with the central region remaining neutral,

02:58:36.146 --> 02:58:37.581
while those in the Middle East

02:58:37.581 --> 02:58:39.749
were just now starting to be of interest

02:58:39.749 --> 02:58:41.118
to the British Empire.

02:58:41.118 --> 02:58:44.654
In 1908, the Persian city of Masjid-i-Sulaiman,

02:58:44.654 --> 02:58:49.392
1,180 feet below the desert was a large oil reserve

02:58:49.392 --> 02:58:51.928
able to make any empire a fortune.

02:58:51.928 --> 02:58:56.133
In 1909, the Anglo-Persian Oil Company was formed,

02:58:56.133 --> 02:58:57.801
and within 30 minutes,

02:58:57.801 --> 02:59:01.338
all of their initial public offering stocks were sold out.

02:59:01.338 --> 02:59:04.441
The British needed to increase their control in the region.

02:59:04.441 --> 02:59:06.977
Their neighbors of Persia were the Ottomans,

02:59:06.977 --> 02:59:10.347
a fledgling empire trying to retain its former glory,

02:59:10.347 --> 02:59:12.749
but the British knew they could take their lands

02:59:12.749 --> 02:59:14.985
and continue growing their empire.

02:59:14.985 --> 02:59:17.921
That's why they needed a world war.

02:59:17.921 --> 02:59:20.690
(dramatic music)

02:59:22.259 --> 02:59:26.096
Most people will claim that on June 28th, 1914,

02:59:26.096 --> 02:59:29.699
Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary and his wife

02:59:29.699 --> 02:59:33.737
were assassinated in Sarajevo by Gavrilo Princip,

02:59:33.737 --> 02:59:37.274
a Bosnian Serb nationalist started the war.

02:59:37.274 --> 02:59:41.244
However, the war was a battle of worldwide colonization.

02:59:41.244 --> 02:59:42.646
The Triple Entente,

02:59:42.646 --> 02:59:45.115
which featured France, Russia, and Britain,

02:59:45.115 --> 02:59:47.751
faced off against the Triple Alliance,

02:59:47.751 --> 02:59:51.855
which featured Germany, Austria-Hungary, and the Ottomans.

02:59:51.855 --> 02:59:54.291
Germany wanted to expand their empire.

02:59:54.291 --> 02:59:56.760
The British wanted to expand their empire.

02:59:56.760 --> 02:59:59.296
France wanted to expand their empire.

02:59:59.296 --> 03:00:01.464
The Ottomans tried to keep it.

03:00:01.464 --> 03:00:05.602
As the war began, the British Expeditionary Force, BEF,

03:00:05.602 --> 03:00:07.437
was dispatched to the continent

03:00:07.437 --> 03:00:10.440
where they confronted the Germans at the Battle of Mons.

03:00:10.440 --> 03:00:12.342
This initial conflict was marked

03:00:12.342 --> 03:00:14.678
by a robust British defense,

03:00:14.678 --> 03:00:16.313
stalling the German advance,

03:00:16.313 --> 03:00:20.250
and commencing trench warfare's enduring, grim nature.

03:00:20.250 --> 03:00:23.086
The Western Front was a tangle of trenches,

03:00:23.086 --> 03:00:26.556
but the allies sought to make strategic gains elsewhere.

03:00:26.556 --> 03:00:29.926
This led to the initiation of the Gallipoli campaign.

03:00:29.926 --> 03:00:32.796
British, Australian, and New Zealand forces aimed

03:00:32.796 --> 03:00:34.698
to secure the Dardanelles Strait,

03:00:34.698 --> 03:00:37.567
hoping to knock the Ottoman Empire out of the war.

03:00:37.567 --> 03:00:40.971
However, instead of the anticipated swift victory,

03:00:40.971 --> 03:00:43.540
the campaign became a drawn-out ordeal

03:00:43.540 --> 03:00:46.910
with rugged terrains, stiff enemy resistance,

03:00:46.910 --> 03:00:48.712
and immense casualties.

03:00:48.712 --> 03:00:50.513
As the war was in a stalemate,

03:00:50.513 --> 03:00:52.716
the British and French had a secret agreement

03:00:52.716 --> 03:00:55.418
of what to do in the Middle East after the war.

03:00:55.418 --> 03:00:57.420
In this Sykes-Picot Agreement,

03:00:57.420 --> 03:00:59.089
France would gain the territories

03:00:59.089 --> 03:01:01.491
of modern-day Syria and Lebanon

03:01:01.491 --> 03:01:02.993
while the British would get the lands

03:01:02.993 --> 03:01:06.930
of Jordan, southern Iraq, and much of modern-day Israel.

03:01:06.930 --> 03:01:09.933
The Western Front saw another significant endeavor

03:01:09.933 --> 03:01:11.468
to break the stalemate,

03:01:11.468 --> 03:01:13.169
the Battle of the Somme.

03:01:13.169 --> 03:01:16.439
Initiated in July, this battle became one of the war's

03:01:16.439 --> 03:01:18.608
most significant engagements.

03:01:18.608 --> 03:01:21.044
Machine guns and fortified defenses

03:01:21.044 --> 03:01:22.979
thwarted hopes of a breakthrough.

03:01:22.979 --> 03:01:24.914
While some ground was gained,

03:01:24.914 --> 03:01:26.549
it came at a high cost,

03:01:26.549 --> 03:01:28.251
rendering the Somme a symbol

03:01:28.251 --> 03:01:30.987
of the war's futility and devastation.

03:01:30.987 --> 03:01:34.157
The war's deadlock led to repeated offensives,

03:01:34.157 --> 03:01:36.126
including the Battle of Arras.

03:01:36.126 --> 03:01:38.428
While initial gains were promising,

03:01:38.428 --> 03:01:41.464
it eventually became another battle of attrition.

03:01:41.464 --> 03:01:42.465
Later in the year,

03:01:42.465 --> 03:01:44.834
the Battle of Passchendaele became notorious

03:01:44.834 --> 03:01:46.503
for its muddy wasteland,

03:01:46.503 --> 03:01:49.439
making any advance almost impossible

03:01:49.439 --> 03:01:51.808
and leading to immense casualties.

03:01:51.808 --> 03:01:53.410
The war reached a turning point

03:01:53.410 --> 03:01:55.945
when Germany launched its spring offensive,

03:01:55.945 --> 03:01:59.349
a desperate attempt to break through Entente lines.

03:01:59.349 --> 03:02:02.185
Initially, the Germans made significant gains,

03:02:02.185 --> 03:02:03.887
pushing the Entente back.

03:02:03.887 --> 03:02:07.891
However, by summer, resilience, fresh American troops,

03:02:07.891 --> 03:02:10.960
and logistical strains on the Germans set the stage

03:02:10.960 --> 03:02:13.163
for the Hundred Days Offensive.

03:02:13.163 --> 03:02:14.864
This series of allied attacks

03:02:14.864 --> 03:02:17.033
gradually pushed the Germans back,

03:02:17.033 --> 03:02:20.003
eventually leading to the armistice in November,

03:02:20.003 --> 03:02:23.606
silencing the guns and marking the war's conclusion.

03:02:23.606 --> 03:02:26.843
When the Treaty of Versailles was signed in 1919,

03:02:26.843 --> 03:02:28.578
Germany was forced to surrender

03:02:28.578 --> 03:02:31.014
all their colonial territories,

03:02:31.014 --> 03:02:34.884
losing Tanganyika, modern-day Tanzania, to the British,

03:02:34.884 --> 03:02:39.122
Cameroon, and Togoland to a joint French-British coalition.

03:02:39.122 --> 03:02:42.525
In the Pacific, Nauru and the German colonies in New Guinea

03:02:42.525 --> 03:02:44.127
were placed under the joint mandate

03:02:44.127 --> 03:02:45.962
of Britain and Australia,

03:02:45.962 --> 03:02:47.297
while in the Middle East,

03:02:47.297 --> 03:02:50.033
the Ottoman Empire was fully dissolved,

03:02:50.033 --> 03:02:52.736
the Sykes-Picot Agreement was fully realized,

03:02:52.736 --> 03:02:55.271
and the British Empire stood at its peak.

03:02:55.271 --> 03:02:59.109
But yet, little did they know the sun was finally setting.

03:02:59.109 --> 03:03:01.611
The day always turns into night,

03:03:01.611 --> 03:03:04.881
and the end of the British Empire was upon us.

03:03:04.881 --> 03:03:07.717
The end of colonization was imminent.

03:03:09.452 --> 03:03:12.956
When one faces resistance, one must fight back.

03:03:12.956 --> 03:03:14.991
In the aftermath of World War I,

03:03:14.991 --> 03:03:18.661
India grew tired of being ignored by their colonial rulers.

03:03:18.661 --> 03:03:20.797
They wanted to speak out and fight.

03:03:20.797 --> 03:03:24.501
But in 1919, the Imperial Legislative Council in Delhi

03:03:24.501 --> 03:03:26.069
passed the Rowlatt Act,

03:03:26.069 --> 03:03:29.372
which allowed the police to arrest anyone without reason.

03:03:29.372 --> 03:03:31.941
There would be no trials, there would be no rights,

03:03:31.941 --> 03:03:33.710
and the accused wouldn't even know

03:03:33.710 --> 03:03:35.645
the evidence brought against them.

03:03:35.645 --> 03:03:37.380
The implementation was quick.

03:03:37.380 --> 03:03:39.115
Two non-violence leaders,

03:03:39.115 --> 03:03:42.285
Saifuddin Kitchlew and Dr. Satyapal Singh,

03:03:42.285 --> 03:03:44.287
were arrested shortly after that.

03:03:44.287 --> 03:03:46.489
But instead of fighting with their swords,

03:03:46.489 --> 03:03:48.525
they fought with their actions.

03:03:48.525 --> 03:03:50.960
Under the guidance of Mahatma Gandhi,

03:03:50.960 --> 03:03:54.230
a new philosophy in resisting oppression was created

03:03:54.230 --> 03:03:56.099
called satyagraha,

03:03:56.099 --> 03:04:00.103
a Sanskrit word that means polite insistence on truth.

03:04:00.103 --> 03:04:02.839
Instead of getting angry and causing a war,

03:04:02.839 --> 03:04:05.708
politely resisting is the best way to fight.

03:04:05.708 --> 03:04:08.645
When the arrest of Kitchlew and Singh was made public,

03:04:08.645 --> 03:04:12.582
thousands of Indians flocked to Jallianwala Bagh in Punjab

03:04:12.582 --> 03:04:15.185
to protest peacefully against the Rowlett Act

03:04:15.185 --> 03:04:18.321
and the release of the activists wrongly in jail.

03:04:18.321 --> 03:04:22.125
Instead, Brigadier General Reginald Edward Harry Dyer

03:04:22.125 --> 03:04:24.928
surrounded the people with 50 riflemen.

03:04:24.928 --> 03:04:28.431
His men blocked the exit and then ordered them to shoot.

03:04:28.431 --> 03:04:30.567
As the protestors tried to flee,

03:04:30.567 --> 03:04:33.002
Dyer and his rifleman continued to fire

03:04:33.002 --> 03:04:35.104
until they ran out of ammunition

03:04:35.104 --> 03:04:38.308
and 1,500 people lay dead.

03:04:38.308 --> 03:04:42.545
This led to the question, is nonviolence really the answer?

03:04:43.413 --> 03:04:46.583
Ireland would test out their theory in their way.

03:04:46.583 --> 03:04:50.186
In the 1918 election, Irish voters had a choice.

03:04:50.186 --> 03:04:53.022
Do they wanna follow the radical nationalist party

03:04:53.022 --> 03:04:54.557
called the Sinn Fein

03:04:54.557 --> 03:04:57.494
or do they still wanna be in the British Empire?

03:04:57.494 --> 03:05:01.731
The unequivocal demand by Sinn Fein's leader Eamon de Valera

03:05:01.731 --> 03:05:04.701
was for a united and independent Ireland.

03:05:04.701 --> 03:05:08.204
They won 73 of the 105 Irish seats

03:05:08.204 --> 03:05:10.373
in the British Parliament in the election.

03:05:10.373 --> 03:05:14.511
By January 1919, they declared themselves independent

03:05:14.511 --> 03:05:16.546
and recreated their parliament.

03:05:16.546 --> 03:05:17.780
With their parliament,

03:05:17.780 --> 03:05:21.317
they created the Irish Republican Army, IRA,

03:05:21.317 --> 03:05:23.520
to resist British rule in Ireland

03:05:23.520 --> 03:05:25.855
under the rule of Michael Collins.

03:05:25.855 --> 03:05:28.091
In response, the British sent soldiers

03:05:28.091 --> 03:05:29.926
nicknamed the Black and Tans

03:05:29.926 --> 03:05:32.562
to fight and quell the Irish resistance.

03:05:32.562 --> 03:05:35.598
The first battle struck Sologheadbeg, Tipperary.

03:05:35.598 --> 03:05:39.602
On a crisp January, two unsuspecting Black and Tans fell

03:05:39.602 --> 03:05:41.571
to an IRA ambush.

03:05:41.571 --> 03:05:43.473
This marked the first blood of a war

03:05:43.473 --> 03:05:46.109
that would rage on for two years.

03:05:46.109 --> 03:05:50.179
In November 1920, the event was dubbed Bloody Sunday.

03:05:50.179 --> 03:05:52.282
It would change the face of the war.

03:05:52.282 --> 03:05:54.317
In the early hours, the IRA,

03:05:54.317 --> 03:05:56.686
acting on Michael Collins' intelligence,

03:05:56.686 --> 03:05:59.355
targeted British agents across Dublin,

03:05:59.355 --> 03:06:02.025
leaving 14 British officers dead.

03:06:02.025 --> 03:06:04.127
In retaliation, later that day,

03:06:04.127 --> 03:06:07.096
the Black and Tans stormed into Dublin's Croke Park

03:06:07.096 --> 03:06:08.798
during a football match,

03:06:08.798 --> 03:06:11.768
killing 14 civilians in revenge.

03:06:11.768 --> 03:06:15.204
Angry, Tom Barry and his 36 men from the IRA

03:06:15.204 --> 03:06:18.207
took positions along the Macroom-Dunmanway road

03:06:18.207 --> 03:06:19.242
near Kilmichael.

03:06:19.242 --> 03:06:22.545
They anticipated the movement of the Black and Tans.

03:06:22.545 --> 03:06:25.315
Barry's strategy was simple but daring.

03:06:25.315 --> 03:06:28.685
Allow the first lorry of auxiliaries to pass by,

03:06:28.685 --> 03:06:31.354
targeting the second to create a buffer,

03:06:31.354 --> 03:06:34.991
preventing any immediate retreat or forward charge.

03:06:34.991 --> 03:06:38.561
Camouflaged by the roadside, the men waited in tension.

03:06:38.561 --> 03:06:40.330
As the first lorry passed,

03:06:40.330 --> 03:06:42.532
it all happened in a flash.

03:06:42.532 --> 03:06:45.535
The men launched a ferocious up-close attack

03:06:45.535 --> 03:06:46.869
on the second vehicle,

03:06:46.869 --> 03:06:49.072
catching the auxiliaries off guard.

03:06:49.072 --> 03:06:52.208
Fighting was intense and hand-to-hand combat ensued.

03:06:52.208 --> 03:06:55.612
The first lorry soon realized the situation and returned,

03:06:55.612 --> 03:06:58.581
only to be met by a relentless barrage.

03:06:58.581 --> 03:07:02.518
When smoke cleared, 17 auxiliaries laid dead,

03:07:02.518 --> 03:07:05.254
the IRA had three casualties.

03:07:05.254 --> 03:07:07.890
But British forces, humiliated and angered

03:07:07.890 --> 03:07:11.494
by the audacity of the ambush and the scale of the loss,

03:07:11.494 --> 03:07:13.029
were quick to retaliate.

03:07:13.029 --> 03:07:15.264
Barely two weeks after Kilmichael,

03:07:15.264 --> 03:07:17.300
they attacked the city of Cork.

03:07:17.300 --> 03:07:19.268
They began by looting businesses

03:07:19.268 --> 03:07:21.270
and then escalating to arson.

03:07:21.270 --> 03:07:24.040
Residents awoke to an apocalyptic site.

03:07:24.040 --> 03:07:27.644
The once thriving heart of Cork smoldered in ruins,

03:07:27.644 --> 03:07:30.947
the river Lee reflecting the embers of destruction.

03:07:30.947 --> 03:07:33.282
The sky was an eerie hue of orange

03:07:33.282 --> 03:07:36.152
with dark plumes of smoke blotting the dawn.

03:07:36.152 --> 03:07:40.523
However, in 1921, Eamon de Valera negotiated a treaty

03:07:40.523 --> 03:07:41.591
with the British.

03:07:41.591 --> 03:07:45.628
Like the Confederation Catholics of Ireland in 1642,

03:07:45.628 --> 03:07:46.863
they created a parliament

03:07:46.863 --> 03:07:49.799
that swore an oath of allegiance to the British monarch.

03:07:49.799 --> 03:07:53.403
However, they would govern themselves as independent.

03:07:53.403 --> 03:07:55.805
Not all of Ireland agreed with the treaty.

03:07:55.805 --> 03:07:58.041
These six northern Anglican counties

03:07:58.041 --> 03:08:00.910
decided to remain part of the British Empire,

03:08:00.910 --> 03:08:02.812
so they formed their own country

03:08:02.812 --> 03:08:05.548
and were still represented in the British Parliament.

03:08:05.548 --> 03:08:07.817
Ireland was now separated.

03:08:07.817 --> 03:08:09.419
(dramatic music)

03:08:09.419 --> 03:08:10.953
While back in India,

03:08:10.953 --> 03:08:13.790
the British Raj was struggling to hold power.

03:08:13.790 --> 03:08:16.926
To make money, the Raj imposed a salt tax,

03:08:16.926 --> 03:08:20.229
making it illegal for Indians to produce or sell salt

03:08:20.229 --> 03:08:22.165
without a colonial license.

03:08:22.165 --> 03:08:25.568
This simple oppressive act was a stark reminder

03:08:25.568 --> 03:08:28.171
of a colonial rule that had its grasp

03:08:28.171 --> 03:08:31.741
over the most fundamental aspects of Indian life.

03:08:31.741 --> 03:08:34.310
On the morning of March 12th, 1930,

03:08:34.310 --> 03:08:37.413
Mahatma Gandhi and 78 ashram residents

03:08:37.413 --> 03:08:40.550
went on a protest march 240 miles

03:08:40.550 --> 03:08:42.552
to the coastal town of Dandi.

03:08:42.552 --> 03:08:45.154
On the march, they practiced satyagraha,

03:08:45.154 --> 03:08:47.790
showing respect and refusal to be violent

03:08:47.790 --> 03:08:49.492
against their oppressors.

03:08:49.492 --> 03:08:52.161
Gandhi and his group journeyed through dusty roads

03:08:52.161 --> 03:08:54.163
and met with swelling crowds.

03:08:54.163 --> 03:08:55.765
In every village and town,

03:08:55.765 --> 03:08:58.735
people gathered to catch a glimpse, hear him speak,

03:08:58.735 --> 03:09:01.137
and join in this act of defiance.

03:09:01.137 --> 03:09:05.174
The group grew, their footsteps echoing a rhythm of change,

03:09:05.174 --> 03:09:06.809
their path lined with flowers

03:09:06.809 --> 03:09:09.011
and accompanied by songs of freedom.

03:09:09.011 --> 03:09:11.013
With his walking stick in hand,

03:09:11.013 --> 03:09:13.916
Gandhi spoke fervently about non-violence

03:09:13.916 --> 03:09:16.319
and the injustice of the salt tax.

03:09:16.319 --> 03:09:18.154
He painted a vision of an India

03:09:18.154 --> 03:09:21.023
free from the shackles of colonial rule,

03:09:21.023 --> 03:09:24.560
urging his followers to embrace civil disobedience,

03:09:24.560 --> 03:09:26.863
but always to remain peaceful.

03:09:26.863 --> 03:09:30.333
After 24 days, the sea came into view.

03:09:30.333 --> 03:09:33.202
The salty breeze hinted at their journey's end.

03:09:33.202 --> 03:09:35.838
On April 6th, as the first rays of dawn

03:09:35.838 --> 03:09:37.573
touched Dandi shores,

03:09:37.573 --> 03:09:41.110
Gandhi bent down, scooped up a handful of mud and salt,

03:09:41.110 --> 03:09:45.181
and declared, "With this, I am shaking the foundations

03:09:45.181 --> 03:09:46.849
of the British Empire."

03:09:46.849 --> 03:09:49.952
Mass civil disobedience spread throughout India

03:09:49.952 --> 03:09:51.921
as millions broke the salt laws

03:09:51.921 --> 03:09:54.557
by making or burying illegal salt.

03:09:54.557 --> 03:09:58.161
Salt was sold illegally all over the coast of India.

03:09:58.161 --> 03:09:59.362
Not ready to give up,

03:09:59.362 --> 03:10:02.665
the British government arrested over 60,000 people

03:10:02.665 --> 03:10:04.200
by the end of the month.

03:10:04.200 --> 03:10:06.769
What had begun as a salt satyagraha

03:10:06.769 --> 03:10:10.039
quickly grew into a mass satyagraha.

03:10:10.039 --> 03:10:12.708
British clothes and goods were boycotted,

03:10:12.708 --> 03:10:15.077
unpopular forest laws were defied

03:10:15.077 --> 03:10:18.281
in the Bombay, Mysore, and Central Provinces.

03:10:18.281 --> 03:10:21.050
Gujarati peasants refused to pay tax,

03:10:21.050 --> 03:10:23.152
fearing losing their crops and land.

03:10:23.152 --> 03:10:25.321
In Midnapore, Bengalis took part

03:10:25.321 --> 03:10:27.924
by refusing to pay the chowkidar tax.

03:10:27.924 --> 03:10:30.459
The British responded with more laws,

03:10:30.459 --> 03:10:32.929
including censorship of correspondence

03:10:32.929 --> 03:10:34.263
and declaring the Congress

03:10:34.263 --> 03:10:37.200
and its associate organizations illegal.

03:10:37.200 --> 03:10:38.901
None of those measures slowed

03:10:38.901 --> 03:10:40.903
the civil disobedience movement.

03:10:40.903 --> 03:10:43.973
The people were willing to fight for their actions,

03:10:43.973 --> 03:10:46.843
and five years later, in 1935,

03:10:46.843 --> 03:10:49.078
the efforts were starting to pay off.

03:10:49.078 --> 03:10:51.514
The Government of India Act allowed India

03:10:51.514 --> 03:10:53.115
to rule itself partially.

03:10:53.115 --> 03:10:56.385
For the first time since the establishment of the Raj,

03:10:56.385 --> 03:10:59.722
an Indian representative was allowed to have power.

03:10:59.722 --> 03:11:02.992
In 1937, they had their first election.

03:11:02.992 --> 03:11:05.828
However, India would be placed on the back burner

03:11:05.828 --> 03:11:10.199
as Germany, under Adolf Hitler, was invading Poland.

03:11:10.199 --> 03:11:13.636
(dramatic music)

03:11:13.636 --> 03:11:16.706
Britain, upholding its guarantee to the Polish state,

03:11:16.706 --> 03:11:17.974
declared war.

03:11:17.974 --> 03:11:20.343
The echoes of those war declarations

03:11:20.343 --> 03:11:23.479
paired with Prime Minister Neville Chamberlain's grim voice

03:11:23.479 --> 03:11:24.447
over the radio

03:11:24.447 --> 03:11:26.682
permeated British households.

03:11:26.682 --> 03:11:29.619
But for most, this war was initially distant

03:11:29.619 --> 03:11:32.121
with no significant ground conflicts,

03:11:32.121 --> 03:11:34.790
leading many to call it the phony war.

03:11:34.790 --> 03:11:39.362
However, the illusion of a remote war was shattered in 1940.

03:11:39.362 --> 03:11:42.465
As the German war machine blitzed through Europe,

03:11:42.465 --> 03:11:44.700
British forces were quickly pushed back

03:11:44.700 --> 03:11:46.435
to the beaches of Dunkirk.

03:11:46.435 --> 03:11:48.604
The situation seemed dire.

03:11:48.604 --> 03:11:50.506
Yet across the English channel,

03:11:50.506 --> 03:11:51.974
an armada of vessels

03:11:51.974 --> 03:11:54.577
ranging from navy ships to fishing boats

03:11:54.577 --> 03:11:56.812
sailed to rescue stranded soldiers

03:11:56.812 --> 03:12:00.082
in what became known as Operation Dynamo.

03:12:00.082 --> 03:12:05.054
Families across Britain rejoiced as 338,000 troops returned,

03:12:05.454 --> 03:12:07.690
but the triumph was short-lived.

03:12:07.690 --> 03:12:08.891
The Battle of Britain saw

03:12:08.891 --> 03:12:11.027
the skies above London and other cities

03:12:11.027 --> 03:12:13.129
transformed into war zones.

03:12:13.129 --> 03:12:16.365
Night after night, families huddled in underground stations

03:12:16.365 --> 03:12:19.402
as the Luftwaffe dropped their deadly payloads.

03:12:19.402 --> 03:12:23.039
The spirit of defiance was captured in Churchill's voice,

03:12:23.039 --> 03:12:26.175
declaring that Britain would never surrender.

03:12:26.175 --> 03:12:28.077
1941 brought hope.

03:12:28.077 --> 03:12:29.645
Though not yet in the war,

03:12:29.645 --> 03:12:33.049
America began supporting Britain with vital supplies

03:12:33.049 --> 03:12:35.084
under the Lease-Lend agreement.

03:12:35.084 --> 03:12:38.321
By December, following the attack on Pearl Harbor,

03:12:38.321 --> 03:12:42.158
the US joined the allies, bolstering British morale.

03:12:42.158 --> 03:12:45.628
The war's tides began turning in 1942.

03:12:45.628 --> 03:12:48.698
General Montgomery's troops faced Rommel's forces

03:12:48.698 --> 03:12:51.000
in the vast deserts of north Africa.

03:12:51.000 --> 03:12:53.102
The pivotal battle of El Alamein

03:12:53.102 --> 03:12:55.638
led to a sweeping allied victory,

03:12:55.638 --> 03:12:57.173
but the joy was bittersweet

03:12:57.173 --> 03:12:59.241
as news from the east arrived.

03:12:59.241 --> 03:13:02.044
Singapore had fallen to the Japanese.

03:13:02.044 --> 03:13:03.412
In the subsequent years,

03:13:03.412 --> 03:13:07.083
Britain participated in a series of crucial operations,

03:13:07.083 --> 03:13:08.951
from the hot sands of Sicily

03:13:08.951 --> 03:13:11.721
to the snowy landscapes of the Netherlands.

03:13:11.721 --> 03:13:16.692
The pivotal moment came in 1944 with the D-Day landings.

03:13:16.726 --> 03:13:18.928
British forces, alongside their American

03:13:18.928 --> 03:13:20.363
and Canadian allies,

03:13:20.363 --> 03:13:22.398
stormed the beaches of Normandy,

03:13:22.398 --> 03:13:26.002
initiating the beginning of the end for Hitler's Europe.

03:13:26.002 --> 03:13:30.706
Yet even as victory in Europe was celebrated in May 1945

03:13:30.706 --> 03:13:33.743
with jubilant crowds flooding London streets,

03:13:33.743 --> 03:13:35.711
the war raged on in the east.

03:13:35.711 --> 03:13:37.246
It wasn't until August

03:13:37.246 --> 03:13:40.149
after the devastating atomic bombs were dropped

03:13:40.149 --> 03:13:43.686
on Hiroshima and Nagasaki that the war ended.

03:13:43.686 --> 03:13:45.187
With the fall of Hitler,

03:13:45.187 --> 03:13:48.824
the interest in large colonial empires was done.

03:13:48.824 --> 03:13:51.227
Even though Great Britain may have won the war,

03:13:51.227 --> 03:13:53.996
it was the final bullet in the empire.

03:13:53.996 --> 03:13:58.467
Their former colony, America, who revolted in 1776,

03:13:58.467 --> 03:14:02.671
would become the next great empire on a colonial stage.

03:14:04.340 --> 03:14:06.742
As the British empire was winding down,

03:14:06.742 --> 03:14:09.478
in the heart of Delhi, Sir Louis Mountbatten,

03:14:09.478 --> 03:14:12.114
the last British Viceroy of India,

03:14:12.114 --> 03:14:14.216
gazed at the vast subcontinent

03:14:14.216 --> 03:14:16.852
on the cusp of monumental change.

03:14:16.852 --> 03:14:19.221
Soon, the tricolor flag of India

03:14:19.221 --> 03:14:22.358
and the green crescent of Pakistan would fly high,

03:14:22.358 --> 03:14:25.094
signaling the end of British rule in India.

03:14:25.094 --> 03:14:28.230
Years passed, and as the 1950s dawned,

03:14:28.230 --> 03:14:30.399
optimism and determination washed over

03:14:30.399 --> 03:14:31.767
the African continent.

03:14:31.767 --> 03:14:35.037
In the Gold Coast, Kwame Nkrumah passionately spoke

03:14:35.037 --> 03:14:36.872
of self-rule and destiny.

03:14:36.872 --> 03:14:41.710
By 1957, jubilant Ghanians danced in the streets of Accra,

03:14:41.710 --> 03:14:44.847
celebrating the birth of an independent Ghana.

03:14:44.847 --> 03:14:48.350
Over in Malaya, amidst the dense rainforests,

03:14:48.350 --> 03:14:51.320
Tunku Abdul Rahman, a prince and statesman,

03:14:51.320 --> 03:14:52.655
rallied his people.

03:14:52.655 --> 03:14:55.157
They sang songs that dreamt of unity,

03:14:55.157 --> 03:14:58.928
and in 1957, Malaya stood independent,

03:14:58.928 --> 03:15:02.198
later forming a larger union known as Malaysia.

03:15:02.198 --> 03:15:04.900
But freedom's journey wasn't without its trials.

03:15:04.900 --> 03:15:08.204
In Cyprus, tension brewed between the Greeks and Turks,

03:15:08.204 --> 03:15:11.006
often pulling British soldiers into the fray.

03:15:11.006 --> 03:15:13.609
The island's beauty was often overshadowed

03:15:13.609 --> 03:15:15.544
by the sporadic bursts of violence

03:15:15.544 --> 03:15:17.046
that threatened its peace.

03:15:17.046 --> 03:15:19.682
As the sun set in the 1960s,

03:15:19.682 --> 03:15:21.984
the African continent transformed.

03:15:21.984 --> 03:15:24.620
Flags bearing new symbols and colors rose

03:15:24.620 --> 03:15:28.023
in Nigeria, Uganda, Kenya, and beyond.

03:15:28.023 --> 03:15:30.259
African leaders, educated at home

03:15:30.259 --> 03:15:32.328
and in the very heart of the empire,

03:15:32.328 --> 03:15:35.197
led their nations with a blend of traditional wisdom

03:15:35.197 --> 03:15:36.932
and modern insights.

03:15:36.932 --> 03:15:39.135
The Caribbeans wasn't left behind.

03:15:39.135 --> 03:15:41.637
The rhythmic beats of reggae in Jamaica

03:15:41.637 --> 03:15:43.973
echoed the nation's newfound freedom,

03:15:43.973 --> 03:15:45.875
while in Trinidad and Tobago,

03:15:45.875 --> 03:15:49.478
the fusion of cultures heralded the birth of a nation.

03:15:49.478 --> 03:15:52.781
By the 1980s, far from the African savannas

03:15:52.781 --> 03:15:54.316
and Caribbean beaches,

03:15:54.316 --> 03:15:57.153
the British grappled with a different challenge.

03:15:57.153 --> 03:16:00.022
In Zimbabwe, then Southern Rhodesia,

03:16:00.022 --> 03:16:02.892
Robert Mugabe and his guerillas waged a war

03:16:02.892 --> 03:16:04.460
against British rule.

03:16:04.460 --> 03:16:06.896
The result was a free Zimbabwe,

03:16:06.896 --> 03:16:10.065
albeit with scars that would take time to heal.

03:16:10.065 --> 03:16:14.136
But perhaps the most poignant moment came in 1997

03:16:14.136 --> 03:16:16.972
in the bustling city of Hong Kong.

03:16:16.972 --> 03:16:19.208
The Union Jack was lowered

03:16:19.208 --> 03:16:22.344
and the red star of China took its place.

03:16:22.344 --> 03:16:24.780
Watching alongside the city's leaders,

03:16:24.780 --> 03:16:28.417
Prince Charles represented an empire bidding farewell

03:16:28.417 --> 03:16:31.754
to its last significant outpost.

03:16:31.754 --> 03:16:35.024
As the sun finally sets on the British Empire,

03:16:35.024 --> 03:16:37.426
the world has forever changed.

03:16:37.426 --> 03:16:39.895
From the land stolen from the natives,

03:16:39.895 --> 03:16:42.031
the lines drawn in Africa,

03:16:42.031 --> 03:16:45.501
to the stolen artifacts held in the British museums,

03:16:45.501 --> 03:16:48.304
the effects of colonization could be still felt

03:16:48.304 --> 03:16:49.672
around the world.

03:16:49.672 --> 03:16:53.042
As the darkness of the night covers the London sky,

03:16:53.042 --> 03:16:55.978
who knows what'll be in store for the United Kingdom.

03:16:55.978 --> 03:16:59.148
Their history is still being written.

